  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bloody nipple discharge? Think papilloma, but rule out the big C!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, \"Red.\" Intraductal papillomas are benign breast lesions that commonly present with bloody or serosanguinous nipple discharge due to their friable nature and rich vascularity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraductal papillomas are small, benign, wart-like growths that develop within the milk ducts of the breast. These lesions are typically friable and have a delicate vascular supply, making them prone to microtrauma and bleeding into the ductal system. This bleeding manifests as spontaneous, unilateral, and often bloody or serosanguinous (red or pinkish) nipple discharge, which is a classic clinical presentation requiring thorough investigation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Green Creamy: This type of discharge is typically associated with benign conditions such as duct ectasia or fibrocystic changes, which involve inflammation and dilation of the ducts, leading to stagnant secretions rather than bleeding.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Discharge Color | Common Causes | Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Red/Bloody | Intraductal Papilloma, Ductal Carcinoma In Situ (DCIS), Invasive Ductal Carcinoma (IDC) | Requires thorough investigation for malignancy |\n| Serous/Clear | Fibrocystic changes, Oral Contraceptives, Intraductal Papilloma (less common) | Can be benign, but still warrants evaluation |\n| Green/Brown/Creamy | Duct Ectasia, Fibrocystic Changes, Periductal Mastitis | Usually benign, related to stagnant secretions or inflammation |\n| Milky (Galactorrhea) | Hyperprolactinemia, Medications (e.g., antipsychotics), Hypothyroidism | Endocrine evaluation needed |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Red nipple discharge = papilloma or cancer until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, mammography may show calcifications or a mass, while ultrasound can identify intraductal masses or duct dilation. Ductography (galactography) is often crucial for visualizing the intraductal lesion and its extent. Intraoperatively, during microdochectomy, the affected duct is identified (often with methylene blue), and the small, friable papilloma is excised from within the duct.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBS) Consensus Guideline on the Management of Nipple Discharge (e.g., 2016). Recommends evaluation of pathologic nipple discharge (spontaneous, unilateral, persistent, from a single duct, or bloody/serous) with imaging (mammogram, ultrasound) and potentially ductography or MRI, followed by surgical excision for definitive diagnosis and treatment if a lesion is identified.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Red | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Green Creamy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
