  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Phyllodes: Wide excision, no excuses!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nWide tumor excision (WLE) is the correct treatment for a 4 cm phyllodes tumor. This approach is necessary because phyllodes tumors, even benign ones, have a significant risk of local recurrence if not adequately excised with clear margins.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhyllodes tumors are fibroepithelial tumors of the breast that can be benign, borderline, or malignant. Regardless of their histological classification, the primary treatment is surgical excision with clear margins, typically at least 1 cm, to minimize the risk of local recurrence. Unlike fibroadenomas, phyllodes tumors have a propensity for rapid growth and local recurrence, making simple enucleation or narrow excision inadequate. The goal of WLE is to achieve tumor-free margins while preserving as much breast tissue as possible.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Mastectomy): Incorrect. Mastectomy is generally considered overly aggressive for a 4 cm phyllodes tumor unless wide local excision cannot achieve clear margins, the tumor is exceptionally large, or there are multiple recurrences. \nOption C (Follow up): Incorrect. Phyllodes tumors require definitive surgical excision due to their potential for local recurrence and, in some cases, malignant transformation. Observation or follow-up alone is not an appropriate management strategy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Phyllodes Tumor | Fibroadenoma | Invasive Ductal Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Nature | Fibroepithelial, potential for local recurrence | Benign, common | Malignant, metastatic potential |\n| Treatment | Wide local excision with clear margins | Observation or excision (if symptomatic/large) | Lumpectomy + radiation or Mastectomy + sentinel node biopsy |\n| Recurrence | Local recurrence if margins positive | Rare | Local/distant recurrence |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Phyllodes tumors demand wide excision to prevent local recurrence.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, phyllodes tumors often appear as well-circumscribed, lobulated masses with heterogeneous echotexture and sometimes cystic spaces. Intraoperatively, they are typically firm, well-demarcated, and may exhibit a characteristic 'leaf-like' pattern on cut section, which gives them their name.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (e.g., Version 1.2024) recommend surgical excision with clear margins for phyllodes tumors, emphasizing the importance of achieving negative margins to reduce local recurrence rates.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Wide tumor excision (WLE) | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Follow up | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
