  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When TSH is low, scan the nodule, don't just poke it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The correct answer is a Radioactive iodine scan because in a patient with a thyroid nodule and biochemical hyperthyroidism (low TSH, high T4), the primary investigation is to determine if the nodule is hyperfunctioning (\"hot\") or non-functioning (\"cold\").\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA radioactive iodine scan (RAI scan) utilizes the thyroid gland's ability to uptake iodine. A \"hot\" nodule will concentrate the radioactive iodine more than the surrounding normal thyroid tissue, appearing as an area of increased uptake on the scan. Conversely, a \"cold\" nodule will show decreased or no uptake. This distinction is critical because hyperfunctioning \"hot\" nodules are almost universally benign and are the cause of the hyperthyroidism, while \"cold\" nodules have a higher risk of malignancy and would warrant further investigation like FNA.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Hemithyroidectomy) (Incorrect): Hemithyroidectomy is a surgical treatment, not an initial diagnostic investigation. It would be considered after a definitive diagnosis, for instance, if the nodule is confirmed to be hot and symptomatic, or if it's cold and suspicious for malignancy.\nOption C (FNA) (Incorrect): Fine needle aspiration (FNA) is primarily used to assess the cytology of a nodule for malignancy risk. While crucial for cold nodules, it is generally not the first step in a hyperthyroid patient with a nodule. A radioactive iodine scan should precede FNA to determine if the nodule is hot (low malignancy risk) or cold (higher malignancy risk, warranting FNA).\nOption D (Follow up) (Incorrect): Simply following up is inappropriate given the presence of a new thyroid nodule and clear biochemical evidence of hyperthyroidism (low TSH, high T4). This situation requires prompt and specific investigation to determine the cause and guide management.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hot Nodule (Hyperfunctioning) | Cold Nodule (Non-functioning) |\n|---|---|---|\n| TSH Level | Low (suppressed) | Normal to High |\n| RAI Scan Appearance | Increased uptake | Decreased or no uptake |\n| Malignancy Risk | Very low (<1%) | Higher (5-15%) |\n| Initial Investigation | RAI Scan | FNA (after US) |\n| Management | RAI ablation, surgery, anti-thyroid meds | FNA, surgery if malignant/suspicious |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hyperthyroid nodule + low TSH = RAI scan first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a radioactive iodine scan, a \"hot\" nodule will appear as a distinct area of increased radiotracer uptake, often suppressing uptake in the rest of the thyroid gland due to TSH suppression. The surrounding normal thyroid tissue may show reduced or absent uptake.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (e.g., 2015 or subsequent updates). These guidelines recommend a thyroid scintigraphy (radioactive iodine scan) for patients with a thyroid nodule and suppressed TSH to determine if the nodule is hyperfunctioning.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Radioactive iodine scan | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Hemithyroidectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | FNA | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Follow up | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
