  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Vomit blood, no pain, stable? Mallory Weiss is the game!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Mallory Weiss tear. This diagnosis is strongly suggested by the sudden onset of bloody vomiting following a likely emetic event, coupled with the patient's stable condition and absence of abdominal or sternal tenderness.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA Mallory Weiss tear is a longitudinal mucosal laceration at the gastroesophageal junction, typically caused by a sudden increase in intra-abdominal pressure from forceful vomiting or retching. The tear extends through the mucosa and submucosa but usually not through the muscularis, leading to self-limited bleeding. The absence of tenderness further supports a mucosal injury rather than a transmural perforation or deep ulceration.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Peptic ulcers often present with epigastric pain and hematemesis, but the sudden onset after vomiting and lack of tenderness make Mallory Weiss more specific in this scenario.\nOption C (Incorrect): Esophageal varices typically cause massive, painless hematemesis in patients with portal hypertension and liver disease, which is not indicated here. The \"two episodes\" and stability also make varices less likely than a self-limiting Mallory Weiss tear.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Mallory Weiss Tear | Peptic Ulcer | Esophageal Varices |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Cause** | Forceful vomiting/retching | H. pylori, NSAIDs | Portal hypertension |\n| **Presentation** | Sudden hematemesis, often post-emesis | Epigastric pain, hematemesis/melena | Massive, painless hematemesis |\n| **Tenderness** | Usually absent | Often epigastric | Absent |\n| **Stability** | Often stable, self-limiting | Variable, can be unstable | Often unstable, high mortality |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sudden hematemesis after vomiting, think Mallory Weiss tear.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would reveal a linear, non-circumferential mucosal tear, typically located at the gastroesophageal junction, often with active or recent bleeding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Upper Gastrointestinal and Ulcer Bleeding (2021) recommends endoscopy for diagnosis and management of upper GI bleeding, including Mallory Weiss tears.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Peptic ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mallory Weiss tear | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Varicose veins | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
