  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Antrum out, acid down, ulcer gone. Precision matters!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Antrectomy. For multiple antral ulcers unresponsive to PPI therapy, especially with melena, surgical intervention is indicated. Antrectomy specifically targets the diseased area, removing the ulcerated antrum and the primary source of gastrin production.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAntrectomy is the most accurate management because it directly addresses the pathology. The antrum is the primary site of gastrin production, and its removal can reduce acid secretion, which is crucial for refractory ulcers. This procedure removes the ulcer-bearing segment while preserving more gastric tissue than a total gastrectomy, offering a balance between effective treatment and minimizing post-gastrectomy syndromes. It's particularly relevant if underlying conditions like Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome are considered, although further workup would be needed.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Partial gastrectomy) (Incorrect): While antrectomy is a type of partial gastrectomy, 'partial gastrectomy' is a broad term. Given the specific location of 'multiple ulcers in the antrum,' antrectomy is the most precise and appropriate surgical option, making it a more accurate answer than the general term.\nOption C (Total gastrectomy) (Incorrect): Total gastrectomy is an overly aggressive procedure for multiple antral ulcers. It is reserved for extensive gastric malignancy, widespread intractable bleeding, or perforation not amenable to lesser resections, and would lead to significant nutritional and quality of life issues.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Indication | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Antrectomy** | Refractory antral ulcers, gastrinoma, severe H. pylori complications | Removes gastrin-producing antrum, preserves fundus/body |\n| **Partial Gastrectomy** | Gastric cancer, large benign ulcers, severe bleeding | Resection of a portion of the stomach, can include antrectomy |\n| **Total Gastrectomy** | Extensive gastric cancer, diffuse polyposis, intractable bleeding/perforation | Complete removal of the stomach, requires esophagojejunostomy |\n| **Vagotomy** | Historically for duodenal ulcers, reduces acid secretion | Denervation of acid-secreting parietal cells, often combined with drainage procedure |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Refractory antral ulcers often require antrectomy to remove the source of pathology and gastrin.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would show multiple, often deep or atypical, ulcers confined to the gastric antrum, potentially with signs of recent bleeding (e.g., adherent clot, visible vessel). Intraoperatively, the antrum would be resected, and reconstruction typically involves a Billroth I or Billroth II anastomosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) 2017 Clinical Guideline: Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease. It recommends surgical intervention for refractory ulcers, complications, or when malignancy cannot be excluded, with the specific procedure tailored to the location and extent of disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Antrectomy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Partial gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Total gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
