  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't cut a GIST that's less than two, just watch it do!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is observation because GISTs less than 2cm, especially if asymptomatic and incidentally found, have a very low malignant potential. Current guidelines recommend conservative management with surveillance for these small lesions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastrointestinal stromal tumors (GISTs) originate from interstitial cells of Cajal and are the most common mesenchymal tumors of the GI tract. Their malignant potential is primarily determined by size and mitotic index. For very small gastric GISTs (<2cm), the risk of progression or metastasis is exceedingly low, often making the risks of surgical intervention outweigh the benefits. Therefore, a watchful waiting approach with endoscopic or imaging surveillance is the standard of care, avoiding unnecessary morbidity associated with gastrectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Total gastrectomy is an overly aggressive procedure for a small, low-risk GIST and carries significant morbidity. It is reserved for very large, multifocal, or high-risk tumors.\nOption B (Incorrect): Partial gastrectomy, while less extensive than total, is still an unnecessary surgical intervention for a GIST <2cm. The current guidelines favor observation for such small lesions.\nOption D (Incorrect): PPIs (proton pump inhibitors) are medications used to reduce stomach acid production and are completely irrelevant for the management of a GIST tumor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| GIST Size | Management |\n|---|---|\n| < 2 cm (asymptomatic, gastric) | Observation/Surveillance |\n| 2-5 cm | Endoscopic or Laparoscopic Resection |\n| > 5 cm | Surgical Resection (Open/Laparoscopic) |\n| Symptomatic (any size) | Surgical Resection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Small GISTs (<2cm) are often observed, not resected.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, a GIST typically appears as a submucosal lesion with an intact overlying mucosa. Endoscopic Ultrasound (EUS) can characterize size, origin layer, and features suggestive of malignancy. CT scans can show the exophytic nature and potential for metastasis in larger lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for GIST (e.g., 2023) recommend observation for asymptomatic gastric GISTs <2cm.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Total gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Partial gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Observation | ✅ Correct |\n| D | PPI | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
