  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 GIST: Cut it out, don't burst it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: The correct answer is C, WLE (Wedge Local Excision). For a 5cm GIST, a wedge local excision with negative margins is the standard of care, aiming for R0 resection while preserving gastric function.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastrointestinal stromal tumors (GISTs) are typically resected with a goal of achieving negative microscopic margins (R0 resection) without the need for extensive lymphadenectomy, unlike gastric adenocarcinomas. For smaller GISTs, generally <5-8 cm and amenable to local excision, a wedge resection is preferred. This approach minimizes morbidity by preserving gastric volume and function, while still achieving oncologic clearance. The key is to avoid tumor rupture, which can disseminate tumor cells and worsen prognosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Partial Gastrectomy) (Incorrect): This is generally too extensive for a 5cm GIST that can be managed with a more limited resection. GISTs do not require the wide surgical margins or routine lymphadenectomy associated with partial gastrectomy for adenocarcinoma.\nOption B (Total complete Gastrectomy) (Incorrect): This is a grossly overtreatment for a 5cm GIST. Total gastrectomy is reserved for very large, multifocal, or diffuse GISTs where less extensive resection is not feasible, or for advanced gastric adenocarcinomas.\nOption D (Not Remember) (Incorrect): This is not a medical option.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | GIST (5cm) | Gastric Adenocarcinoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Surgical Goal** | R0 resection, preserve organ | R0 resection, wide margins |\n| **Lymphadenectomy** | Not routine | D1/D2 lymphadenectomy |\n| **Margin Requirement** | Grossly negative (1-2 cm) | 5 cm proximal, 2 cm distal |\n| **Adjuvant Therapy** | Imatinib for high risk | Chemo/radiation based on stage |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: GISTs: Resect with negative margins, no routine lymphadenectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or EUS, a GIST typically appears as a well-circumscribed, often exophytic, submucosal mass. Intraoperatively, it's crucial to handle the tumor gently to avoid rupture, which can lead to peritoneal seeding. The tumor often has a pseudocapsule.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (Version 1.2024) recommend surgical resection with negative margins for resectable primary GISTs.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Partial Gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Total complete Gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | WLE | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Not Remember | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
