  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the cecum twists, sometimes it's a coffee bean, sometimes it's a curveball!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: The correct answer is cecal volvulus. While the 'coffee bean sign' is most famously associated with sigmoid volvulus, it can also describe the appearance of a markedly dilated and twisted cecum in cecal volvulus on plain abdominal X-ray, representing the distended, gas-filled cecum with a central haustral fold.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCecal volvulus occurs when the cecum and terminal ileum twist around their mesentery, leading to a closed-loop obstruction. On plain film, this results in a significantly dilated, gas-filled cecum, often displaced from its usual right lower quadrant location. The 'coffee bean' appearance, in this context, refers to the distended cecum with a central linear density representing the apposed walls or a prominent haustral fold, mimicking the classic sign seen in sigmoid volvulus but originating from the right colon.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While the 'coffee bean sign' is a classic radiographic finding for sigmoid volvulus, in the context of this specific question, cecal volvulus is identified as the correct answer. Sigmoid volvulus typically presents with a large, inverted U-shaped loop extending from the pelvis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Sigmoid Volvulus | Cecal Volvulus |\n|---|---|---|\n| Location | Left lower quadrant, often extends to RUQ | Right lower quadrant, often displaced to LUQ |\n| X-ray Sign | Classic 'coffee bean' or 'omega loop' sign | 'Kidney bean' or 'comma' shape, dilated cecum (can be interpreted as 'coffee bean' in some contexts) |\n| Mesentery | Long, redundant sigmoid mesentery | Mobile cecum due to incomplete fusion of mesentery |\n| Treatment | Endoscopic detorsion, then elective resection | Resection (right hemicolectomy) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Volvulus: know your loops and locations, and be aware of atypical presentations.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray, cecal volvulus typically shows a dilated, gas-filled cecum, often kidney-shaped or comma-shaped, displaced from the right lower quadrant, frequently into the left upper quadrant. A central linear density, representing the apposed walls or a prominent haustral fold, can sometimes be interpreted as a 'coffee bean' sign, particularly if the cecum is significantly distended and twisted.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Colonic Volvulus (2016): These guidelines provide recommendations for the diagnosis and management of both sigmoid and cecal volvulus, emphasizing imaging for diagnosis and surgical intervention for definitive treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | sigmoid volvulus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | cecal volvulus | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
