  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Diverticulitis: The old man's LLQ nemesis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nDiverticulitis is the correct diagnosis. The classic presentation of an old male with acute left lower quadrant (LLQ) pain and rebound tenderness strongly points to inflammation of colonic diverticula.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDiverticula are outpouchings of the colonic mucosa and submucosa, most commonly found in the sigmoid colon. When these become inflamed or perforated, it leads to diverticulitis, causing localized LLQ pain. Rebound tenderness signifies peritoneal irritation, a common finding in acute diverticulitis due to localized inflammation or microperforation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Colon cancer typically presents with chronic symptoms like change in bowel habits, weight loss, or bleeding, not usually acute, moderate pain with rebound tenderness as the primary symptom unless complicated by perforation or obstruction.\nOption B (Incorrect): Crohn’s disease can cause abdominal pain, but it's more commonly in the right lower quadrant (terminal ileum) or diffuse. While it can affect the colon, acute LLQ pain with rebound tenderness is not its most typical presentation, especially in an older male presenting acutely.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Typical Presentation | Key Diagnostic Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Diverticulitis** | Acute LLQ pain, fever, change in bowel habits, rebound tenderness | CT scan showing diverticula, pericolic fat stranding, wall thickening |\n| **Colon Cancer** | Chronic change in bowel habits, rectal bleeding, weight loss, anemia | Colonoscopy with biopsy, CT for staging |\n| **Crohn’s Disease** | Chronic abdominal pain, diarrhea, weight loss, perianal disease | Endoscopy with biopsy, skip lesions, transmural inflammation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: LLQ pain with rebound in an old male? Think diverticulitis first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, you would typically see colonic diverticula, thickening of the colonic wall, pericolic fat stranding, and possibly an abscess or free air in more severe cases.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) 2020 Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Treatment of Left-Sided Colonic Diverticulitis: Recommends CT scan with IV contrast as the diagnostic modality of choice for acute diverticulitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Colon cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Crohn’s disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Diverticulosis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
