  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bile in the belly? Clean/contaminated, not clean!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Class II, Clean/contaminated. This classification is appropriate because an elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy involves entering the biliary tract, which is a viscus containing normal flora, under controlled conditions without evidence of infection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSurgical wound classification is crucial for predicting surgical site infection risk and guiding prophylactic antibiotic use. Class II, or Clean/contaminated, wounds are defined as those involving elective, controlled entry into the respiratory, alimentary, genitourinary, or oropharyngeal tracts, or the biliary system, without unusual contamination. A laparoscopic cholecystectomy, even when elective, requires opening the gallbladder (part of the biliary system), thus exposing the surgical field to potential, albeit minimal, bacterial flora from the bile, fitting the Class II definition perfectly.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Class I, Clean wounds, are elective procedures that do not involve entry into the respiratory, alimentary, genitourinary, or oropharyngeal tracts, and there is no inflammation or break in sterile technique (e.g., hernia repair, breast biopsy). Cholecystectomy involves the biliary tract.\nOption C (Incorrect): Class III, Contaminated wounds, involve gross spillage from the gastrointestinal tract, acute non-purulent inflammation, or major breaks in sterile technique. An elective cholecystectomy is performed under controlled conditions.\nOption D (Incorrect): Class IV, Dirty/infected wounds, are those where pus or a perforated viscus is encountered, or where there is pre-existing clinical infection. This is not the case for an elective procedure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Wound Class | Definition | Examples |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Class I (Clean)** | Elective, primary closure, no inflammation, no entry into tracts with normal flora. | Hernia repair, breast biopsy, thyroidectomy |\n| **Class II (Clean/Contaminated)** | Controlled entry into respiratory, alimentary, genitourinary, or biliary tracts without unusual contamination. | Elective cholecystectomy, appendectomy (unruptured), gastrectomy |\n| **Class III (Contaminated)** | Gross spillage from GI tract, acute non-purulent inflammation, major break in sterile technique. | Appendectomy (inflamed), colon resection with spillage, penetrating trauma |\n| **Class IV (Dirty/Infected)** | Existing clinical infection, perforated viscus, pus present. | Abscess drainage, perforated bowel, debridement of infected tissue |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Elective entry into a viscus with normal flora equals Class II, Clean/contaminated.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring a laparoscopic cholecystectomy, the surgeon identifies Calot's triangle and achieves the critical view of safety by dissecting away fat and fibrous tissue to clearly visualize the cystic duct and cystic artery entering the gallbladder, ensuring no misidentification of structures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Guideline for the Prevention of Surgical Site Infection (2017): Recommends appropriate surgical wound classification to guide prophylactic antibiotic use and risk assessment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Class I, Clean | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Class II, Clean/contaminated | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Class III, Contaminated | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Class IV, Dirty | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
