  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gallbladder's calm, but the CBD's wide, think pancreas, not just bile's tide.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. This patient's presentation of painless jaundice, vague abdominal pain, and a dilated common bile duct with a non-tender gallbladder strongly points to an obstructive process, most commonly pancreatic head adenocarcinoma. This classic constellation is known as Courvoisier's sign.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic head cancer often presents insidiously with vague abdominal pain, weight loss, and eventually obstructive jaundice as the tumor compresses the common bile duct. The non-tender, palpable gallbladder (Courvoisier's sign) occurs because the obstruction is typically distal and slow-growing, allowing the gallbladder to distend without inflammation. The dilated CBD on ultrasound confirms biliary obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Acute cholecystitis typically presents with acute right upper quadrant pain, fever, and a tender gallbladder (Murphy's sign). While jaundice can occur with associated choledocholithiasis, it's not the primary presentation with a non-tender gallbladder.\nOption C (Incorrect): Stomach cancer, while potentially causing vague abdominal pain, is less likely to present primarily with isolated obstructive jaundice and a dilated CBD without other prominent gastric symptoms or direct invasion of the porta hepatis, which would be a later stage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pancreatic Head Cancer | Acute Cholecystitis | Choledocholithiasis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pain | Vague, epigastric, often radiating to back | Acute RUQ, often radiating to shoulder | Biliary colic, RUQ, intermittent |\n| Jaundice | Common, progressive, often painless | Less common, usually with CBD stone | Common, fluctuating, often painful |\n| Gallbladder | Non-tender, often palpable (Courvoisier's) | Tender (Murphy's sign) | Non-tender, not typically palpable |\n| CBD | Dilated | Normal or mildly dilated (if stone present) | Dilated (if obstructing) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Painless jaundice + dilated CBD + non-tender gallbladder = pancreatic head mass until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound would show a dilated common bile duct and potentially a mass in the head of the pancreas. CT scan with contrast would further delineate the pancreatic mass, its relationship to surrounding vessels, and assess for metastatic disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and management of pancreatic cancer, including imaging protocols and surgical considerations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pancreas cancer | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Stomach cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
