  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, check the veins out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Venous duplex. This is the best initial diagnostic step for non-pitting lower extremity edema with intact pulses because it effectively evaluates for common venous pathologies like chronic venous insufficiency or deep vein thrombosis, which are frequent causes of such edema.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNon-pitting edema, especially when chronic, often points towards venous insufficiency or lymphedema. A venous duplex ultrasound is a non-invasive, readily available, and highly sensitive and specific test to assess the patency and competence of the deep and superficial venous systems. It can identify venous reflux (incompetent valves) or obstruction (thrombosis), both of which lead to increased hydrostatic pressure in the capillaries, causing fluid extravasation into the interstitial space and subsequent edema.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): CT Angiography is primarily used to evaluate arterial pathology or pulmonary embolism, neither of which is the most likely initial concern for non-pitting edema with intact pulses.\nOption C (Incorrect): Arterial duplex is used to assess arterial flow and blockages. With an intact pulse, significant arterial occlusive disease causing edema is less likely to be the primary diagnosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): This is a statement about an absent option, not a diagnostic choice. While lymphoscintigraphy is the gold standard for diagnosing lymphedema, venous causes are typically ruled out first due to their prevalence and treatability.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Edema Type | Pulse | Initial Diagnostic Test |\n| :---------------------- | :------------------ | :-------------------- | :-------------------------------- |\n| Chronic Venous Insufficiency | Non-pitting (late) / Pitting (early) | Intact | Venous Duplex Ultrasound |\n| Lymphedema | Non-pitting, firm | Intact | Lymphoscintigraphy (if venous ruled out) |\n| Deep Vein Thrombosis | Pitting, acute, unilateral | Intact | Venous Duplex Ultrasound |\n| Arterial Occlusive Disease | None (ischemia) / Pitting (rare, severe) | Diminished/Absent | Arterial Duplex Ultrasound |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Non-pitting edema + intact pulse = rule out venous disease first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA venous duplex ultrasound would show evidence of venous reflux (backward flow during Valsalva or compression) in chronic venous insufficiency, or a thrombus within the vein lumen in cases of DVT.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Society for Vascular Surgery (SVS) and American Venous Forum (AVF) 2020 Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Chronic Venous Disease recommend duplex ultrasound as the primary diagnostic tool for evaluating venous anatomy and function.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Venous duplex | ✅ Correct |\n| B | CT Angio | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Arterial duplex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | NO lymphoscintigraphy in the options | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
