  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Anterior tibia, think ACL: Always correct!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Anterior Cruciate Ligament (ACL). An anterior displacement of the tibia relative to the femur is the hallmark clinical sign of an ACL tear, as the ACL is the primary restraint to anterior tibial translation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Anterior Cruciate Ligament (ACL) originates from the posteromedial aspect of the lateral femoral condyle and inserts into the anteromedial aspect of the tibial plateau. Its primary anatomical function is to prevent anterior translation of the tibia on the femur and to provide rotational stability. When this ligament is compromised or torn, the tibia is no longer adequately restrained, leading to the observed anterior displacement during examination, often elicited by tests like the Lachman or anterior drawer.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Posterior cruciate) (Incorrect): A tear of the Posterior Cruciate Ligament (PCL) would result in posterior displacement or 'sag' of the tibia relative to the femur, not anterior.\nOption C (Lemnisci tear) (Incorrect): 'Lemnisci' is not a recognized anatomical term for knee ligaments. If it refers to menisci, meniscal tears are cartilaginous injuries that cause mechanical symptoms like clicking or locking, but do not primarily manifest as anterior tibial displacement.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Ligament/Structure | Primary Function | Clinical Sign of Injury |\n|--------------------|-----------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|\n| Anterior Cruciate Ligament (ACL) | Prevents anterior tibial translation | Anterior drawer, Lachman test, pivot shift |\n| Posterior Cruciate Ligament (PCL) | Prevents posterior tibial translation | Posterior drawer, posterior sag sign |\n| Medial Collateral Ligament (MCL) | Resists valgus stress | Valgus stress test at 0 and 30 degrees |\n| Lateral Collateral Ligament (LCL) | Resists varus stress | Varus stress test at 0 and 30 degrees |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Anterior tibial translation = ACL. Posterior = PCL.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, an ACL tear would show discontinuity or abnormal signal intensity within the ligament. Arthroscopically, the torn fibers of the ACL would be visibly disrupted or absent, often with a 'mop-end' appearance.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for Management of Anterior Cruciate Ligament Injuries (2014). These guidelines recommend a comprehensive history and physical examination, imaging (MRI), and shared decision-making regarding surgical reconstruction based on patient activity level and goals.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Anterior cruciate | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Posterior cruciate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lemnisci tear | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
