  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Save the spleen, save the child's immune future!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is spleen preservation surgery (splenorrhaphy) because, in pediatric splenic trauma, the primary goal is to preserve splenic function whenever possible, even for Grade 3 injuries, given the spleen's critical immunological role. Non-operative management (NOM) or spleen-preserving surgery is the preferred approach unless there is hemodynamic instability.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe spleen plays a vital role in immune function, particularly in children, by filtering encapsulated bacteria and producing opsonins. Splenectomy carries a significant lifelong risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI). Therefore, modern trauma management prioritizes non-operative management or spleen-preserving techniques like splenorrhaphy, even for higher-grade injuries, to mitigate this risk and maintain immune competence.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Splenectomy) (Incorrect): Splenectomy is generally avoided in pediatric splenic trauma due to the high risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI). It is reserved for cases of hemodynamic instability unresponsive to resuscitation or severe, irreparable splenic destruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Spleen Injury Grade (AAST) | Typical Management (Pediatric) | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| I-III | Non-operative management (NOM) or Spleen Preservation | High success rate, preserve immune function, avoid OPSI. |\n| IV-V | NOM often attempted, Angioembolization, or Splenectomy | NOM still preferred if stable; angioembolization for active bleed; splenectomy as last resort for instability/irreparable damage. |\n| Any Grade with Hemodynamic Instability | Operative Intervention (Splenorrhaphy or Splenectomy) | Life-saving intervention takes precedence over preservation. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always prioritize pediatric spleen preservation unless hemodynamically unstable.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a Grade 3 spleen laceration typically shows a laceration >3 cm deep, or a subcapsular/intraparenchymal hematoma >50% surface area or expanding, or a ruptured subcapsular/intraparenchymal hematoma. Active contrast extravasation indicates ongoing bleeding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) Splenic Injury Scale (2018) and Pediatric Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) guidelines emphasize non-operative management for hemodynamically stable pediatric patients with splenic injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Splenectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Spleen preservation surgery (splenorrhaphy) | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) by exclusion.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
