  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Saphenous nerve: the sensory collateral damage of varicose vein repair.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Saphenous nerve. This nerve is purely sensory and runs in close proximity to the great saphenous vein, making it highly susceptible to injury during varicose vein procedures, which perfectly explains the patient's presentation of isolated sensory loss with intact motor function in the foot.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe saphenous nerve is the longest cutaneous branch of the femoral nerve, providing sensation to the medial side of the leg, ankle, and foot. It descends with the femoral artery and then accompanies the great saphenous vein (GSV) along its course. During varicose vein surgery, such as GSV stripping, thermal ablation, or phlebectomy, the saphenous nerve is at significant risk of direct trauma, compression, or thermal injury due to its anatomical relationship with the vein. Its pure sensory function means that injury manifests as numbness or paresthesia without any motor deficits, precisely matching the clinical scenario.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Sciatic) (Incorrect): The sciatic nerve is a major mixed nerve, providing both motor and sensory innervation to the posterior thigh and nearly all of the leg and foot. Injury to the sciatic nerve would result in significant motor weakness or paralysis, which is absent in this patient, and its anatomical location makes injury during routine varicose vein surgery highly improbable.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Function | Typical Injury Context | Sensory Distribution | Motor Distribution |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Saphenous | Purely Sensory | Varicose vein surgery (stripping, ablation) | Medial leg, ankle, foot | None |\n| Sciatic | Mixed (Motor & Sensory) | Hip dislocation, trauma, IM injection | Posterior thigh, most of leg/foot | Hamstrings, all muscles below knee |\n| Sural | Purely Sensory | Lateral ankle surgery, trauma | Lateral leg, ankle, 5th toe | None |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Varicose surgery + pure sensory loss in medial leg = Saphenous nerve.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound is the gold standard for pre-operative mapping of venous insufficiency and the great saphenous vein. Intraoperatively, the saphenous nerve can often be visualized running adjacent to the great saphenous vein, particularly in the distal thigh and calf, highlighting its vulnerability during vein dissection or ablation procedures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Venous Forum (AVF) and Society for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Varicose Veins and Chronic Venous Insufficiency (e.g., 2011, 2022 update). These guidelines emphasize careful pre-operative mapping and intraoperative techniques to minimize nerve injury.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sciatic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Saphenous | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) N.B: Sciatic > motor and sensory Saphenous > pure sensory Varicose test? Duplex ultrasound** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
