  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ear numbness after neck surgery? Blame the Great Auricular!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe Great auricular nerve is the primary sensory nerve to the pinna and external ear, making option A the correct choice. It provides sensation to the majority of the external ear, including the helix, antihelix, concha, and lobule.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Great auricular nerve originates from the cervical plexus (C2-C3) and ascends obliquely across the sternocleidomastoid muscle. It then divides into anterior and posterior branches, supplying sensory innervation to the skin over the parotid gland, the mastoid process, and, crucially, the majority of the external ear (pinna) on both its lateral and medial surfaces. This extensive coverage makes it the principal nerve for pinna sensation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (less occipital nerve) (Incorrect): The Lesser occipital nerve, also from the cervical plexus (C2), primarily supplies sensation to the skin of the scalp posterior to the auricle and the upper part of the medial surface of the auricle, but not the main body of the pinna.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Primary Sensory Area |\n|---|---|---|\n| Great Auricular Nerve | Cervical Plexus (C2-C3) | Majority of pinna (helix, antihelix, concha, lobule), skin over parotid gland and mastoid |\n| Lesser Occipital Nerve | Cervical Plexus (C2) | Scalp posterior to auricle, upper medial surface of auricle |\n| Auriculotemporal Nerve | Mandibular Nerve (V3) | Tragus, crus of helix, anterior part of external auditory meatus |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Great auricular nerve: \"Great\" for most of the ear's sensation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, during a parotidectomy or neck dissection, the Great auricular nerve is often identified crossing the sternocleidomastoid muscle, superficial to the external jugular vein, and must be preserved if possible to avoid post-operative ear numbness.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific surgical guideline directly addresses this anatomical detail.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Great auricular nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| B | less occipital nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
