  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, drain the bladder and kill the bugs!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. This answer is correct because it addresses both the acute obstructive symptoms (weak urination, potential retention) and the infectious component (painful micturition) in an elderly male. Immediate bladder decompression with a Foley catheter and empiric antibiotics are crucial for stabilization.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe patient's symptoms of weak urination in an 82-year-old male strongly suggest benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) leading to bladder outlet obstruction, potentially progressing to acute urinary retention. Painful micturition indicates a concurrent urinary tract infection (UTI), which is common in patients with incomplete bladder emptying. A Foley catheter provides immediate relief from obstruction, prevents renal damage from back pressure, and allows for bladder decompression. Antibiotics are essential to treat the infection, which can be severe in elderly patients and can complicate any future interventions. This combined approach prioritizes patient comfort, prevents complications, and stabilizes the patient before further diagnostic workup or definitive treatment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (ABx for UTI) (Incorrect): While antibiotics are needed, they do not address the underlying obstruction or potential urinary retention, which can lead to worsening symptoms, renal damage, or urosepsis if left untreated. \nOption C (Cystoscopy and TURP) (Incorrect): Cystoscopy and TURP are definitive diagnostic and surgical treatments for BPH, respectively. They are not appropriate initial management for an acute presentation with suspected infection and obstruction. Performing TURP in the setting of an active UTI is contraindicated due to the high risk of sepsis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Acute Management | Definitive Management | Key Consideration |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Acute Urinary Retention (AUR) | Foley catheterization | Alpha-blockers, 5-ARI, TURP | Rapid bladder decompression |\n| Urinary Tract Infection (UTI) | Empiric antibiotics | Culture-directed antibiotics | Rule out underlying cause (e.g., obstruction) |\n| Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (BPH) | Alpha-blockers, 5-ARI | TURP, UroLift, Rezum | Symptom severity, quality of life |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always decompress an obstructed bladder and treat infection first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn bedside ultrasound, you would likely see a distended bladder with significant post-void residual volume. The prostate might appear enlarged. During catheterization, there might be resistance due to prostatic enlargement, and a large volume of urine would be drained.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines for the Management of Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia/Lower Urinary Tract Symptoms (2021) and AUA Guidelines for Asymptomatic Bacteriuria and Urinary Tract Infection (2019) recommend immediate catheterization for acute urinary retention and antibiotics for symptomatic UTIs.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | ABx for UTI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Foley catheter and ABx | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Cystoscopy and TURP | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
