  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't catheterize a broken urethra; divert and defer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nSuprapubic cystostomy is the correct initial management for a retroperitoneal urethral injury associated with a pelvic fracture. This approach provides immediate urinary diversion without risking further damage to the compromised urethra.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPelvic fractures are frequently associated with posterior urethral injuries, which are retroperitoneal. The primary goal in managing such injuries acutely is to establish urinary drainage safely while avoiding manipulation of the injured urethra. A suprapubic cystostomy achieves this by diverting urine directly from the bladder, preventing extravasation of urine into the retroperitoneum and allowing the urethra to heal or be definitively repaired at a later, more stable time.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Foley's cath) (Incorrect): Attempting to pass a Foley catheter through a known or suspected urethral injury is contraindicated as it can worsen the tear, create a false passage, or introduce infection, potentially complicating future repair.\nOption C (Laparoscopic repair) (Incorrect): Acute urethral injuries, especially posterior ones, are not typically managed with immediate laparoscopic repair. The initial management focuses on urinary diversion (suprapubic cystostomy), with definitive repair often delayed for several weeks or months to allow for resolution of inflammation and hematoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Injury Type | Location | Initial Management | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Anterior Urethral Injury (e.g., straddle injury) | Bulbar/Penile urethra | Suprapubic cystostomy | Avoids further damage, allows healing |\n| Posterior Urethral Injury (e.g., pelvic fracture) | Membranous/Prostatic urethra | Suprapubic cystostomy | Avoids further damage, allows healing, prevents extravasation |\n| Urethral stricture (acute retention) | Any part of urethra | Suprapubic cystostomy (if unable to pass catheter) | Provides drainage, avoids trauma to stricture |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pelvic fracture + urethral injury = suprapubic cystostomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA urethrogram would demonstrate extravasation of contrast from the urethral lumen into the retroperitoneal space, confirming the injury. On CT, one might see a pelvic hematoma or displacement of the bladder/prostate due to the pelvic fracture and associated soft tissue injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Urethral Trauma (2017): Recommends initial urinary diversion with suprapubic cystostomy for most posterior urethral injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Folly's cath | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Supra pubic cystostomy | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Laparoscopic repair | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
