  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For GISTs, if it's 5 cm, it's time to trim!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Wedge Local Excision (WLE). A 5 cm gastric GIST is a resectable tumor that requires surgical intervention to achieve cure and prevent progression, making WLE the appropriate primary treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGISTs originate from the interstitial cells of Cajal in the muscularis propria. Surgical resection, specifically a wedge gastrectomy for gastric GISTs, aims for an R0 margin. Unlike adenocarcinomas, GISTs rarely metastasize to lymph nodes, so routine lymphadenectomy is not indicated. The goal is complete tumor removal with minimal gastric tissue sacrifice, which is typically achieved with a wedge resection for a 5 cm gastric lesion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Observe) (Incorrect): A 5 cm GIST carries a significant risk of malignant behavior and progression, thus observation is not appropriate. Observation is generally reserved for very small (<2 cm) asymptomatic GISTs in low-risk locations.\nOption C (Chemo) (Incorrect): While imatinib is crucial for GIST management, it is typically used in the neoadjuvant or adjuvant setting for high-risk, unresectable, or metastatic disease. For a primary resectable 5 cm gastric GIST, surgery is the first-line treatment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | <2 cm Gastric GIST | 2-5 cm Gastric GIST | >5 cm Gastric GIST or High Mitotic Index | Unresectable/Metastatic GIST |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Risk | Very Low | Low to Intermediate | High | High |\n| Management | Observation or Endoscopic Resection | Surgical Resection (WLE) | Surgical Resection +/- Adjuvant Imatinib | Neoadjuvant/Palliative Imatinib |\n| Lymphadenectomy | Not indicated | Not indicated | Not indicated | Not indicated |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Resectable gastric GISTs >2cm require surgical excision, usually wedge.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or EUS, a GIST typically appears as a well-circumscribed, often exophytic, submucosal mass arising from the muscularis propria. Intraoperatively, it presents as a firm, often encapsulated tumor, usually without associated lymphadenopathy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (e.g., Version 1.2024). These guidelines recommend surgical resection with negative margins as the primary treatment for localized, resectable GISTs.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | WLE | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Observe | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Chemo | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
