  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cut the stricture, save the patient.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nResection with ileostomy is the most appropriate next step for a stricture in the terminal ileum. This approach definitively removes the diseased segment and provides a safe diversion, especially if the patient's condition or local inflammation makes a primary anastomosis high-risk.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA symptomatic stricture in the terminal ileum, a common site for Crohn's disease, often necessitates surgical intervention to relieve obstruction. Resection removes the fibrotic, non-compliant segment, restoring luminal patency and alleviating symptoms. The decision to perform an ileostomy, rather than a primary anastomosis, is often made when there is significant inflammation, perforation, or other factors that increase the risk of anastomotic leak, thus protecting the patient from severe postoperative complications.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Strictureplasty) (Incorrect): Strictureplasty is typically reserved for shorter, non-fibrotic strictures or multiple strictures to preserve bowel length, but resection is often preferred for terminal ileal strictures, especially if long or complicated.\nOption B (Small bowel resection) (Incorrect): While small bowel resection is part of the correct answer, 'resection with ileostomy' is a more complete and often safer option in scenarios where primary anastomosis is contraindicated or high-risk due to inflammation or patient factors.\nOption D (IV antibiotics) (Incorrect): IV antibiotics may treat associated inflammation or infection but do not resolve a mechanical, fibrotic stricture causing obstruction. This is a medical, not a surgical, solution for a structural problem.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Indication | Pros | Cons |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Strictureplasty | Short, non-fibrotic strictures; multiple strictures | Bowel preservation | Risk of recurrence; not for complicated strictures |\n| Resection with primary anastomosis | Localized, resectable disease; healthy bowel ends | Definitive; restores continuity | Risk of anastomotic leak; recurrence |\n| Resection with ileostomy | Severe inflammation; perforation; high-risk anastomosis | Diverts fecal stream; protects anastomosis | Stoma care; potential for reversal |\n| Medical management (e.g., biologics) | Inflammatory strictures; mild symptoms | Avoids surgery | Not effective for fibrotic strictures; long-term commitment |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Terminal ileal stricture often means resection, sometimes with diversion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, a terminal ileal stricture would appear as a segment of narrowed bowel lumen with proximal dilation. Wall thickening and enhancement might also be present. Intraoperatively, the strictured segment would be palpably firm, thickened, and narrowed, often with surrounding inflammation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASCRS Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Surgical Management of Crohn's Disease (2020) recommend surgical resection for symptomatic, fibrotic, or complicated strictures unresponsive to medical therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Strictureplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Small bowel resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Resection with ileostomy | ✅ Correct |\n| D | IV antibiotics | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
