  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Polyps galore? Think FAP, cancer's knocking at the door!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Familial polypoid, which in this context refers to Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP). This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the presence of \"numerous polyps covering the linings\" in a young, otherwise healthy 28-year-old male presenting with abdominal pain and bloody stools.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFamilial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP) is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by a germline mutation in the APC gene. It is characterized by the development of hundreds to thousands of adenomatous polyps throughout the colon and rectum, typically appearing in the teenage years or early twenties. Without intervention, nearly 100% of individuals with FAP will develop colorectal cancer by age 40. The clinical presentation of diffuse polyposis in a young patient, as described in the question, is pathognomonic for FAP, even in the absence of a known family history (due to de novo mutations).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (UC) (Incorrect): Ulcerative Colitis is an inflammatory bowel disease characterized by diffuse inflammation of the colonic mucosa, leading to bloody diarrhea. While UC can lead to pseudopolyps (inflammatory polyps), it does not typically present with \"numerous polyps covering the linings\" that are true adenomas, which is characteristic of FAP.\nOption C (Diverticulosis coli) (Incorrect): Diverticulosis involves the formation of small pouches (diverticula) in the colon wall, usually in older individuals. It can cause abdominal pain and bleeding but does not involve the presence of \"numerous polyps covering the linings.\"\nOption D (Human papillomavirus polyp) (Incorrect): Human papillomavirus (HPV) typically causes anogenital warts or squamous cell carcinoma, not diffuse adenomatous polyps throughout the colon. HPV polyps are not a common cause of widespread colonic polyposis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP) | Ulcerative Colitis (UC) | Diverticulosis Coli | Juvenile Polyposis Syndrome (JPS) |\n| :------------------ | :----------------------------------- | :---------------------------------- | :------------------------------ | :-------------------------------- |\n| **Etiology** | Germline APC mutation | Autoimmune inflammatory | Acquired, low fiber diet | Germline BMPR1A/SMAD4 mutation |\n| **Polyps** | Hundreds-thousands of adenomas | Inflammatory pseudopolyps | Not polyps (outpouchings) | Few (5-100) hamartomatous polyps |\n| **Age of Onset** | Teens-20s | Any age, often young adult | >50 years | Childhood |\n| **Cancer Risk** | Nearly 100% colorectal cancer | Increased (with duration/extent) | No direct increase | Increased (colorectal, gastric) |\n| **Key Presentation** | Diffuse polyps, bleeding, abd pain | Bloody diarrhea, tenesmus, urgency | LLQ pain, bleeding, constipation | Rectal bleeding, prolapse, anemia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hundreds of polyps in a young patient = FAP until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn proctoscopy or colonoscopy, FAP is characterized by a carpet of innumerable polyps (often >100) covering the mucosal surface of the colon and rectum. These polyps are typically small, sessile, or pedunculated adenomas. Biopsies would confirm adenomatous histology.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) and American Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) guidelines for the management of FAP (e.g., 2015 ASCRS Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Familial Adenomatous Polyposis) recommend prophylactic colectomy due to the near 100% lifetime risk of colorectal cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Familial polypoid | ✅ Correct |\n| B | UC | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Diverticulosis coli | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Human papillomavirus polyp | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
