  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, it's usually a benign, silent adrenal guest.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, nonfunctional adenoma. This is because the vast majority of adrenal masses discovered incidentally on imaging are benign, non-hormone-producing lesions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdrenal incidentalomas are common, found in up to 4-7% of abdominal CT scans. A nonfunctional adenoma is a benign tumor of the adrenal cortex that does not produce excess hormones. Its high prevalence, coupled with its asymptomatic nature, makes it the most frequent type of adrenal mass discovered accidentally, often during imaging for unrelated conditions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (sub clinical Cushing) (Incorrect): While subclinical Cushing's syndrome is a functional adrenal adenoma that can be discovered incidentally, it accounts for a smaller percentage of incidentalomas compared to nonfunctional adenomas.\nOption B (Conn’s) (Incorrect): Conn's syndrome (primary hyperaldosteronism) is caused by an aldosterone-producing adenoma, which is a functional tumor and less common than nonfunctional adenomas.\nOption C (cancer) (Incorrect): Adrenocortical carcinoma is a rare malignancy, accounting for a very small fraction of adrenal incidentalomas. Most incidentalomas are benign.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Adrenal Mass | Functionality | Prevalence (of Incidentalomas) | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Nonfunctional Adenoma | Non-functional | ~70-80% | Most common, benign |\n| Subclinical Cushing's | Cortisol excess | ~5-10% | Mild hypercortisolism |\n| Conn's Syndrome | Aldosterone excess | ~1-5% | Hypertension, hypokalemia |\n| Adrenocortical Carcinoma | Variable (often functional) | <1% | Malignant, aggressive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Most adrenal incidentalomas are benign and nonfunctional.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a benign adrenal adenoma typically appears as a well-circumscribed, homogeneous mass with a low unenhanced Hounsfield unit (HU) value (<10 HU) due to its high lipid content, and rapid contrast washout (>50% absolute washout at 15 minutes).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2016 AACE/AAES Medical and Surgical Guidelines for Adrenal Incidentalomas. These guidelines recommend a comprehensive evaluation for functionality and malignancy risk, with follow-up imaging and hormonal testing based on initial findings.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | sub clinical Cushing | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Conn’s | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | nonfunctional adenoma | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
