  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Phyllodes: Go wide, or it'll ride again!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct management for a phyllodes tumor is Wide Local Excision (WLE). This approach is crucial to ensure adequate tumor-free margins, which is the primary goal in preventing local recurrence, a significant concern with phyllodes tumors.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhyllodes tumors, while often benign, have a propensity for local recurrence if not completely excised. WLE involves removing the tumor with a surrounding rim of healthy tissue (clear margins), typically 1 cm or more, to minimize this risk. The surgical mechanism focuses on achieving R0 resection, which is paramount for local control and is the standard of care across all grades of phyllodes tumors.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Simple mastectomy is generally considered overtreatment for most phyllodes tumors. It is typically reserved for very large tumors where WLE would result in an unacceptable cosmetic outcome, or for recurrent tumors after previous excisions, or for malignant phyllodes tumors with extensive local disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Breast Lesion Type | Typical Management | Key Feature |\n| :----------------- | :----------------- | :---------- |\n| Phyllodes Tumor    | Wide Local Excision (WLE) with clear margins | Risk of local recurrence |\n| Fibroadenoma       | Observation; Excision if symptomatic/large | Benign, common |\n| Ductal Carcinoma In Situ (DCIS) | WLE + radiation or mastectomy | Non-invasive cancer |\n| Invasive Ductal Carcinoma (IDC) | Lumpectomy + radiation or mastectomy + sentinel lymph node biopsy | Invasive cancer |\n| Atypical Ductal Hyperplasia (ADH) | Excisional biopsy | Increased cancer risk |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Phyllodes tumors demand wide excision to prevent recurrence.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (ultrasound or mammography), phyllodes tumors often appear as well-circumscribed, lobulated masses, sometimes with cystic areas. Intraoperatively, they can be firm and well-defined, but achieving clear margins requires careful dissection and often intraoperative margin assessment.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (latest edition) recommend wide local excision with clear margins (typically ≥1 cm) for phyllodes tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | WLE | ✅ Correct |\n| B | simple mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
