  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For chronic fissures, cut the spasm, not just the tag.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A, Internal lateral sphincterotomy, is the correct management for a chronic anal fissure with a skin tag. The presence of a skin tag (sentinel pile) indicates chronicity, and the definitive treatment for chronic anal fissures is surgical division of the internal anal sphincter to reduce hypertonia and promote healing.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInternal lateral sphincterotomy (ILS) is the gold standard surgical treatment for chronic anal fissures. This procedure involves a controlled division of a portion of the internal anal sphincter, which is pathologically hypertonic in chronic fissures. By reducing the resting anal canal pressure, ILS improves blood flow to the anoderm, thereby facilitating the healing of the fissure. The associated skin tag, or sentinel pile, is a reactive inflammatory process and typically resolves or becomes asymptomatic once the underlying fissure heals, thus not requiring separate excision.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Curettage of the fissure with removal of the skin tag is an inadequate treatment. This approach fails to address the underlying cause of chronic anal fissure, which is the hypertonicity of the internal anal sphincter, and would likely result in recurrence and persistent symptoms.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Anal Fissure | Chronic Anal Fissure |\n|---|---|---|\n| Duration | < 6 weeks | > 6 weeks |\n| Appearance | Superficial tear, no sentinel pile | Deep ulcer, often with sentinel pile/hypertrophied papilla |\n| Pathophysiology | Trauma, spasm | Sphincter hypertonia, ischemia |\n| First-line Tx | Medical (nitrates, CCBs, stool softeners) | Internal Lateral Sphincterotomy (ILS) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Chronic anal fissure with skin tag = internal lateral sphincterotomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, a chronic anal fissure typically appears as a deep ulcer, most commonly in the posterior midline, often with a distal hypertrophied skin tag (sentinel pile) and/or a proximal hypertrophied anal papilla. During internal lateral sphincterotomy, the hypertrophied internal anal sphincter is identified and carefully divided.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Anal Fissures (2017) recommend internal lateral sphincterotomy as the most effective surgical treatment for chronic anal fissures refractory to medical therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Internal lateral sphincterotomy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Curettage of fissure with removal of the skin tag | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
