  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Air in the bile ducts plus obstruction means a stone on the move.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Gallstone Ileus, which is characterized by pneumobilia resulting from a cholecystoenteric fistula, often leading to intestinal obstruction. The 10-year history of gallstones suggests a chronic process leading to fistula formation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus is a rare complication of chronic cholecystitis where a large gallstone erodes through the gallbladder wall into an adjacent loop of bowel, forming a cholecystoenteric fistula. This fistula allows air from the intestine to enter the biliary tree, causing pneumobilia. The migrated gallstone then travels distally, typically lodging in the terminal ileum, causing mechanical small bowel obstruction. This sequence of events explains both the air in the biliary system and the potential for obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cholecystitis) (Incorrect): While emphysematous cholecystitis, a severe form of acute cholecystitis, can cause air in the biliary system due to gas-forming organisms, it does not typically lead to intestinal obstruction. The question's emphasis on a 10-year history and the correct answer's mention of obstruction points away from acute cholecystitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Pathophysiology | Pneumobilia | Intestinal Obstruction |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Gallstone Ileus | Cholecystoenteric fistula formation and stone migration | Yes | Yes (due to ectopic stone) |\n| Emphysematous Cholecystitis | Gas-forming bacterial infection of gallbladder | Yes | No |\n| Post-ERCP/Sphincterotomy | Iatrogenic introduction of air | Yes | No |\n| Biliary-enteric Anastomosis | Surgical connection allowing air reflux | Yes | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pneumobilia + SBO + ectopic stone = Gallstone Ileus.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (X-ray/CT), Rigler's triad is pathognomonic for gallstone ileus: pneumobilia, small bowel obstruction, and an ectopic gallstone. Intraoperatively, a cholecystoenteric fistula is typically found, often between the gallbladder and duodenum or jejunum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the management of acute calculous cholecystitis (2020) discuss complications like gallstone ileus, recommending surgical intervention for obstruction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gallbladder ileus | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) air in biliary cause by necrotizing infection or fistula. If there intestinal obstruction > B.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
