  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the patient's burned, don't be burned by a big cut!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. In a critically ill major burn patient presenting with acute cholecystitis, the primary goal is source control with minimal physiological insult. A cholecystostomy tube achieves gallbladder decompression and drainage, stabilizing the patient without the high morbidity of a major surgical procedure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute cholecystitis in critically ill patients, especially those with major burns, is often acalculous and represents a severe inflammatory process. Performing an open cholecystectomy in this setting carries significant risks due to the patient's compromised physiological state, including increased risk of sepsis, wound complications, and mortality. Percutaneous cholecystostomy provides effective biliary decompression and drainage, reducing inflammation and sepsis, thereby allowing the patient to stabilize before considering definitive cholecystectomy at a later, safer time.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Open cholecystectomy is a definitive procedure that is too invasive and carries unacceptably high morbidity and mortality in a critically ill major burn patient. It would significantly worsen their already precarious physiological state.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Cholecystostomy Tube | Cholecystectomy (Open/Laparoscopic) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Indication** | Critically ill patients (sepsis, burns, multi-organ failure), high surgical risk, acalculous cholecystitis | Stable patients, calculous cholecystitis, recurrent cholecystitis |\n| **Goal** | Source control, decompression, temporizing measure | Definitive treatment, gallbladder removal |\n| **Invasiveness** | Minimally invasive (percutaneous) | Moderately to highly invasive |\n| **Timing** | Urgent/Emergent | Elective or urgent (depending on severity and patient stability) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: In critically ill patients with cholecystitis, drain first, excise later.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound or CT scan would typically show gallbladder wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, and potentially a distended gallbladder. Intraoperatively, a cholecystostomy tube is placed percutaneously under imaging guidance (ultrasound or CT) into the gallbladder lumen to drain bile and pus.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis. They recommend percutaneous cholecystostomy for Grade II or III acute cholecystitis in high-risk or critically ill patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | cholecystostomy tube | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Open cholecystectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
