  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gallbladder is angry, take it out early!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is laparoscopic cholecystectomy. This is the definitive treatment for acute cholecystitis with gallstones, as indicated by the ultrasound findings of gallbladder wall thickening, pericystic fluid, and stones.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute cholecystitis, characterized by RUQ pain and sonographic evidence of inflammation (wall thickening, pericystic fluid, stones), is best managed by early laparoscopic cholecystectomy. This approach removes the source of inflammation, prevents recurrence, and is associated with lower morbidity and shorter hospital stays compared to delayed surgery or non-operative management in suitable candidates.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (percutanous drainage) (Incorrect): Percutaneous cholecystostomy is typically reserved for patients who are too unstable for surgery, have severe comorbidities, or as a temporizing measure. It does not remove the underlying pathology (stones) and is not the definitive \"best\" intervention for an otherwise stable patient.\n\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy | Percutaneous Cholecystostomy |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Indication** | Definitive treatment for acute cholecystitis in stable patients | Temporizing measure for unstable patients or those with severe comorbidities |\n| **Goal** | Remove gallbladder and stones, prevent recurrence | Decompress gallbladder, resolve acute inflammation |\n| **Definitive?** | Yes | No (often requires subsequent cholecystectomy) |\n| **Risk** | Surgical risks (anesthesia, bile duct injury) | Catheter-related complications (dislodgement, infection), persistent fistula |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute cholecystitis with stones = early laparoscopic cholecystectomy for stable patients.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound findings for acute cholecystitis include gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, gallstones, and a positive sonographic Murphy's sign. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder would appear inflamed, edematous, and potentially distended.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis recommend early laparoscopic cholecystectomy (within 72 hours of symptom onset) for Grade I and II acute cholecystitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | percutanous drainage. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | laparoscopic cholecystectomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
