  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Clear the duct, then take the sack!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with jaundice and ultrasound evidence of stones in both the gallbladder (GB) and the common bile duct (CBD). The immediate priority is to relieve the biliary obstruction caused by the CBD stone, which is best achieved by ERCP.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nObstructive jaundice due to a CBD stone is a critical condition that requires prompt intervention to prevent complications such as cholangitis, pancreatitis, and liver damage. ERCP (Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography) is the gold standard for both diagnosing and therapeutically managing CBD stones. It allows for direct visualization of the ampulla, sphincterotomy, and subsequent extraction of the CBD stone using a balloon or basket, or placement of a stent to ensure biliary drainage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Laparoscopic cholecystectomy) (Incorrect): While the patient has gallstones, performing a cholecystectomy alone would not address the CBD stone or the obstructive jaundice. The CBD stone must be cleared first to relieve the obstruction and prevent serious complications. Cholecystectomy is typically performed after CBD clearance.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Presentation | Initial Treatment | Subsequent Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cholelithiasis | Asymptomatic gallstones | Observation | N/A |\n| Biliary Colic | RUQ pain, post-prandial | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy | N/A |\n| Acute Cholecystitis | RUQ pain, fever, leukocytosis | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy (early) | N/A |\n| Choledocholithiasis | Jaundice, RUQ pain, fever (Charcot's triad) | ERCP with stone extraction | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy (after CBD clearance) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Jaundice + CBD stone = ERCP first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound showing a dilated CBD with a hyperechoic focus and posterior shadowing within it is highly suggestive of choledocholithiasis. During ERCP, fluoroscopy with contrast injection confirms the presence and location of the CBD stone, guiding endoscopic stone extraction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) Guidelines for the role of endoscopy in the management of choledocholithiasis (2019). These guidelines recommend ERCP for patients with a high probability of choledocholithiasis, especially those with jaundice and CBD dilation/stones on imaging.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Laparoscopic cholecystectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | ERCP | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
