  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a pseudocyst grows, it's time for it to go!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: Internal drainage is the correct management for a pancreatic pseudocyst that is increasing in size over 3 months. This indicates a mature, symptomatic pseudocyst that is unlikely to resolve spontaneously and requires definitive surgical intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInternal drainage, typically via cystogastrostomy or cystojejunostomy, establishes a permanent communication between the pseudocyst and the gastrointestinal tract. This allows continuous drainage of the cyst contents, preventing further enlargement and symptom recurrence. The 3-month duration suggests the pseudocyst wall is mature and fibrotic, making it suitable for anastomosis and reducing the risk of leak or fistula compared to earlier intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Follow up) (Incorrect): Continued observation is inappropriate for a pseudocyst that is actively increasing in size, as this indicates progression and potential complications rather than spontaneous resolution.\nOption C (percutaneous drainage) (Incorrect): While useful for acutely infected or unstable patients, percutaneous drainage is often temporary, associated with higher recurrence rates, and carries a risk of pancreatic fistula, making it less definitive than internal drainage for a mature, enlarging pseudocyst in a stable patient.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Observation | Percutaneous Drainage | Internal Drainage |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Indication | Asymptomatic, <6cm, <6 weeks | Infected pseudocyst, unstable patient, temporary relief | Symptomatic, >6cm, mature (>6 weeks), enlarging |\n| Efficacy | Spontaneous resolution (up to 50%) | High recurrence, risk of fistula | Definitive, low recurrence |\n| Complications | Rupture, infection | Fistula, infection, recurrence | Bleeding, leak, infection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Enlarging, mature pseudocyst = internal drainage.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a pancreatic pseudocyst appears as a well-defined, encapsulated fluid collection adjacent to the pancreas. Intraoperatively, a mature pseudocyst will have a thick, fibrous wall suitable for anastomosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nIAP/APA Guidelines for the Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013) recommend intervention for symptomatic or enlarging pseudocysts, with internal drainage being the preferred definitive method for mature cysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Follow up | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Internal drainage | ✅ Correct |\n| C | percutaneous drainage | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
