  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Deep peroneal: Dorsiflexion and the dorsal webspace, don't forget!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is the Deep Peroneal nerve. This nerve is responsible for dorsiflexion of the foot and provides sensory innervation to the critical first dorsal webspace, making its injury the direct cause of the patient's symptoms.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Deep Peroneal nerve, a terminal branch of the common peroneal nerve, innervates the muscles of the anterior compartment of the leg, including the tibialis anterior, extensor hallucis longus, and extensor digitorum longus. Damage to these muscles results in 'drop foot' due to impaired dorsiflexion. Crucially, it also supplies sensation to the skin of the first dorsal webspace between the first and second toes. The combination of drop foot and this specific sensory loss is pathognomonic for deep peroneal nerve injury, often due to compression or trauma in the anterior compartment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (common peroneal nerve) (Incorrect): While the common peroneal nerve gives rise to the deep peroneal, a common peroneal nerve injury would typically present with a broader sensory deficit involving the lateral leg and dorsum of the foot, in addition to drop foot. The specific first webspace loss points to the deep branch.\nOption C (Tibial nerve) (Incorrect): The tibial nerve innervates the posterior compartment muscles (plantarflexion, toe flexion) and provides sensation to the sole of the foot. Its injury would cause a 'calcaneal gait' and plantar sensory loss, not drop foot or first webspace numbness.\nOption D (Femoral nerve) (Incorrect): The femoral nerve innervates the quadriceps femoris for knee extension and provides sensation to the anterior thigh and medial leg. Damage would result in quadriceps weakness and different sensory deficits, unrelated to foot drop or dorsal foot sensation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Motor Function | Sensory Distribution | Key Clinical Sign |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Deep Peroneal** | Dorsiflexion, toe extension | 1st dorsal webspace | Drop foot, 1st webspace numbness |\n| **Common Peroneal** | Dorsiflexion, eversion, toe extension | Lateral leg, dorsum of foot (broader) | Drop foot, broader dorsal foot numbness |\n| **Tibial** | Plantarflexion, toe flexion | Sole of foot | Calcaneal gait, plantar numbness |\n| **Femoral** | Knee extension, hip flexion | Anterior thigh, medial leg | Quadriceps weakness, anterior thigh numbness |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Drop foot + 1st webspace numbness = Deep Peroneal nerve injury.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging such as MRI or ultrasound might reveal nerve compression or injury along the course of the deep peroneal nerve, particularly in the anterior compartment of the leg or at the ankle. Intraoperatively, direct visualization would confirm nerve transection, entrapment, or compression.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Neurology (AAN) guidelines for the diagnosis and management of peripheral neuropathy (2020) provide frameworks for evaluating nerve injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | common peroneal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Deep Peroneal nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Tibial nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Femoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
