  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Midline, mobile, and moves with munching? Think thyroglossal!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Thyroglossal cyst. This diagnosis is confirmed by the classic presentation of a midline cervical mass that moves with swallowing, a hallmark sign of its embryological origin.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThyroglossal duct cysts arise from the persistent embryological thyroglossal duct, which normally involutes by the 10th week of gestation. This duct connects the foramen cecum at the base of the tongue to the thyroid gland's final position. The cyst's attachment to the hyoid bone, and often to the tongue base, explains its characteristic upward movement with tongue protrusion and swallowing, as these actions elevate the hyoid bone.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cystic hygroma) (Incorrect): Cystic hygromas are lymphatic malformations, typically presenting as soft, compressible, transilluminable masses, usually located laterally in the neck (posterior triangle) and do not move with swallowing.\nOption C (Submental lymphadenopathy) (Incorrect): Submental lymphadenopathy refers to enlarged lymph nodes in the submental region, usually due to infection or inflammation. These are typically tender, firm, and do not exhibit movement with swallowing or tongue protrusion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Thyroglossal Cyst | Cystic Hygroma | Submental Lymphadenopathy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Location** | Midline, often near hyoid bone | Lateral neck (posterior triangle) | Submental region (under chin) |\n| **Movement with Swallowing** | Yes | No | No |\n| **Etiology** | Remnant of thyroglossal duct | Lymphatic malformation | Infection/Inflammation |\n| **Consistency** | Smooth, firm, mobile | Soft, compressible, transilluminable | Firm, often tender |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Midline neck mass moving with swallowing = Thyroglossal cyst until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, a thyroglossal duct cyst appears as a well-defined, anechoic or hypoechoic midline cystic lesion, often intimately associated with the hyoid bone. Intraoperatively, the Sistrunk procedure involves excising the cyst along with the central portion of the hyoid bone and a core of tissue extending to the foramen cecum to prevent recurrence.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) guidelines for pediatric neck masses (various years) recommend surgical excision (Sistrunk procedure) for symptomatic or enlarging thyroglossal duct cysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cystic hygroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thyroglossal cyst | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Submental lymphadenopathy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
