  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the spleen's vein clots, the fundus bleeds; remove the spleen, and the problem recedes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Splenectomy. This patient presents with gastric fundus bleeding due to isolated splenic vein thrombosis (ISVT) following pancreatitis, a classic scenario where splenectomy is the definitive treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIsolated splenic vein thrombosis (ISVT) leads to increased pressure in the splenic venous system, which then decompresses via the short gastric veins into the gastric fundus, causing gastric varices (often GOV1 type). Since the portal vein is patent, the hypertension is localized to the splenic circulation. Splenectomy removes the thrombosed splenic vein and the spleen, thereby eliminating the source of high pressure and decompressing the short gastric veins, effectively treating the gastric varices and preventing further bleeding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Portal-systemic shunts are typically reserved for generalized portal hypertension, such as that caused by cirrhosis or diffuse portal vein thrombosis. In this case, the portal vein is patent, indicating that the hypertension is localized to the splenic system, not generalized portal hypertension. A portal-systemic shunt would be an overly aggressive and inappropriate intervention for ISVT.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Isolated Splenic Vein Thrombosis (ISVT) | Generalized Portal Hypertension (e.g., Cirrhosis) |\n| :------------------ | :-------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------ |\n| **Cause** | Pancreatitis, malignancy, myeloproliferative disorders | Cirrhosis, portal vein thrombosis, Budd-Chiari |\n| **Varices Location**| Primarily gastric fundus (GOV1) | Esophageal, gastric (GOV2, IGV1), ectopic |\n| **Portal Vein** | Patent | Often patent but elevated pressure, or thrombosed |\n| **Management** | Splenectomy | TIPS, shunts, endoscopic therapy, beta-blockers |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gastric fundal varices + patent portal vein = think isolated splenic vein thrombosis, treat with splenectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound would show a thrombosed splenic vein with absent flow, while the portal vein would demonstrate normal patency and flow. Endoscopy would reveal gastric fundal varices, often appearing as large, tortuous veins in the fundus.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nBaveno VII Consensus Report (2022): While not specifically detailing ISVT management, it provides comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis and management of portal hypertension and variceal bleeding, including gastric varices, emphasizing the importance of identifying the underlying cause.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Splenectomy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Portal-systemic shunt | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
