  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stability dictates the bleed's fate.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct management of bleeding angiodysplasia hinges critically on the patient's hemodynamic stability. For stable patients, a less invasive, targeted approach is preferred, while unstable patients require rapid and effective bleeding control.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEndoscopic laser ablation (Option C) is the gold standard for stable patients with angiodysplasia, offering direct visualization and precise coagulation of the vascular lesion, minimizing invasiveness. For unstable patients, angio-embolization (Option B) provides rapid, minimally invasive control of active bleeding by selectively occluding the culprit vessel, which is crucial for hemodynamic stabilization. Angiodysplasias are typically small, superficial vascular malformations, making these targeted approaches highly effective.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Left hemicolectomy) (Incorrect): Surgical resection is generally considered a last resort for angiodysplasia, reserved for cases of massive, refractory bleeding or diffuse disease unresponsive to endoscopic or angiographic interventions. It is too aggressive for initial management.\nOption B (Angio-embolization) (Incorrect for stable patients): While effective for unstable patients, it is more invasive than endoscopy. For a stable patient, endoscopic therapy is the preferred first-line treatment due to its lower risk profile and direct visualization.\nOption C (Endoscopic laser ablation) (Incorrect for unstable patients): Endoscopic therapy can be time-consuming and may not be sufficient to control massive, life-threatening bleeding in an unstable patient, where rapid hemostasis via angio-embolization is paramount.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Patient Status | Bleeding Severity | Initial Management | Next Step (if failed) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Stable | Mild-Moderate | Endoscopic therapy (ablation, APC, cautery) | Angiography with embolization |\n| Unstable | Severe/Refractory | Angiography with embolization | Surgical resection (e.g., hemicolectomy) |\n| Recurrent | Localized | Repeat Endoscopic therapy | Angiography/Surgery |\n| Recurrent | Diffuse/Unlocalized | Surgical resection (e.g., colectomy) | N/A |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stability dictates initial GI bleed management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, angiodysplasia appears as flat or slightly raised cherry-red lesions, often with a fern-like or stellate pattern. Angiography can reveal a vascular tuft, early venous filling, and a slow washout of contrast, confirming the diagnosis and location for embolization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Patients With Acute Lower Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2016) recommends endoscopic therapy as first-line for stable patients with identifiable bleeding sources, and angiography with embolization for unstable patients or those failing endoscopic therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Left hemicolectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Angio-embolization | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Endoscopic laser ablation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: Stable > C, Unstable > B.) Stable > C, Unstable > B.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
