  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Vomit hard, bleed bright, Mallory-Weiss takes flight.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Mallory-Weiss tear. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the patient's history of forceful vomiting following food poisoning, which then led to blood vomiting and epigastric pain. This sequence of events is classic for a Mallory-Weiss tear.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMallory-Weiss syndrome involves a longitudinal mucosal tear at the gastroesophageal junction, typically caused by a sudden increase in intra-abdominal pressure from forceful vomiting or retching. The rapid pressure changes can lead to a laceration of the mucosa and submucosa, often involving small arteries, resulting in hematemesis. The tear is usually non-transmural, differentiating it from the more severe Boerhaave's syndrome.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Peptic ulcer) (Incorrect): While peptic ulcers can cause epigastric pain and hematemesis, the preceding history of forceful vomiting is the key differentiator pointing away from a primary peptic ulcer bleed. Peptic ulcer bleeding typically does not have such a clear precipitating event of severe emesis, although vomiting can occur secondary to the ulcer itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Mallory-Weiss Tear | Peptic Ulcer | Esophageal Varices |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Forceful vomiting/retching | H. pylori, NSAIDs, stress | Portal hypertension (cirrhosis) |\n| **Bleeding** | Arterial, usually self-limiting | Arterial/venous, can be severe | Venous, often massive, life-threatening |\n| **Pain** | Epigastric/chest, often post-emesis | Epigastric, burning, relieved by food/antacids | Often painless, but can have discomfort |\n| **Key History** | Preceding emesis, alcohol abuse | Chronic dyspepsia, NSAID use, H. pylori | Liver disease, alcoholism, jaundice |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Forceful vomiting + hematemesis = Mallory-Weiss until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy is the diagnostic modality of choice, revealing a linear, non-circumferential mucosal tear, typically at the gastroesophageal junction. Active bleeding or a visible vessel may be seen within the tear.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Patients With Acute Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2021). This guideline recommends early endoscopy for diagnosis and management of upper GI bleeding, including Mallory-Weiss tears.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Mallory Weiss | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Peptic ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
