  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Adult intussusception: find the cause, cut it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is surgical resection. Adult intussusception is a rare condition, and unlike its pediatric counterpart, it is almost always secondary to an underlying pathological lead point, which is frequently malignant. Therefore, definitive surgical resection of the involved segment of bowel, including the lead point, is the standard of care.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdult intussusception differs significantly from pediatric intussusception in its etiology and management. In adults, a lead point is identified in 70-90% of cases, with malignancy accounting for a substantial proportion (e.g., adenocarcinoma, lymphoma, carcinoid tumors). Attempting reduction without resection risks leaving behind a malignant or potentially malignant lesion, leading to recurrence, delayed diagnosis, or metastatic spread. Surgical resection ensures complete removal of the pathological lead point and any compromised bowel, providing both definitive treatment and histological diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (barium enema) (Incorrect): While a barium or air enema can be diagnostic for intussusception, it is rarely therapeutic in adults. The underlying lead point prevents successful reduction, and there is a risk of perforation, especially with compromised bowel or a rigid mass.\nOption C (surgical reduction) (Incorrect): Surgical reduction alone without resection is generally contraindicated in adult intussusception. Reducing the intussusception without removing the lead point, particularly if it's malignant, can lead to tumor seeding, recurrence, or missing the opportunity for curative resection.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pediatric Intussusception | Adult Intussusception |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------- | :-------------------------------- |\n| Incidence | Common (3-12 months) | Rare (<5% of all intussusceptions) |\n| Lead Point | Usually none (idiopathic) | Almost always present (70-90%) |\n| Etiology | Viral illness, Peyer's patches | Neoplasm (benign/malignant), polyp, Meckel's |\n| Initial Management | Enema reduction (air/hydrostatic) | Surgical resection |\n| Recurrence after reduction | Higher (10-15%) | High if lead point not removed |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adult intussusception = always resect the lead point.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, a CT scan is the diagnostic modality of choice, typically revealing a 'target sign' or 'sausage-shaped mass' with mesenteric fat and vessels trapped within the intussusceptum. Intraoperatively, a palpable, often firm, mass will be found at the apex of the intussusception, with varying degrees of bowel edema and congestion, necessitating en bloc resection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWhile no single society guideline specifically addresses adult intussusception management in detail, general surgical principles for bowel obstruction and oncologic resection, as outlined by organizations like the American College of Surgeons (ACS), guide the approach, emphasizing definitive surgical management for underlying pathology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | barium enema | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | surgical resection | ✅ Correct |\n| C | surgical reduction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
