  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Time is tissue: heparinize first, image next, revascularize fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nHeparin is the correct initial step. The patient's presentation of unilateral leg swelling and pain with intact femoral but absent peripheral pulses is highly suggestive of acute limb ischemia, necessitating immediate anticoagulation to prevent clot propagation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute limb ischemia (ALI) is a time-sensitive emergency characterized by the sudden decrease in limb perfusion, threatening limb viability. The classic \"6 Ps\" (pain, pallor, pulselessness, paresthesia, paralysis, poikilothermia) are key diagnostic indicators. In this scenario, the intact femoral pulse but absent peripheral pulses point to a distal arterial occlusion. Immediate intravenous unfractionated heparin is crucial to prevent thrombus propagation, preserve collateral flow, and buy time for definitive diagnostic imaging and revascularization, thereby improving limb salvage rates.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (morphine) (Incorrect): Morphine provides symptomatic pain relief but does not address the underlying limb-threatening ischemia. It is not the *next step* for limb salvage.\nOption C (CT angiography) (Incorrect): While CT angiography is the definitive diagnostic imaging for ALI, immediate anticoagulation with heparin should be initiated *prior to* or *concurrently with* imaging to prevent further clot propagation and irreversible tissue damage.\nOption D (venous duplex) (Incorrect): A venous duplex ultrasound is used to diagnose deep vein thrombosis (DVT). The patient's presentation, particularly the absent peripheral pulses, is indicative of arterial, not venous, pathology.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Limb Ischemia (ALI) | Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pathophysiology | Arterial occlusion (embolus, thrombosis) | Venous thrombus formation |\n| Classic Signs | 6 Ps: Pain, Pallor, Pulselessness, Paresthesia, Paralysis, Poikilothermia | Swelling, pain, warmth, erythema, Homan's sign (unreliable) |\n| Pulses | Absent or diminished distal to occlusion | Usually intact, may be difficult to palpate due to edema |\n| Initial Management | Immediate IV unfractionated heparin | Anticoagulation (heparin, LMWH, DOACs) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Acute limb ischemia demands immediate heparin to save the limb.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT angiography would reveal the exact location and extent of the arterial occlusion, showing a filling defect within the arterial lumen. An intraoperative angiogram would confirm the occlusion and guide revascularization strategies like embolectomy or bypass.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe 2016 American Heart Association (AHA) / American College of Cardiology (ACC) Guideline on the Management of Patients With Lower Extremity Peripheral Artery Disease recommends immediate anticoagulation with unfractionated heparin for patients with acute limb ischemia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | heparin | ✅ Correct |\n| B | morphine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CT angiography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | venous duplex | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
