  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When infection strikes a pseudocyst, drain it, don't cut it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is percutaneous drainage. An infected pancreatic pseudocyst requires prompt drainage to control sepsis. Percutaneous drainage offers the least invasive and often preferred initial approach for source control in this setting.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPercutaneous drainage provides a direct, minimally invasive route to decompress and decontaminate an infected fluid collection. It allows for removal of infected fluid and debris, often with continuous irrigation, without the significant morbidity associated with open surgical intervention in an inflamed and potentially septic patient. This approach effectively controls the infection while minimizing physiological stress, which is paramount in managing critically ill patients with pancreatic infections.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Surgical resection is a highly morbid procedure and is not indicated for the management of an infected pancreatic pseudocyst. The goal is drainage and source control, not removal of the pancreatic tissue.\nOption C (Incorrect): Internal drainage (e.g., cystogastrostomy, cystojejunostomy) is typically reserved for symptomatic, mature, non-infected pseudocysts. Performing internal drainage on an actively infected pseudocyst carries a high risk of anastomotic leak, sepsis, and peritonitis due to the inflamed and friable tissues.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Pseudocyst Type | Key Feature | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Asymptomatic, small (<6cm), early (<6 weeks) | Observation | Expectant management |\n| Symptomatic, large (>6cm), mature, non-infected | Well-formed wall | Endoscopic or surgical internal drainage |\n| Infected | Signs of sepsis, gas bubbles on imaging | Percutaneous drainage |\n| Walled-off necrosis (WON) | Heterogeneous collection with solid debris | Endoscopic necrosectomy/drainage or surgical debridement |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Infected pseudocyst? Drain it percutaneously first!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, an infected pseudocyst typically appears as a well-defined, encapsulated fluid collection, often with gas bubbles within the collection or surrounding inflammatory changes. Percutaneous drainage involves placing a pigtail catheter into this collection under CT or ultrasound guidance to aspirate fluid and allow for continuous drainage.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for the management of severe acute pancreatitis (2019) recommend percutaneous drainage as the first-line treatment for infected pancreatic fluid collections, including pseudocysts, especially in unstable patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | percutaneous drainage | ✅ Correct |\n| B | surgical resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Internal drainage | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
