  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Malignant phyllodes: Go big or go home (with recurrence).**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Mastectomy. Malignant phyllodes tumors are characterized by aggressive local behavior and a high risk of local recurrence, making mastectomy the preferred surgical approach for optimal local control, even in the absence of lymph node involvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant phyllodes tumors are stromal tumors of the breast with a propensity for rapid growth and local recurrence. While they rarely metastasize to lymph nodes, their aggressive local nature necessitates wide surgical excision. Mastectomy provides the widest possible margins, significantly reducing the high local recurrence rates (up to 25-30%) associated with less extensive resections, thereby ensuring the best chance for disease-free survival from a local perspective.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (WLE) (Incorrect): Wide Local Excision (WLE) is generally insufficient for malignant phyllodes tumors due to their high local recurrence rate, even with seemingly clear margins. It is typically reserved for benign or select borderline cases.\nOption C (Radiotherapy) (Incorrect): Radiotherapy is not a primary treatment for malignant phyllodes tumors. It may be considered as adjuvant therapy in specific high-risk situations (e.g., large tumors, positive margins after mastectomy) but is not the definitive surgical management.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Local Recurrence Risk (WLE) | Recommended Surgical Treatment | Adjuvant Therapy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Benign Phyllodes | Low (<10%) | WLE with 1 cm margin | None |\n| Borderline Phyllodes | Moderate (10-20%) | WLE with 1 cm margin | Consider RT if margins close/positive |\n| Malignant Phyllodes | High (20-30%) | Mastectomy (or WLE with >1 cm margin if feasible) | Consider RT if margins positive/large tumor |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Malignant phyllodes = Mastectomy for local control.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (mammogram/ultrasound), malignant phyllodes tumors often appear as rapidly growing, large, lobulated masses with cystic areas. Intraoperatively, they are typically firm, often encapsulated, and can be quite bulky, sometimes with areas of necrosis or hemorrhage, reflecting their aggressive nature.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer, Version 1.2024, recommend wide local excision with at least 1 cm margins for benign and borderline phyllodes tumors. For malignant phyllodes, mastectomy is often recommended, especially for larger tumors or when adequate margins cannot be achieved with WLE, to minimize local recurrence. Adjuvant radiation therapy may be considered for large tumors or positive margins.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | WLE | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mastectomy | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Radiotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
