  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Benign phyllodes: Excise wide, keep it tidy.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Wide local excision. Benign phyllodes tumors are biphasic tumors of the breast with both epithelial and stromal components. Although benign, they have a propensity for local recurrence if not adequately excised, making wide local excision the standard of care.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhyllodes tumors, even benign ones, are characterized by stromal overgrowth and a leaf-like architecture. The key to successful management is complete surgical removal with clear margins to prevent local recurrence. Wide local excision achieves this by removing the tumor with a surrounding rim of healthy tissue, typically aiming for a 1 cm margin. This approach balances oncologic control with breast conservation, as these tumors do not metastasize when benign, but can grow aggressively locally.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Wide local excision with radio) (Incorrect): Adjuvant radiation therapy is generally not indicated for benign phyllodes tumors. It may be considered for borderline or malignant phyllodes, especially with positive margins or large tumor size, but not for benign.\nOption C (Mastectomy) (Incorrect): Mastectomy is an overtreatment for a benign phyllodes tumor. It is reserved for very large tumors, recurrent malignant or borderline phyllodes, or when clear margins cannot be achieved with breast-conserving surgery.\nOption D (Reassurance) (Incorrect): Reassurance is insufficient. Benign phyllodes tumors have growth potential and a risk of local recurrence if left untreated, and they can rarely progress to borderline or malignant forms. Surgical excision is mandatory.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Benign Phyllodes | Borderline Phyllodes | Malignant Phyllodes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Stromal Overgrowth** | Mild to moderate | Moderate to marked | Marked, often atypical |\n| **Mitotic Activity** | <5 mitoses/10 HPF | 5-9 mitoses/10 HPF | >10 mitoses/10 HPF |\n| **Stromal Atypia** | Mild or absent | Moderate | Marked |\n| **Margins** | Well-circumscribed | Infiltrative | Infiltrative |\n| **Management** | Wide local excision | Wide local excision (consider radiation for positive margins) | Wide local excision or mastectomy (consider radiation/chemo) |\n| **Metastasis Risk** | Rare | Rare | Up to 20-30% (hematogenous) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Benign phyllodes require wide excision, not just observation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, phyllodes tumors often appear as well-circumscribed, lobulated masses. Ultrasound may show a solid, hypoechoic mass with cystic areas. Intraoperatively, they are typically firm, mobile, and well-demarcated, often with a 'leaf-like' appearance on cut section, which gives them their name.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024) recommend wide local excision with negative margins for phyllodes tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Wide local excision | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Wide local excision with radio | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Reassurance | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
