  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When LFTs rise, stop the drug, don't rush the knife.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is to stop methotrexate. This patient presents with elevated liver function tests (LFTs) and a liver lesion while on methotrexate, a known hepatotoxic drug. Addressing potential drug-induced liver injury is the critical first step before considering further invasive management for the liver lesion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMethotrexate is a commonly prescribed disease-modifying antirheumatic drug (DMARD) for rheumatoid arthritis, but it carries a significant risk of hepatotoxicity, manifesting as elevated LFTs. Regular monitoring of LFTs is essential for patients on this medication. When LFTs are significantly elevated, especially in the presence of a new liver lesion, the immediate and most appropriate action is to discontinue the suspected offending agent. This allows for assessment of liver enzyme normalization, helping to differentiate drug-induced injury from other potential liver pathologies and guiding subsequent management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Resection of the liver is a major surgical intervention and is premature at this stage. A 5cm hypodense lesion requires further characterization (e.g., contrast-enhanced CT or MRI, and potentially biopsy) to determine its nature (benign vs. malignant) before considering surgical resection. Rushing to surgery without first ruling out a reversible cause like drug-induced liver injury is inappropriate and potentially harmful.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature                 | Methotrexate Hepatotoxicity                               | Liver Lesion Workup                                     | RA Management (General)                               |\n| :---------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------ | :---------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Cause**               | Drug-induced (dose-dependent, idiosyncratic)              | Varied (benign, malignant, inflammatory, infectious)    | Autoimmune disease                                    |\n| **Monitoring**          | Regular LFTs (ALT, AST, albumin), CBC, creatinine         | Imaging (US, CT, MRI), tumor markers, biopsy            | Disease activity scores, inflammatory markers, imaging |\n| **Initial Management**  | Discontinue MTX, supportive care, rule out other causes   | Characterize lesion, rule out drug-induced injury       | DMARDs, biologics, symptom management                 |\n| **Definitive Treatment**| Resolution after MTX cessation, potentially liver biopsy  | Resection, ablation, chemotherapy, observation          | Long-term medication, physical therapy, surgery       |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always rule out drug-induced injury before invasive liver lesion workup.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a hypodense lesion appears darker than the surrounding liver parenchyma, indicating it is less echogenic. This is a non-specific finding and could represent a variety of pathologies including cysts, hemangiomas, metastases, or hepatocellular carcinoma. Further characterization with contrast-enhanced CT or MRI would be essential to narrow the differential diagnosis and guide further management.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Rheumatology (ACR) Guidelines for the Management of Rheumatoid Arthritis (e.g., 2021). These guidelines recommend regular monitoring of LFTs in patients on methotrexate and provide recommendations for dose adjustment or discontinuation in cases of elevated liver enzymes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Stop methotrexate. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Resection of liver. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
