  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let pregnancy mask the appendix; it's still a surgical emergency!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Appendicitis. In a 16-week pregnant female presenting with right lower quadrant (RLQ) pain, nausea, and vomiting, after ruling out pregnancy-related causes, appendicitis is the most common non-obstetric surgical emergency and aligns well with the classic presentation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAppendicitis in pregnancy presents a diagnostic challenge due to the gravid uterus displacing the appendix superiorly and laterally, which can alter the classic RLQ pain location. Nausea and vomiting are common in both early pregnancy and appendicitis, further complicating diagnosis. However, persistent, localized abdominal pain, often with guarding or rebound tenderness, even if the location is atypical, should raise suspicion. Early diagnosis and surgical intervention are crucial to prevent perforation, which significantly increases maternal and fetal morbidity and mortality.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Gastritis): Incorrect. Gastritis typically causes epigastric pain, not RLQ pain. While nausea and vomiting can occur, the pain location is inconsistent with the primary complaint.\nOption B (Pancreatitis): Incorrect. Pancreatitis presents with severe epigastric pain, often radiating to the back, not primarily RLQ pain. Although nausea and vomiting are common, the pain location is distinct.\nOption C (Cholecystitis): Incorrect. Cholecystitis typically causes right upper quadrant (RUQ) pain, often radiating to the right shoulder or back, not RLQ pain. While associated with nausea and vomiting, the pain location is different.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Typical Pain Location | Associated Symptoms | Diagnostic Approach |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Appendicitis | RLQ (can be higher in pregnancy) | Nausea, vomiting, anorexia, fever | US, MRI (preferred in pregnancy) |\n| Pyelonephritis | Flank pain, CVA tenderness | Dysuria, fever, chills, nausea | Urinalysis, urine culture, US |\n| Ovarian Torsion | Sudden, severe unilateral lower abdominal pain | Nausea, vomiting | US with Doppler |\n| Ectopic Pregnancy (ruptured) | Unilateral lower abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding | Syncope, shoulder pain | hCG, transvaginal US |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: RLQ pain in pregnancy? Appendicitis until proven otherwise, even if atypical.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a non-compressible, dilated appendix (>6mm diameter) with a target sign and periappendiceal fluid/fat stranding may be seen. MRI is the preferred imaging modality in pregnancy, showing an inflamed appendix. Intraoperatively, a hyperemic, edematous, or purulent appendix would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 178 (2017) on Appendicitis in Pregnancy recommends graded compression ultrasound as the initial imaging modality, followed by MRI if ultrasound is inconclusive.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Appendicitis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
