  "question": "Pt with hx of IHD with no fever, low CO, low wedge pressure and normal Rt ventricular pressure. What’s the type of shock?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Septic",
    "B": "Cardiogenic",
    "C": "Anaphylactic",
    "D": "Hypovolemic"
  },
  "answer": "D) D",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the tank is empty, the pump can't fill.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Hypovolemic shock. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the classic hemodynamic profile of low cardiac output and low wedge pressure, which together indicate inadequate preload. The normal right ventricular pressure further rules out primary right heart failure or obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypovolemic shock results from a significant reduction in intravascular volume, leading to decreased venous return to the heart. This reduced preload directly causes a fall in end-diastolic volume and pressure, manifesting as a low pulmonary capillary wedge pressure (PCWP). Consequently, stroke volume and cardiac output are diminished. The body attempts to compensate by increasing systemic vascular resistance (SVR) to maintain blood pressure, but without adequate volume, CO remains low.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Septic) (Incorrect): Septic shock is a distributive shock characterized by vasodilation, often leading to a high cardiac output (in early stages) and low systemic vascular resistance, not low CO and low PCWP.\nOption B (Cardiogenic) (Incorrect): Cardiogenic shock is a pump failure, resulting in low cardiac output but *high* pulmonary capillary wedge pressure due to fluid backing up in the pulmonary circulation.\nOption C (Anaphylactic) (Incorrect): Anaphylactic shock is also a distributive shock, characterized by massive vasodilation and increased capillary permeability, leading to low systemic vascular resistance and often a high cardiac output in the initial phases, not low CO and low PCWP.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Shock Type | Cardiac Output (CO) | PCWP (Preload) | SVR (Afterload) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Hypovolemic | Low | Low | High |\n| Cardiogenic | Low | High | High |\n| Septic (early) | High | Low/Normal | Low |\n| Anaphylactic | High | Low/Normal | Low |\n| Obstructive | Low | Variable (often high) | High |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Low CO + Low Wedge = Low Volume.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn point-of-care ultrasound, you might see a 'kissing ventricle' sign (ventricular walls touching during systole) or a small, underfilled inferior vena cava (IVC) that collapses significantly with inspiration, indicating severe hypovolemia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 10th Edition (2018) recommends rapid identification and fluid resuscitation for hypovolemic shock.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Septic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cardiogenic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Anaphylactic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hypovolemic | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "D"
