  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sarcoma spreads to lungs; chest CT is your staging compass.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is CT of the chest. For a patient diagnosed with thigh sarcoma, evaluating for distant metastases is a critical component of staging, and the lungs are the most common site of hematogenous spread for soft tissue sarcomas.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSoft tissue sarcomas are aggressive mesenchymal tumors that primarily metastasize via the bloodstream. The lungs are the most frequent site for these distant metastases, making a CT of the chest an indispensable tool for accurate staging. Detecting pulmonary nodules indicative of metastatic disease significantly impacts prognosis, guides treatment decisions (e.g., neoadjuvant therapy, surgical resection of metastases), and determines the overall management strategy for the patient.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Bone scan. Bone scans are primarily used to detect bone metastases, which are a less common site of spread for soft tissue sarcomas compared to the lungs. While some sarcomas can metastasize to bone, it is not the primary or most critical initial staging investigation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Primary Purpose in Sarcoma Staging | Common Metastatic Site Detected |\n|--------------------|------------------------------------|---------------------------------|\n| CT Chest           | Detect pulmonary metastases        | Lungs                           |\n| MRI Primary Site   | Local tumor extent, resectability  | N/A (local assessment)          |\n| Bone Scan          | Detect bone metastases             | Bone (less common for STS)      |\n| PET/CT             | Detect distant metastases, assess metabolic activity | Various (can be used for overall staging) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sarcoma staging = Chest CT for lung mets.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a CT of the chest, you would be looking for pulmonary nodules, which can range from small, solitary lesions to multiple, larger masses, indicative of metastatic disease. These nodules typically appear as well-defined, rounded opacities within the lung parenchyma.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (2023). NCCN guidelines recommend chest CT with IV contrast for all patients with high-grade or large (>5 cm) soft tissue sarcomas for staging purposes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bone scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT of the chest | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
