  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the leg swells but the pulse still beats, ultrasound the veins, not the streets!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Doppler venous. Left leg swelling with intact distal pulses strongly suggests a venous pathology, most commonly deep vein thrombosis (DVT), making venous Doppler ultrasound the gold standard first-line investigation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLeg swelling, particularly unilateral, with intact distal pulses, points away from acute arterial occlusion and towards venous obstruction or insufficiency. Deep vein thrombosis (DVT) is a critical diagnosis due to the risk of pulmonary embolism. Venous Doppler ultrasound is highly sensitive and specific for DVT, allowing direct visualization of thrombus, assessment of vein compressibility, and evaluation of venous flow dynamics. Its non-invasive nature, portability, and lack of radiation exposure make it the preferred initial diagnostic modality.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Doppler arterial) (Incorrect): Intact distal pulses indicate that major arterial flow to the limb is preserved, making primary arterial occlusion an unlikely cause of the swelling. Arterial Doppler would be indicated for suspected arterial insufficiency or occlusion.\nOption C (CT angio) (Incorrect): CT angiography is primarily used to visualize arterial structures and is not the first-line investigation for suspected DVT. It involves radiation and contrast, and while it can show large venous thrombi, it's less sensitive for calf DVTs and not as readily available as ultrasound.\nOption D (CT venum) (Incorrect): Assuming \"CT venum\" refers to CT venography, this is a more invasive test involving intravenous contrast and radiation. While it can diagnose DVT, it is typically reserved for cases where ultrasound is inconclusive or technically difficult, or for evaluating central venous structures, not as a first-line investigation for peripheral DVT.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Investigation | Primary Indication | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Venous Doppler US | Suspected DVT, venous insufficiency | Non-invasive, no radiation, portable, high sensitivity/specificity for DVT | Operator dependent, less effective for pelvic/central veins |\n| Arterial Doppler US | Suspected arterial occlusion/insufficiency | Non-invasive, no radiation, assesses arterial flow | Does not evaluate venous system |\n| CT Angiography | Arterial aneurysm, stenosis, dissection | Detailed arterial anatomy, 3D reconstruction | Radiation, contrast nephropathy risk, less sensitive for DVT |\n| CT Venography | Central DVT, complex venous anatomy, inconclusive US | Detailed venous anatomy, can assess surrounding structures | Radiation, contrast nephropathy risk, not first-line for peripheral DVT |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unilateral leg swelling + intact pulses = think DVT, get venous Doppler.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a venous Doppler ultrasound, a DVT appears as an incompressible vein lumen containing echogenic material (thrombus) that partially or completely obstructs blood flow, with absent or blunted flow signals.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines (e.g., 2016 CHEST Guideline and Expert Panel Report on Antithrombotic Therapy for VTE Disease). They recommend venous compression ultrasonography as the initial diagnostic test for suspected DVT.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Doppler venous | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Doppler arterial | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CT angio | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | CT venum | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
