  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A 5 cm adrenal mass? Just take it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is adrenalectomy. A 5 cm adrenal mass, even if hormonally inactive and appearing hypodense/lipid-rich on CT, warrants surgical removal due to its size and the inherent risk of malignancy. The size of the mass is the primary driver for intervention in this scenario.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdrenal masses greater than 4-6 cm, regardless of their functional status or initial imaging characteristics (unless unequivocally benign like a myelolipoma with macroscopic fat), have a significant risk of malignancy (adrenocortical carcinoma). While hypodense and lipid tissue can suggest an adenoma, a 5 cm size pushes it into the surgical indication category. Surgical resection (adrenalectomy) is indicated to definitively diagnose and treat potential malignancy, as well as to prevent local complications from mass effect.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Reassurance is inappropriate for a 5 cm adrenal mass, as it carries a significant risk of malignancy requiring further evaluation and intervention.\nOption B (Incorrect): Imaging-guided biopsy is generally discouraged for adrenal masses unless there is strong suspicion of metastatic disease from a known primary, or lymphoma, and the results would change management. Biopsy of a primary adrenocortical carcinoma can lead to tumor seeding and is often non-diagnostic for benign vs. malignant adrenocortical lesions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Adrenal Mass Characteristic | Management | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Non-functional, < 4 cm, benign imaging | Observation (serial imaging) | Low malignancy risk, often adenoma |\n| Non-functional, 4-6 cm | Adrenalectomy often recommended | Intermediate malignancy risk, definitive diagnosis |\n| Non-functional, > 6 cm | Adrenalectomy | High malignancy risk (up to 25% ACC) |\n| Any size, functional | Adrenalectomy | Symptomatic, potential for complications (e.g., hypertensive crisis) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Size matters for adrenal masses; >4cm often means surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, hypodense and lipid-rich tissue suggests an adenoma, but this finding alone does not rule out malignancy in a large mass. Adrenocortical carcinomas can sometimes have areas of lipid. Intraoperatively, a large, firm, or irregular adrenal mass would raise suspicion for malignancy, necessitating complete resection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Adrenal Tumors (2019). These guidelines recommend surgical resection for non-functional adrenal masses >4 cm due to increased malignancy risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | reassure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Imaging guided biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | adrenalectomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
