  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Numb upper lip after sinus roof biopsy? Think infraorbital, not infratrochlear!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe answer is ACCEPT. The infraorbital nerve is correctly identified as the affected nerve because its anatomical course through the roof of the maxillary sinus makes it vulnerable during biopsy, leading to sensory loss in the lower eyelid and upper lip.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe infraorbital nerve, a terminal branch of the maxillary nerve (V2), traverses the infraorbital canal within the roof of the maxillary sinus before exiting the infraorbital foramen. This close anatomical proximity means any surgical manipulation or biopsy of the sinus roof places the nerve at high risk of injury. Its sensory distribution precisely matches the described symptoms: the lower eyelid, upper lip, and ala of the nose.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The infratrochlear nerve is a branch of the nasociliary nerve (V1) and supplies sensation to the medial upper eyelid, side of the nose, and lacrimal sac. Its anatomical location and sensory distribution do not align with injury during a maxillary sinus roof biopsy or the described symptoms of lower eyelid and upper lip numbness.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Sensory Distribution | Relation to Maxillary Sinus |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Infraorbital Nerve | Maxillary Nerve (V2) | Lower eyelid, upper lip, ala of nose, cheek | Travels in infraorbital canal within the roof of the maxillary sinus |\n| Infratrochlear Nerve | Nasociliary Nerve (V1) | Medial upper eyelid, side of nose, lacrimal sac | Not directly associated with the maxillary sinus roof |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Maxillary sinus roof injury = infraorbital nerve risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the infraorbital canal can be visualized as a bony ridge or prominence on the superior wall (roof) of the maxillary sinus. On CT imaging, the infraorbital canal is clearly seen traversing the roof of the maxillary sinus, making it a critical landmark to identify preoperatively to prevent iatrogenic injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific guideline directly addresses this precise anatomical injury, but fundamental surgical anatomy principles, as outlined in standard texts like \"Gray's Anatomy\" or \"Netter's Atlas of Human Anatomy,\" are paramount for safe surgical practice.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | infraorbital | ✅ Correct |\n| B | infratrochlear | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
