  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't cut it out until you know what it is!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is core biopsy. Despite mammography showing an intraductal papilloma, red nipple discharge warrants further tissue sampling to definitively rule out associated atypia or malignancy, which can coexist with papillomas.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraductal papillomas are benign epithelial proliferations within a breast duct, often presenting with nipple discharge. While typically benign, they can be associated with atypical ductal hyperplasia (ADH), ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS), or even invasive carcinoma. Core biopsy, often guided by ultrasound or stereotaxis, provides histological tissue for definitive diagnosis, allowing for appropriate surgical planning. This approach avoids unnecessary surgery if the lesion is benign and guides the extent of surgery if malignancy or atypia is found.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Central duct excision) (Incorrect): Central duct excision is a therapeutic procedure, not a primary diagnostic one in this scenario. Performing an excision without a definitive tissue diagnosis from a biopsy risks either under-treating a malignancy or over-treating a benign lesion. It is typically reserved for persistent troublesome discharge after benign biopsy, or for known malignancy/atypia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Purpose | Indication |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mammography/Ultrasound | Imaging diagnosis/localization | Initial evaluation of breast symptoms, screening |\n| Core Biopsy | Histological diagnosis | Suspicious lesions on imaging, nipple discharge with imaging correlation, to rule out atypia/malignancy |\n| Central Duct Excision | Therapeutic/Diagnostic (excisional) | Persistent troublesome nipple discharge after benign biopsy, known atypia/malignancy requiring excision |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Biopsy before excision for definitive diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, an intraductal papilloma might appear as a circumscribed mass or ductal ectasia. Ultrasound often shows an intraductal mass within a dilated duct, sometimes with internal vascularity. Core biopsy is typically performed under ultrasound guidance for visible lesions or stereotactic guidance for microcalcifications or non-palpable lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBrS) Consensus Guideline on the Management of Benign Breast Disease (2016) recommends tissue sampling for intraductal papillomas, especially those associated with atypia. NCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer Screening and Diagnosis also support tissue diagnosis for suspicious lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Core biopsy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Central duct excision | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
