  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When gallstones cause pain, take the gallbladder out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: The correct answer is A, laparoscopic cholecystectomy. This patient presents with classic symptoms of biliary colic due to gallstones, and laparoscopic cholecystectomy is the definitive treatment for symptomatic cholelithiasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBiliary colic occurs when a gallstone transiently obstructs the cystic duct, leading to gallbladder distension and pain. The pain typically resolves as the stone dislodges. Laparoscopic cholecystectomy removes the source of the problem, preventing recurrent episodes of pain and potential complications like acute cholecystitis, choledocholithiasis, or gallstone pancreatitis. It is a minimally invasive procedure with excellent outcomes for symptomatic cholelithiasis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Ursodeoxycholic) (Incorrect): Ursodeoxycholic acid is used for dissolving cholesterol gallstones, but it is a slow process, not always effective, and not the primary treatment for symptomatic cholelithiasis, especially when surgical candidacy is not an issue. \nOption C (Observation) (Incorrect): Observation is appropriate for asymptomatic gallstones. This patient is clearly symptomatic with severe RUQ pain, making observation an inappropriate and potentially harmful management strategy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Symptoms | US Findings | Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Asymptomatic Cholelithiasis | None | Gallstones, normal GB wall | Observation |\n| Biliary Colic | RUQ pain after fatty meal, resolves | Gallstones, normal GB wall | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy |\n| Acute Cholecystitis | Persistent RUQ pain (>6 hrs), fever, leukocytosis | Gallstones, GB wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, Murphy's sign | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy (urgent/emergent) |\n| Choledocholithiasis | Jaundice, cholangitis, pancreatitis | CBD dilation, stone in CBD | ERCP +/- Lap Chole |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Symptomatic gallstones = cholecystectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, multiple gallstones are seen within the gallbladder lumen. A normal gallbladder wall thickness (<3mm) and absence of pericholecystic fluid or sonographic Murphy's sign differentiate biliary colic from acute cholecystitis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Surgical Management of Gallstones (2019) recommend laparoscopic cholecystectomy for symptomatic cholelithiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | lap chole | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Ursodeoxycholic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Observation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
