  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Vision loss in hyperprolactinemia? Image the brain, stat!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 'Blurred vision'. This answer is correct because visual disturbances, such as blurred vision, are a classic symptom of mass effect from a pituitary adenoma, which is the most common cause of pathological hyperprolactinemia, necessitating brain MRI.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHyperprolactinemia can be caused by a prolactin-secreting pituitary adenoma (prolactinoma). Large prolactinomas (macroprolactinomas) can grow out of the sella turcica and compress adjacent structures, most notably the optic chiasm. Compression of the optic chiasm leads to characteristic visual field defects, such as bitemporal hemianopsia, which can manifest as blurred vision or other visual disturbances. An MRI of the brain is the gold standard for evaluating the pituitary gland and surrounding structures to identify and characterize such adenomas and assess their impact on the optic chiasm.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 'Double of serum prolactin' is incorrect. While significantly elevated prolactin levels (e.g., >200 ng/mL) are highly suggestive of a macroprolactinoma and often warrant imaging, the *degree* of elevation alone is not the primary trigger for imaging in all cases. Clinical symptoms of mass effect, such as visual changes, are a direct and urgent indication for MRI regardless of the exact prolactin level, as they signify potential neurological compromise.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication for MRI in Hyperprolactinemia | Clinical Presentation | Prolactin Level |\n|---|---|---|\n| Visual symptoms | Blurred vision, diplopia, visual field defects | Any hyperprolactinemia |\n| Neurological symptoms | Headache, cranial nerve palsies | Any hyperprolactinemia |\n| Markedly elevated prolactin | Asymptomatic, but >200 ng/mL | >200 ng/mL (suggests macroprolactinoma) |\n| Persistent hyperprolactinemia | Despite medical therapy | Any hyperprolactinemia |\n| Pituitary apoplexy | Sudden headache, visual loss, ophthalmoplegia | Variable, often acute |\n| Pre-surgical planning | Confirmed adenoma requiring intervention | Any hyperprolactinemia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Visual symptoms in hyperprolactinemia demand MRI to rule out optic chiasm compression.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAn MRI of the brain would reveal a pituitary mass (adenoma) in the sella turcica, potentially with suprasellar extension and compression or displacement of the optic chiasm, confirming the need for intervention.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Hyperprolactinemia (2011) recommends MRI for all patients with hyperprolactinemia to exclude a pituitary adenoma or other sellar mass.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Blurred vision | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Double of serum prolactin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
