  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Vomit hard, get air in your neck, think Boerhaave's.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. This answer is correct because the patient's presentation of sudden upper abdominal pain and vomiting followed by supraclavicular subcutaneous emphysema is the classic presentation of Boerhaave's syndrome, an esophageal rupture.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBoerhaave's syndrome is a spontaneous transmural rupture of the esophagus, typically occurring after a sudden increase in intraesophageal pressure, such as from forceful vomiting or retching. The rupture most commonly occurs in the left posterolateral aspect of the distal esophagus. Air and gastric contents leak into the mediastinum, leading to mediastinitis and pneumomediastinum. The air can then dissect superiorly into the neck, manifesting as subcutaneous emphysema, which is a highly specific sign for esophageal perforation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Esophagitis is inflammation of the esophagus and does not cause sudden subcutaneous emphysema or transmural rupture.\nOption B (Incorrect): Acute gastritis is inflammation of the stomach lining and does not explain the presence of subcutaneous emphysema, which indicates an air leak from a visceral perforation.\nOption C (Incorrect): Perforated peptic ulcer causes acute abdominal pain and peritonitis due to leakage of gastric or duodenal contents into the peritoneal cavity. While severe, it does not typically lead to supraclavicular subcutaneous emphysema, which points to a mediastinal air leak.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Boerhaave's Syndrome | Mallory-Weiss Tear | Perforated Peptic Ulcer |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Pathology** | Transmural esophageal rupture | Mucosal/submucosal esophageal tear | Full-thickness gastric/duodenal wall defect |\n| **Cause** | Forceful vomiting/retching | Forceful vomiting/retching | H. pylori, NSAIDs |\n| **Key Symptom** | Severe chest/epigastric pain, subcutaneous emphysema | Hematemesis (bright red blood) | Sudden severe epigastric pain, peritonitis |\n| **Location** | Distal esophagus (left posterolateral) | Gastroesophageal junction | Stomach or duodenum |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Vomiting + subcutaneous emphysema = Boerhaave's until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nChest X-ray may show pneumomediastinum, pleural effusion (often left-sided), or pneumothorax. CT scan of the chest and abdomen is highly sensitive for pneumomediastinum, pleural fluid, and direct visualization of the esophageal wall defect. A water-soluble contrast esophagram can confirm the diagnosis by demonstrating extravasation of contrast.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Esophageal Perforations (2019) recommend early diagnosis and tailored management based on perforation size, location, and patient stability.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | esophagitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | acute gastritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | perforated peptic ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | boerhaav’s syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
