  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't give morphine to a spastic sphincter!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Sphincter of Oddi dysfunction (SOD). The classic presentation of colicky upper abdominal pain, aggravation by morphine (which causes sphincter spasm), and imaging showing dilated CBD and intrahepatic ducts strongly points to SOD.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSphincter of Oddi Dysfunction (SOD) is a motility disorder characterized by intermittent obstruction to bile and/or pancreatic flow due to spasm or stenosis of the sphincter of Oddi. Morphine and its derivatives are known to cause contraction of the sphincter of Oddi, thereby exacerbating pain in patients with SOD. The resulting increased pressure within the biliary system leads to colicky pain and dilation of the common bile duct and intrahepatic ducts, as seen on ultrasound.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Pancreatitis) (Incorrect): While pancreatitis can cause upper abdominal pain, the classic presentation includes elevated amylase/lipase and often radiates to the back. The specific aggravation by morphine and the primary finding of dilated bile ducts without clear pancreatic inflammation on US make SOD a more direct diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Sphincter of Oddi Dysfunction (SOD) | Choledocholithiasis | Cholangitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Pain** | Colicky, RUQ/epigastric, often post-prandial, aggravated by opioids | Colicky, RUQ/epigastric, can be severe | RUQ, often constant, associated with fever/chills |\n| **Imaging (US/MRCP)** | Dilated CBD/IHD, no stones, normal pancreas | Dilated CBD/IHD, stones in CBD | Dilated CBD/IHD, often stones, signs of inflammation |\n| **Labs** | Often normal, transient LFT/amylase elevation | Elevated LFTs, sometimes amylase/lipase | Elevated LFTs, leukocytosis, elevated inflammatory markers |\n| **Opioid Effect** | Aggravates pain (causes spasm) | No specific aggravation, may mask pain | No specific aggravation |\n| **Definitive Diagnosis** | Sphincter of Oddi manometry (elevated basal pressure) | ERCP/MRCP showing stones | Clinical (Charcot's triad/Reynold's pentad), imaging, labs |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Morphine exacerbates pain + dilated ducts = Sphincter of Oddi Dysfunction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound would show a dilated common bile duct (9mm in this case) and dilated intrahepatic ducts without evidence of stones or mass. ERCP with manometry would reveal elevated basal sphincter pressure.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nRome IV Criteria for Functional Biliary Sphincter of Oddi Disorder (2016) provides diagnostic criteria for SOD.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sphincter of oddi dysfunction | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
