  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For CRPS, active physical therapy is non-negotiable.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is physiotherapy. Despite prior specialist and pain clinic involvement, active physical therapy remains the cornerstone of Complex Regional Pain Syndrome (CRPS) management, especially after a precipitating event like surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhysiotherapy for CRPS is crucial for restoring function, reducing pain, and preventing long-term disability. It encompasses a range of techniques including desensitization, graded motor imagery, mirror therapy, and progressive range-of-motion and strengthening exercises. These interventions aim to normalize sensory processing, improve motor control, and combat the physical manifestations of CRPS such as allodynia, hyperalgesia, and trophic changes. Early and consistent engagement in physical therapy is paramount for optimal outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Counselling is an important supportive measure for CRPS patients, addressing psychological distress, anxiety, and coping mechanisms. However, it is not the primary active intervention for the physical pain and functional deficits associated with CRPS. While part of a multidisciplinary approach, physiotherapy directly targets the physical symptoms and is more critical in this scenario.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| CRPS Management Pillar | Description | Goal |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Physiotherapy** | Graded motor imagery, desensitization, ROM exercises, functional training | Restore function, reduce pain, prevent atrophy |\n| **Pharmacotherapy** | Neuropathic agents (gabapentin, pregabalin), NSAIDs, bisphosphonates, corticosteroids | Pain control, inflammation, bone turnover |\n| **Psychological Support** | Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT), counselling, biofeedback | Address distress, improve coping, manage fear-avoidance |\n| **Interventional** | Sympathetic nerve blocks, spinal cord stimulation, intrathecal pumps | Refractory pain management, neuromodulation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Physiotherapy is the cornerstone of CRPS management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (X-rays, MRI) in CRPS is primarily used to rule out other pathologies rather than for definitive diagnosis. In later stages, X-rays may show diffuse osteopenia. Intraoperatively, CRPS is not directly observed, but meticulous surgical technique is vital to minimize nerve irritation and potential CRPS exacerbation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Association for the Study of Pain (IASP) Guidelines for CRPS (2010) recommend a multidisciplinary approach with physical therapy as a core component.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Counselling | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | physiotherapy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
