  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When scopes are clear, the small bowel's where the bleed is, and the capsule's your guide.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nCapsule endoscopy is the correct next investigation. In an elderly patient with lower GI bleeding and normal upper and lower endoscopies, the bleeding source is most likely in the small bowel, which is beyond the reach of conventional endoscopes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCapsule endoscopy is a non-invasive diagnostic tool that allows for direct visualization of the entire small bowel mucosa. This is crucial for identifying obscure gastrointestinal bleeding sources, such as angioectasias, ulcers, or small tumors, which are common in the elderly population and often located in the jejunum or ileum. Its ability to survey the vast expanse of the small intestine makes it superior to other imaging modalities for detecting intermittent or slow bleeding when initial endoscopic evaluations are unrevealing.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CT angio) (Incorrect): CT angiography is primarily used for localizing active, brisk GI bleeding. If the bleeding is intermittent or slow, CT angio is unlikely to detect the source, and the question does not specify active, massive bleeding.\nOption C (MRI) (Incorrect): While MRI can visualize small bowel pathology (e.g., MR enterography), it is not the first-line investigation for obscure GI bleeding after negative conventional endoscopies. Capsule endoscopy offers direct mucosal visualization, which is superior for identifying subtle bleeding lesions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Investigation | Indication | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Capsule Endoscopy | Obscure GI bleeding after negative endoscopies | Non-invasive, full small bowel visualization | No therapeutic capability, risk of retention |\n| CT Angiography | Acute, brisk GI bleeding | Rapid localization of active bleeding | Radiation exposure, requires active bleeding, less sensitive for slow bleeds |\n| Push Enteroscopy | Proximal small bowel bleeding | Biopsy and therapeutic intervention possible | Limited reach (proximal jejunum only) |\n| Small Bowel Follow-Through | Suspected structural small bowel disease (e.g., Crohn's) | Non-invasive, provides structural information | Poor sensitivity for bleeding, radiation exposure |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Obscure GI bleed + normal scopes = think small bowel, think capsule.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn capsule endoscopy, you would be looking for mucosal lesions such as angioectasias (red spots or streaks), ulcers, erosions, or small tumors within the small bowel lumen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Obscure Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2021) recommends capsule endoscopy as the initial investigation for obscure GI bleeding after negative upper and lower endoscopies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT angio | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | capsule | ✅ Correct |\n| C | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
