  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Radial nerve: Extend, don't just feel the dorsum!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Radial nerve. The patient's symptoms of tingling sensation over the dorsum of the hand (thumb, index, and ring fingers) combined with weak extension of the fingers and wrist are classic manifestations of radial nerve palsy. This nerve is solely responsible for these specific motor and sensory functions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe radial nerve, originating from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus, is crucial for upper limb function. It innervates the extensors of the wrist and fingers, allowing for movements like wrist extension and finger straightening. Sensitively, it supplies the dorsum of the hand, including the thumb, index, and middle fingers. Post-surgical nerve palsies, especially after prolonged procedures like rectal surgery, can occur due to sustained pressure or improper positioning, leading to compression of the radial nerve along its course, often in the spiral groove of the humerus, resulting in the described 'wrist drop' and sensory deficits.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Ulnar nerve injury typically presents with sensory loss over the medial 1.5 fingers (ring and little finger) and weakness in intrinsic hand muscles, leading to a 'claw hand' deformity, not wrist or finger extension weakness.\nOption C (Incorrect): Median nerve injury causes sensory loss over the palmar aspect of the thumb, index, middle, and radial half of the ring finger, and weakness in thumb opposition and flexion of the index/middle fingers, often resulting in an 'ape hand' deformity, not wrist or finger extension weakness.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Sensory Distribution | Motor Deficit | Classic Sign |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Radial | Dorsum of hand (thumb, index, middle) | Wrist/finger extension weakness | Wrist drop |\n| Ulnar | Medial 1.5 fingers (palmar & dorsal) | Intrinsic hand muscles, finger adduction/abduction | Claw hand |\n| Median | Palmar aspect (thumb, index, middle, radial ring) | Thumb opposition, index/middle finger flexion | Ape hand |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Wrist drop and dorsal hand numbness equals radial nerve.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, careful patient positioning and padding of pressure points, particularly around the humerus where the radial nerve is superficial, are critical to prevent compression neuropathies during prolonged surgical cases. No specific imaging is typically used for diagnosis of this type of iatrogenic injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) Practice Guidelines for Perioperative Neuropathies 2018. These guidelines emphasize meticulous patient positioning and padding to minimize the risk of nerve injury during surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Radial | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Ulnar | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Median | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
