  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Itchy mom, high liver enzymes? Think ICP, not just skin disease!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Pregnancy cholestasis. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the classic presentation of a pregnant woman experiencing itching with elevated liver enzymes, a hallmark of intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy (ICP).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy (ICP) is a liver disorder unique to pregnancy, characterized by impaired bile flow. The primary symptom is intense pruritus, often worse at night, without a rash. This itching is due to the accumulation of bile acids in the skin. Elevated liver enzymes, particularly transaminases, and significantly elevated serum bile acids are key diagnostic markers. The condition typically resolves spontaneously after delivery but carries risks for the fetus, including preterm birth and stillbirth, necessitating careful monitoring and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Viral hepatitis can cause elevated liver enzymes and sometimes itching, but the primary presentation usually includes other systemic symptoms like malaise, nausea, vomiting, and jaundice, which are not mentioned here. The isolated complaint of itching in pregnancy with elevated LFTs points more specifically to cholestasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Intrahepatic Cholestasis of Pregnancy (ICP) | Viral Hepatitis (e.g., Hep A, B, C) | Preeclampsia with HELLP Syndrome | Acute Fatty Liver of Pregnancy (AFLP) |\n| :---------------------- | :------------------------------------------ | :---------------------------------- | :------------------------------- | :------------------------------------ |\n| **Key Symptoms** | Pruritus (itching), often severe | Malaise, nausea, jaundice, fatigue | Hypertension, proteinuria, RUQ pain | Nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, jaundice |\n| **Liver Enzymes (LFTs)** | Elevated (AST/ALT) | Markedly elevated (AST/ALT) | Elevated (AST/ALT) | Elevated (AST/ALT) |\n| **Bile Acids** | Markedly elevated | Normal to mildly elevated | Normal | Normal to mildly elevated |\n| **Other Labs** | Normal bilirubin (early), normal platelets | Specific viral serology | Thrombocytopenia, hemolysis | Hypoglycemia, coagulopathy, hyperbilirubinemia |\n| **Timing** | Second/third trimester, resolves postpartum | Any time, depends on exposure | Third trimester, postpartum | Third trimester, postpartum |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Itching + elevated LFTs in pregnancy = Intrahepatic Cholestasis of Pregnancy (ICP).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile not diagnostic for ICP itself, an abdominal ultrasound may be performed to rule out other causes of cholestasis, such as gallstones or biliary obstruction, which could also present with elevated liver enzymes and itching. The diagnosis of ICP is primarily clinical and biochemical.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 231: Intrahepatic Cholestasis of Pregnancy (2021). This guideline recommends monitoring bile acid levels and considering ursodeoxycholic acid for symptomatic relief and improved fetal outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Viral hepatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pregnancy cholestasis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
