  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Crohn's: It skips around and goes deep!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nCrohn's disease is the correct diagnosis because the patient presents with abdominal pain and diarrhea, and colonoscopy reveals non-contiguous (skip) lesions in both the terminal ileum and colon. Crucially, pathology confirms transmural inflammation, which are all hallmark features of Crohn's disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCrohn's disease is characterized by its discontinuous, or 'skip,' pattern of inflammation, which can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from mouth to anus, but commonly involves the terminal ileum and colon. The hallmark pathological feature is transmural inflammation, meaning the inflammation extends through all layers of the bowel wall, often leading to complications like strictures, fistulas, and abscesses. Endoscopically, this manifests as patchy involvement with areas of normal mucosa interspersed with inflamed segments, deep ulcers, and cobblestoning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ulcerative colitis) (Incorrect): Ulcerative colitis typically presents with contiguous inflammation starting in the rectum and extending proximally, affecting only the colon, and is characterized by superficial mucosal inflammation, not transmural.\nOption C (Pseudomembranous colitis) (Incorrect): Pseudomembranous colitis is an infectious colitis, usually caused by *Clostridioides difficile*, characterized by pseudomembranes on endoscopy and superficial inflammation, not transmural inflammation or skip lesions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Crohn's Disease | Ulcerative Colitis | Pseudomembranous Colitis |\n| :------------------ | :-------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------ | :--------------------------------------------- |\n| **Location** | Any part of GI tract (mouth to anus), often terminal ileum & colon | Colon only, contiguous from rectum proximally | Colon only |\n| **Inflammation** | Transmural | Mucosal/Submucosal (superficial) | Mucosal (superficial) |\n| **Pattern** | Non-contiguous (skip lesions) | Contiguous | Patchy pseudomembranes |\n| **Endoscopy** | Skip lesions, cobblestoning, deep ulcers, strictures, fistulas | Diffuse erythema, friability, pseudopolyps, no skip lesions | Yellowish plaques (pseudomembranes) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Skip lesions + transmural inflammation = Crohn's.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, one would observe discontinuous areas of inflammation (skip lesions) with intervening normal mucosa, deep linear ulcers, cobblestone appearance of the mucosa, and potentially strictures or fistulous openings, especially in the terminal ileum and colon.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Clinical Practice Guideline on the Management of Crohn's Disease (2020) emphasizes the role of endoscopy and histology for diagnosis and disease classification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ulcerative colitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | crohn disease | ✅ Correct |\n| C | pseudomembranous colitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
