  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Elective surgery + incidental mass = Stage first, then resect.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, to perform the cholecystectomy only. This approach prioritizes patient safety and adheres to sound surgical principles when encountering an unexpected, potentially significant finding during an elective procedure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWhen an incidental, potentially malignant mass is discovered during an elective operation, the primary goal is to complete the planned procedure safely and then address the new finding in a staged manner. Resecting an unknown gastric mass without prior biopsy, staging, and multidisciplinary discussion is poor surgical practice. This approach allows for proper preoperative evaluation (e.g., endoscopy with biopsy, CT staging), patient counseling, and optimal surgical planning, which is crucial for potential oncologic cases and minimizes unnecessary morbidity from an unplanned, complex resection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Resect the mass) (Incorrect): Resecting an unknown gastric mass without prior workup (biopsy, staging, multidisciplinary discussion) is inappropriate and potentially harmful, as it could be benign, or if malignant, an incomplete or inappropriate oncologic resection.\nOption C (end the procedure) (Incorrect): The patient underwent anesthesia and incision for an elective cholecystectomy, which should be completed if safe, as it was the primary indication for surgery.\nOption D (cholecystectomy and mass resection) (Incorrect): Performing an unplanned, potentially extensive resection of an unknown gastric mass concurrently with the cholecystectomy is poor surgical judgment due to lack of staging, potential for malignancy, and increased operative time and morbidity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Scenario | Primary Procedure | Incidental Finding | Recommended Action | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Elective Cholecystectomy | Cholecystectomy | Gastric Mass (unknown) | Complete cholecystectomy, then stage and plan for mass | Avoid unplanned complex surgery; allow for proper staging and multidisciplinary discussion for potential malignancy. |\n| Elective Hysterectomy | Hysterectomy | Acute Appendicitis | Perform appendectomy concurrently | Acute appendicitis is a benign, easily resectable condition that would require a separate operation if not addressed. |\n| Emergency Laparotomy for Trauma | Hemostasis | Small, asymptomatic diverticulum | Leave diverticulum alone | Focus on life-saving procedure; incidental finding is not acute and adds risk. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Don't operate on an unknown mass without a plan.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the surgeon would visualize and palpate a distinct mass on the stomach. Postoperatively, endoscopy with biopsy and cross-sectional imaging (e.g., CT chest/abdomen/pelvis) would be essential for diagnosis and staging of the gastric mass.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Statement on Principles of Patient Safety in Surgery (General Surgical Principles): Emphasizes thorough preoperative evaluation and planning, especially for complex or potentially oncologic cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Resect the mass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | cholecystectomy only | ✅ Correct |\n| C | end the procedure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | cholecystectomy and mass resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
