  "question": "354. pt admitted for Rt adrenalectomy because of Cushing what to give?",
  "options": {
    "A": "post op fludrocortisone",
    "B": "peri op corticosteroid"
  },
  "answer": "B) N.B: Peri-op not Pre-op.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No adrenal, no cortisol, no crisis! Supplement!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is perioperative corticosteroid administration. Patients undergoing adrenalectomy for Cushing's syndrome have chronic suppression of their hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis, making them susceptible to acute adrenal insufficiency upon removal of the cortisol-producing tumor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic hypercortisolism from a Cushing's tumor leads to negative feedback on the pituitary and hypothalamus, suppressing endogenous ACTH production and atrophy of the contralateral adrenal gland (in unilateral disease) or the remaining adrenal cortex (if bilateral). Removing the tumor abruptly eliminates the source of excess cortisol, but the suppressed HPA axis cannot immediately resume normal cortisol production. Perioperative glucocorticoid supplementation bridges this gap, preventing a life-threatening adrenal crisis characterized by hypotension, hypoglycemia, and electrolyte disturbances.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Post-operative fludrocortisone is a mineralocorticoid. While it is essential for long-term replacement after bilateral adrenalectomy, it does not address the acute glucocorticoid deficiency that causes adrenal crisis perioperatively, especially in unilateral adrenalectomy where mineralocorticoid function is usually preserved by the contralateral gland.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Perioperative Steroid Management | Long-term Steroid Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Unilateral Adrenalectomy for Cushing's | Glucocorticoid (e.g., hydrocortisone stress dose) | Tapered, then usually none (if HPA axis recovers) |\n| Bilateral Adrenalectomy | Glucocorticoid (stress dose) | Glucocorticoid + Mineralocorticoid |\n| Primary Adrenal Insufficiency (Addison's) | Glucocorticoid (stress dose for surgery) | Glucocorticoid + Mineralocorticoid |\n| Secondary Adrenal Insufficiency | Glucocorticoid (stress dose for surgery) | Glucocorticoid |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always cover HPA axis suppression perioperatively to prevent adrenal crisis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the surgeon would identify and resect the enlarged right adrenal gland or tumor. Preoperative imaging (CT/MRI) would typically show a well-defined adrenal mass, often with characteristics suggestive of an adenoma (e.g., low Hounsfield units on CT).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline: Treatment of Cushing's Syndrome (2015) recommends perioperative glucocorticoid coverage for all patients undergoing adrenalectomy for Cushing's syndrome.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | post op fludrocortisone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | peri op corticosteroid | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) N.B: Peri-op not Pre-op.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
