  "question": "367. 25 years female with thyroid nodules TSH and T4 normal, FNA cytology done and according to Bethesda classification (stage IV) what is the most accurate management?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Lobectomy",
    "B": "hemithyroidectomy"
  },
  "answer": "A) ",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, cut it out (the lobe, that is).**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Lobectomy. For a 25-year-old female with a thyroid nodule classified as Bethesda IV (Follicular Neoplasm or Suspicious for Follicular Neoplasm), a diagnostic lobectomy is the most accurate initial management to obtain a definitive histological diagnosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBethesda IV cytology indicates a 15-30% risk of malignancy, primarily follicular carcinoma. Since FNA cannot distinguish between a benign follicular adenoma and a malignant follicular carcinoma (which requires capsular or vascular invasion), surgical excision of the entire suspicious lobe is necessary for definitive diagnosis. A lobectomy allows for complete pathological evaluation of the lesion, preserving the contralateral thyroid lobe if the pathology is benign or low-risk, thus avoiding lifelong thyroid hormone replacement. If malignancy is confirmed and requires further intervention, a completion thyroidectomy can be performed subsequently.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (hemithyroidectomy) (Incorrect): While often used interchangeably with lobectomy, 'lobectomy' is the more precise term for the removal of a single thyroid lobe for diagnostic purposes in Bethesda IV cases. The goal is to obtain a definitive histological diagnosis of the entire suspicious lesion, and 'lobectomy' specifically refers to the complete removal of the lobe containing the nodule.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Bethesda Category | Risk of Malignancy | Recommended Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| I (Non-diagnostic) | 5-10% | Repeat FNA with ultrasound guidance |\n| II (Benign) | 0-3% | Clinical follow-up, ultrasound surveillance |\n| III (Atypia of Undetermined Significance/Follicular Lesion of Undetermined Significance) | 10-30% | Repeat FNA, molecular testing, or diagnostic lobectomy |\n| IV (Follicular Neoplasm/Suspicious for Follicular Neoplasm) | 15-30% | Diagnostic lobectomy or molecular testing |\n| V (Suspicious for Malignancy) | 60-75% | Near-total or total thyroidectomy, or lobectomy |\n| VI (Malignant) | 97-99% | Total thyroidectomy or lobectomy (for low-risk, small tumors) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bethesda IV = Diagnostic Lobectomy for definitive pathology.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPreoperative ultrasound would characterize the nodule's features (size, echogenicity, margins, calcifications). Intraoperatively, the surgeon would identify and preserve the recurrent laryngeal nerve and parathyroid glands while excising the entire thyroid lobe containing the suspicious nodule.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Management Guidelines for Patients with Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015, updated 2023).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lobectomy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | hemithyroidectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
