  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Preventing clots after hip fracture: LMWH is the winning shot.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies Enoxaparin as the preferred prophylactic agent for venous thromboembolism (VTE) in patients with hip fractures. Low molecular weight heparins (LMWH) like Enoxaparin are superior to unfractionated heparin for this indication, though the standard prophylactic dose is typically 40 mg once daily (OD) or 30 mg twice daily (BID), not 40 mg BID as implied by 'sc bid' in option A for treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLMWH, such as Enoxaparin, is the gold standard for VTE prophylaxis in orthopedic trauma, including hip fractures, due to its predictable anticoagulant response, longer half-life, and lower incidence of heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT) compared to unfractionated heparin. It works by inhibiting Factor Xa, preventing thrombin generation and clot formation. The efficacy and safety profile of LMWH have been well-established in numerous clinical trials for this high-risk patient population.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While Enoxaparin is the correct agent for VTE prophylaxis in hip fracture, the 'sc bid' dosing (e.g., 40 mg BID) is typically used for treatment of established VTE, not the standard prophylactic dose of 40 mg once daily or 30 mg twice daily.\nOption B (Incorrect): Heparin sulphate (unfractionated heparin) is less effective and carries a higher risk of complications, including HIT and major bleeding, compared to LMWH for VTE prophylaxis in patients with hip fractures.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Enoxaparin (LMWH) | Unfractionated Heparin (UFH) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Mechanism** | Primarily inhibits Factor Xa | Inhibits Factors IIa (thrombin) and Xa via antithrombin |\n| **Dosing (Prophylaxis)** | 40 mg SC OD or 30 mg SC BID | 5000 units SC BID/TID |\n| **Half-life** | Longer (4-6 hours) | Shorter (1-2 hours) |\n| **Predictability** | More predictable, no routine monitoring | Less predictable, requires aPTT monitoring |\n| **HIT Risk** | Lower | Higher |\n| **Renal Adjustment** | Required for severe renal impairment | Less critical, but still consider |\n| **Preferred in Hip Fx** | Yes | No |\n| **Reversal** | Protamine sulfate (partial) | Protamine sulfate (complete) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: LMWH (Enoxaparin 40mg OD) is the preferred VTE prophylaxis for hip fractures.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPatients with hip fractures typically present with pain and inability to bear weight, confirmed by plain radiographs (AP pelvis, lateral hip). Surgical intervention, such as open reduction internal fixation (ORIF) or arthroplasty, is usually performed within 24-48 hours, necessitating prompt VTE prophylaxis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines (10th Edition, 2012) recommend LMWH over unfractionated heparin for VTE prophylaxis in patients undergoing major orthopedic surgery, including hip fracture surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Enoxaparin sc bid | ✅ Correct |\n| B | heparin sulphate 10.00 BID | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) the correct answer is 40 OD.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
