  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the nipple slits horizontally, think duct ectasia, not disaster!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Duct Ectasia. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the classic clinical finding of a unilateral inverted nipple that slits horizontally when attempted to be everted, especially in a breastfeeding or perimenopausal woman.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuct ectasia is a benign condition characterized by the dilatation of the major lactiferous ducts, often accompanied by periductal inflammation and fibrosis. This fibrosis leads to shortening and retraction of the ducts, pulling the nipple inward and causing inversion. The pathognomonic sign of horizontal slitting upon attempted eversion reflects the fibrotic bands tethering the nipple, which is a key differentiator from other causes of nipple inversion. While it can mimic malignancy, this specific maneuver points towards a benign etiology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While malignancy can cause nipple inversion, the specific finding of horizontal slitting upon attempted eversion is highly characteristic of duct ectasia, not typically malignancy. Malignancy-related inversion is usually fixed, often new onset, and not easily manipulated in this manner.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Duct Ectasia | Malignancy |\n|---|---|---|\n| Nipple Inversion | Often unilateral, new onset, may be reducible with horizontal slitting | Often unilateral, new onset, fixed, not easily reducible |\n| Nipple Discharge | Green, black, sticky, multi-ductal | Bloody, serous, spontaneous, uni-ductal |\n| Pain/Tenderness | Common, periareolar | Less common, or associated with a palpable mass |\n| Palpable Mass | May have subareolar mass (inflamed ducts) | Often associated with a distinct, firm mass |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Horizontal nipple slitting on eversion = duct ectasia until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, dilated subareolar ducts with internal echoes or debris and periductal inflammation may be seen. Mammography can show dilated ducts, rod-like calcifications, or a subareolar mass.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) BI-RADS Atlas (5th Edition, 2013) - Provides standardized lexicon for describing breast imaging findings, including duct ectasia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Duct Ectasia | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Malignancy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
