  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Eyesight over anticoagulation: mechanical DVT prophylaxis for retinal surgery.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is mechanical compression. Following retinal surgery, the primary concern is to avoid any intervention that could increase the risk of ocular hemorrhage, which could severely compromise vision. Mechanical prophylaxis effectively prevents DVT without increasing bleeding risk.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRetinal surgery, such as vitrectomy or scleral buckling, involves delicate intraocular structures where even minor bleeding can have catastrophic visual consequences. Mechanical compression devices, like intermittent pneumatic compression (IPC) or graduated compression stockings (GCS), work by increasing venous blood flow velocity and reducing venous stasis in the lower extremities. This physiological action prevents thrombus formation without introducing systemic anticoagulation, thereby prioritizing ocular safety while still mitigating the risk of deep vein thrombosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (heparin) (Incorrect): Heparin is a systemic anticoagulant that significantly elevates the risk of bleeding, which is highly undesirable and potentially vision-threatening after retinal surgery.\nOption B (enoxaparin) (Incorrect): Enoxaparin, a low molecular weight heparin, also carries a substantial risk of systemic bleeding and is generally avoided in patients undergoing or recovering from retinal surgery due to the high risk of ocular hemorrhage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Prophylaxis Type | Mechanism | Indication (General) | Contraindication (Retinal Surgery) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mechanical Compression | Increases venous flow, reduces stasis | Most surgical patients | None (preferred) |\n| Unfractionated Heparin | Inhibits clotting factors | High-risk DVT patients | Ocular hemorrhage risk |\n| LMWH (Enoxaparin) | Inhibits Factor Xa | High-risk DVT patients | Ocular hemorrhage risk |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Retinal surgery + DVT prophylaxis = mechanical, not pharmacologic, due to bleeding risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room or post-anesthesia care unit, one would observe the patient wearing sequential compression devices (SCDs) or graduated compression stockings on their lower extremities to provide mechanical DVT prophylaxis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines for Antithrombotic Therapy and Prevention of Thrombosis (9th Edition, 2012) recommends mechanical prophylaxis for patients at high risk of bleeding where pharmacologic prophylaxis is contraindicated.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | heparin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | enoxaparin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | mechanical compression | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
