  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Enema for kids, knife for adults – intussusception's golden rule!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct management for intussusception in a 9-year-old child is an enema. This non-operative reduction technique is the first-line treatment for uncomplicated intussusception in pediatric patients, aiming to reduce the invaginated bowel segment without surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntussusception in children is often idiopathic, frequently occurring at the ileocolic junction. An enema (air or hydrostatic) uses controlled pressure to push the invaginated bowel segment back into its normal position. This approach avoids the risks of surgery, such as anesthesia complications, adhesions, and potential bowel resection, thereby preserving bowel length, which is particularly important in growing children. Success rates are high, especially when performed early and in the absence of signs of peritonitis or perforation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Surgical resection is typically reserved for cases where enema reduction fails, there are signs of bowel ischemia or perforation, or a pathological lead point (e.g., Meckel's diverticulum, polyp) is identified, which is less common in idiopathic pediatric intussusception.\nOption B (Incorrect): Surgical decompression is not a primary treatment for intussusception; the goal is reduction of the telescoped bowel. Decompression might be part of a surgical procedure if there's significant bowel distention, but it's not the main management strategy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Colonoscopy is primarily a diagnostic and therapeutic tool for colonic pathology, not the standard initial treatment for intussusception. While it might visualize an intussusception, it is not the primary reduction method in this context, especially in a child.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pediatric Intussusception | Adult Intussusception |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Often idiopathic (viral illness) | Pathological lead point (tumor, polyp, adhesion) |\n| **Location** | Ileocolic (most common) | Small bowel or colonic |\n| **First-line Mx** | Non-operative reduction (enema) | Surgical resection (due to lead point) |\n| **Recurrence** | ~5-10% after enema reduction | Less common, but often requires surgery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pediatric intussusception = enema first; adult intussusception = surgery for lead point.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound is the initial diagnostic modality, showing the classic 'target sign' or 'pseudokidney sign.' A contrast enema (air or hydrostatic) is both diagnostic and therapeutic, confirming the diagnosis and attempting reduction. If surgery is required, the intussusception appears as a telescoped bowel segment; manual reduction is attempted first, with resection performed if reduction fails or bowel is non-viable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Intussusception (2019) recommends nonoperative reduction (air or hydrostatic enema) as the initial treatment for stable children with intussusception, citing high success rates and low complication rates.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Surgical resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Surgical decompression | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Colonoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Enema | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) in adult age > A.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
