  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When blood's the only story, and the liver's fine, think gastritis line!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is erosive gastritis. This diagnosis best fits a male patient presenting with recurrent hematemesis, stable vital signs, anemia, and normal liver function tests (LFTs), especially in the absence of any other specific complaints or precipitating events.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nErosive gastritis involves superficial mucosal damage in the stomach, often caused by factors like NSAIDs, alcohol, or stress. This erosion can lead to bleeding, manifesting as hematemesis, which can be recurrent. The bleeding is typically self-limited, explaining the stable vitals, and the absence of other symptoms like abdominal pain (common in peptic ulcer disease) or signs of liver dysfunction (common in variceal bleeding) makes erosive gastritis a highly plausible diagnosis in this scenario.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (esophageal varices) (Incorrect): Normal LFTs significantly reduce the likelihood of portal hypertension, which is the underlying cause of esophageal varices. Variceal bleeding is also often massive and associated with signs of liver disease.\nOption B (peptic ulcer disease) (Incorrect): While PUD can cause hematemesis, it is typically associated with epigastric pain, which is explicitly absent ('no other complaint') in this patient.\nOption D (Mallory weiss tear) (Incorrect): Mallory-Weiss tears usually follow a history of forceful retching or vomiting, which is not mentioned. Recurrent hematemesis without a clear precipitating event makes it less likely as the primary, ongoing diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Erosive Gastritis | Peptic Ulcer Disease | Esophageal Varices | Mallory-Weiss Tear |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Key Symptom** | Recurrent hematemesis, no other specific complaints | Epigastric pain, hematemesis, melena | Massive hematemesis, signs of liver disease | Hematemesis following forceful retching/vomiting |\n| **Common Causes** | NSAIDs, alcohol, stress | H. pylori, NSAIDs | Portal hypertension (cirrhosis) | Forceful vomiting, retching, coughing |\n| **LFTs** | Normal | Normal | Often abnormal (elevated AST/ALT, bilirubin) | Normal |\n| **Endoscopy** | Multiple superficial erosions, petechiae | Single or multiple discrete ulcers | Dilated submucosal veins | Linear mucosal tear at GE junction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Recurrent hematemesis with normal LFTs and no other symptoms points to gastritis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would reveal diffuse or focal areas of mucosal erythema, petechiae, and superficial erosions in the gastric lining, often with active oozing or adherent clots.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2021). Recommends early endoscopy for diagnosis and management of non-variceal upper GI bleeding.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | esophageal varices | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | peptic ulcer disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | erosive gastritis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Mallory weiss tear | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
