  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't irradiate a potential baby; test for pregnancy first!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Pregnancy test. For a 27-year-old female presenting with acute abdominal pain, determining pregnancy status is the most critical initial step before proceeding with a CT scan due to potential fetal radiation exposure and the high clinical relevance of ectopic pregnancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA positive pregnancy test in a reproductive-age female with acute abdominal pain immediately raises concerns for ectopic pregnancy, a life-threatening surgical emergency. Furthermore, ionizing radiation from CT scans poses significant risks to a developing fetus, including teratogenicity, growth restriction, and increased lifetime cancer risk. Therefore, confirming pregnancy status dictates the choice of imaging modality (e.g., ultrasound first), the need for radiation shielding, or the delay/avoidance of radiation-based imaging, prioritizing patient and fetal safety.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Full bladder) (Incorrect): While a full bladder can be helpful for pelvic ultrasound, it is not the most important consideration before a CT scan for acute abdominal pain, especially when compared to ruling out pregnancy.\nOption C (Previous CT scans) (Incorrect): Reviewing previous imaging is good practice for comparison, but it does not supersede the immediate safety concern of radiation exposure to a potential fetus in a young female.\nOption D (Volume status) (Incorrect): Assessing volume status is important for any acutely ill patient and guides resuscitation, but it is a general principle and not the most critical specific pre-CT consideration for a young female with abdominal pain, which directly impacts the safety and choice of the imaging itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Pre-CT Consideration | Importance in 27F with Abdominal Pain | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pregnancy Test | Critical | Avoid fetal radiation exposure; rule out ectopic pregnancy. |\n| Volume Status | Important | General patient stability; guides resuscitation. |\n| Previous Imaging | Helpful | Comparison for acute vs. chronic changes. |\n| Full Bladder | Minor (for CT) | More relevant for pelvic ultrasound. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always pregnancy test reproductive-age females before abdominal CT.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIf pregnant, an ultrasound would be the preferred initial imaging, potentially showing an intrauterine pregnancy or an ectopic gestation. If CT is performed without knowing pregnancy status, it could expose a developing fetus to radiation, with potential long-term consequences.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Acute Pelvic Pain in the Reproductive Age Group (2021) recommends pregnancy testing as a critical initial step.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Full bladder | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pregnancy test | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Previous CT scans | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Volume status | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
