  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Post-op MI: Fix the pipe, don't thin the blood!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Primary angioplasty is the correct treatment for a post-operative myocardial infarction (MI) because it directly addresses the coronary occlusion while minimizing the systemic bleeding risk inherent in recent surgical patients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary angioplasty, or percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI), involves mechanically opening the occluded coronary artery with a balloon and often placing a stent. This approach is superior in the post-operative setting as it provides rapid reperfusion without the systemic fibrinolytic effects of thrombolytics, which would significantly increase the risk of surgical site bleeding, intracranial hemorrhage, or other major bleeding complications in a patient who has recently undergone surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Thrombolytics are generally contraindicated or used with extreme caution in patients who have recently undergone surgery due to the high risk of severe bleeding complications, including at the surgical site or intracranial hemorrhage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Primary Angioplasty (PCI) | Thrombolytics |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mechanism | Mechanical revascularization | Pharmacological clot dissolution |\n| Efficacy | High, especially for STEMI | Effective, but less so than PCI |\n| Bleeding Risk (Post-op) | Localized, lower systemic risk | High systemic bleeding risk |\n| Contraindications (Post-op) | Few, mainly access site issues | Recent surgery is a major contraindication |\n| Time Sensitivity | \"Door-to-balloon\" time critical | \"Door-to-needle\" time critical |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-op MI = PCI first, avoid systemic thrombolysis due to bleeding risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring primary angioplasty, coronary angiography would reveal the acutely occluded coronary artery, which is then re-opened via balloon inflation and stent placement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2013 ACCF/AHA Guideline for the Management of STEMI: Recommends primary PCI as the preferred reperfusion strategy for STEMI when performed in a timely manner by experienced operators.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Primary angioplasty | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Thrombolytics | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
