  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cut the spasm, heal the fissure, live free!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Option A, lateral internal sphincterotomy, is the correct answer because it directly addresses the underlying pathophysiology of chronic anal fissures: internal anal sphincter hypertonia. When medical management fails, surgical division of a portion of the internal sphincter is the gold standard to reduce spasm and promote healing.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic anal fissures are often caused by hypertonicity of the internal anal sphincter, leading to reduced blood flow to the anoderm and impaired healing. A lateral internal sphincterotomy involves a controlled division of a small portion of the internal anal sphincter, typically in the lateral position to minimize risk of incontinence. This procedure effectively reduces resting anal pressure, improves anoderm perfusion, and allows the fissure to heal, boasting success rates over 90%.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): External sphincterotomy is never performed for anal fissures as it would lead to severe and debilitating fecal incontinence due to the voluntary nature of the external sphincter.\nOption C (Incorrect): Anal curettage and removal of the skin tag (sentinel pile) only address superficial aspects of the fissure and its associated findings. It does not resolve the underlying internal sphincter hypertonia, which is the primary cause of chronic non-healing fissures.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment | Indication | Mechanism | Potential Complications |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Medical (e.g., Nitroglycerin, Diltiazem) | Acute fissures, first-line for chronic | Relaxes internal sphincter, improves blood flow | Headache, dizziness, recurrence |\n| Lateral Internal Sphincterotomy (LIS) | Chronic fissures failing medical therapy | Irreversibly reduces internal sphincter tone | Minor incontinence (flatus/soiling) in a small percentage, recurrence (rare) |\n| Fissurectomy | Rarely primary, often with LIS for large/fibrotic fissures | Excises fibrotic tissue, promotes healing | Similar to LIS, but may increase wound size |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Chronic fissure + failed drugs = Lateral Internal Sphincterotomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, a chronic anal fissure appears as a deep ulcer, often with hypertrophied papilla proximally and a sentinel pile (skin tag) distally. During lateral internal sphincterotomy, the intersphincteric groove is identified, and a small portion of the internal sphincter is carefully divided, typically to the dentate line, while preserving the external sphincter.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Anal Fissures (2017) recommends lateral internal sphincterotomy as the gold standard surgical treatment for chronic anal fissures refractory to medical therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Internal sphernctomy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | External sphrenctomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Anal curettage with remove tag | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A, Lateral internal.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
