  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Move it or lose it: CRPS demands early, active rehab.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Physiotherapy. This verdict is based on the understanding that Complex Regional Pain Syndrome (CRPS) requires a multidisciplinary approach, with physiotherapy being a cornerstone for functional restoration and pain modulation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCRPS is characterized by sensory, motor, autonomic, and trophic changes. Physiotherapy directly addresses these by promoting graded motor imagery, desensitization, range of motion exercises, and progressive loading. This active rehabilitation helps to break the pain-spasm-pain cycle, improve blood flow, reduce edema, and restore cortical representation of the affected limb, which is often distorted in CRPS. Early and consistent physical therapy is crucial for preventing long-term disability and improving overall quality of life.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Opiate) (Incorrect): Opiates are generally not recommended as a primary treatment for CRPS due to limited efficacy, risk of dependence, and potential for opioid-induced hyperalgesia, especially in chronic pain conditions.\nOption B (Triptan) (Incorrect): Triptans are a class of drugs primarily used for the acute treatment of migraine headaches and have no established role in the management of CRPS.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Management Strategy | Role in CRPS |\n|---|---|\n| **Physiotherapy** | Cornerstone: desensitization, graded motor imagery, ROM, functional restoration |\n| **Pharmacotherapy** | Neuropathic agents (gabapentin, pregabalin), bisphosphonates, corticosteroids (acute phase) |\n| **Interventional** | Sympathetic blocks, spinal cord stimulation, ketamine infusions |\n| **Psychological** | Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT), pain coping strategies, biofeedback |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Physiotherapy is the cornerstone of CRPS management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging studies like X-rays or MRI in CRPS are primarily used to rule out other pathologies (e.g., fracture, infection, tumor) or assess complications like disuse osteopenia, rather than for direct diagnosis of CRPS itself. There is no specific diagnostic imaging for CRPS.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Association for the Study of Pain (IASP) 2017 diagnostic criteria for CRPS emphasize clinical presentation. For management, national pain societies (e.g., American Pain Society) recommend a multidisciplinary approach with physical therapy as a core component.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Opiate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Triptan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Physiotherapy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
