  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For hip fractures, LMWH once daily keeps the clots away!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct prophylactic agent for a hip fracture patient is Enoxaparin 40mg once daily, as it effectively reduces the risk of venous thromboembolism (VTE) which is significantly elevated in this patient population. This regimen balances efficacy with a favorable safety profile.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHip fracture patients are at a very high risk for deep vein thrombosis (DVT) and pulmonary embolism (PE) due to immobility, surgical trauma, and underlying comorbidities. Low molecular weight heparins (LMWH) like Enoxaparin exert their anticoagulant effect primarily by inhibiting Factor Xa, leading to a more predictable anticoagulant response compared to unfractionated heparin (UFH). The once-daily dosing of Enoxaparin 40mg is a well-established and evidence-based regimen for VTE prophylaxis in major orthopedic surgery, demonstrating superior efficacy and a lower incidence of heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT) compared to UFH.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Enoxaparin sc bid) (Incorrect): While Enoxaparin is the correct agent, the standard prophylactic dose for hip fracture is typically 40mg once daily, not twice daily. Twice-daily dosing is usually reserved for therapeutic anticoagulation or specific high-risk scenarios, which would increase bleeding risk unnecessarily for prophylaxis.\nOption B (heparin sulphate 10.00 BID) (Incorrect): Unfractionated heparin (heparin sulfate) is generally less effective than LMWH for VTE prophylaxis in orthopedic surgery and carries a higher risk of bleeding and HIT. Furthermore, the dose \"10.00 BID\" is vague and likely insufficient or incorrect for effective VTE prophylaxis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Enoxaparin (LMWH) | Unfractionated Heparin (UFH) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mechanism | Primarily inhibits Factor Xa | Inhibits Factors IIa (thrombin) and Xa via antithrombin |\n| Dosing (Prophylaxis) | 40mg SC once daily (ortho) | 5000 units SC 2-3 times daily |\n| Monitoring | Not routinely required (anti-Xa levels in specific cases) | aPTT monitoring required for therapeutic use |\n| Efficacy (Ortho) | Superior for VTE prophylaxis | Less effective than LMWH |\n| HIT Risk | Lower | Higher |\n| Renal Adjustment | Required for severe renal impairment | Less dependent on renal clearance |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: LMWH (Enoxaparin 40mg daily) is the gold standard for hip fracture VTE prophylaxis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, a hip fracture typically appears as a break in the femoral neck, intertrochanteric region, or subtrochanteric region, often with displacement or angulation of the bone fragments. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would identify the fracture pattern and reduce it, followed by internal fixation (e.g., with screws, plates, or an intramedullary nail) or arthroplasty.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Preventing Venous Thromboembolic Disease in Patients Undergoing Elective Hip and Knee Arthroplasty (2016) recommends LMWH for VTE prophylaxis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Enoxaparin sc bid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | heparin sulphate 10.00 BID | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) the correct answer is Enoxaparin 40 once daily** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
