  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Post-sleeve pain? Stability first, then strategy.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct approach to severe abdominal pain four weeks post-sleeve gastrectomy is dictated by the patient's hemodynamic stability. An unstable patient requires immediate surgical exploration, while a stable patient allows for diagnostic imaging to guide intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThis scenario highlights a fundamental principle in acute surgical care: patient stability is paramount in determining the initial management pathway. In an unstable patient, the priority is to identify and control life-threatening complications such as hemorrhage or a major leak causing sepsis, which mandates immediate surgical intervention. For a stable patient, time permits a thorough diagnostic workup, typically with a CT scan, to precisely localize the pathology (e.g., staple line leak, abscess, obstruction, hematoma) and plan a targeted, less invasive, or definitive surgical approach.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Exploratory) (Incorrect): While surgery may ultimately be necessary, proceeding directly to exploration without imaging in a stable patient can lead to unnecessary surgery or a less targeted approach. It is the correct choice only if the patient is unstable.\nOption B (Imaging) (Incorrect): Imaging is crucial for stable patients, but delaying surgery for imaging in an unstable patient with severe abdominal pain post-sleeve gastrectomy can be fatal, as it risks progression of sepsis or exsanguination.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Stable Patient Post-Sleeve Pain | Unstable Patient Post-Sleeve Pain |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Initial Management** | Imaging (CT scan with oral/IV contrast) | Immediate Surgical Exploration |\n| **Goal** | Diagnose specific complication, plan targeted intervention | Control life-threatening hemorrhage/sepsis, identify source |\n| **Urgency** | High, but allows for diagnostic workup | Extreme, emergent intervention |\n| **Potential Findings** | Leak, abscess, hematoma, obstruction, fistula | Peritonitis, active bleeding, staple line disruption, gross contamination |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-op abdominal pain: Unstable to OR, Stable to CT. Stability dictates the next step.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, one might see extraluminal contrast extravasation (leak), peri-gastric fluid collections or abscesses, hematoma, or signs of obstruction. Intraoperatively, findings could include purulent peritonitis, active bleeding from the staple line, staple line dehiscence, or an inflammatory mass.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) Guidelines for the Clinical Application of Bariatric Surgery (2016) recommends a multidisciplinary approach to complications, emphasizing prompt diagnosis and management based on patient stability and specific findings.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Exploratory | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Imaging | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ▫ Depends on the Case Stable > CT ▫ Unstable > Surgery** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
