  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Benign FNA doesn't always mean benign nodule.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe biopsy result of \"normal follicular thyroid cells\" for a neck mass, particularly a thyroid nodule, is often ambiguous. While typically classified as benign (Bethesda II), it does not definitively rule out malignancy, especially follicular carcinoma, which cannot be diagnosed by cytology alone. Therefore, surgical referral for further evaluation and potential excision is warranted.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA fine needle aspiration (FNA) showing \"normal follicular thyroid cells\" corresponds to a Bethesda II (benign) classification. However, this classification is based on cytology and cannot distinguish between a benign follicular adenoma and a malignant follicular carcinoma, as this distinction relies on the presence of capsular or vascular invasion, which can only be assessed on histological examination of the excised specimen. Furthermore, clinical suspicion, nodule growth, or suspicious ultrasound features (e.g., microcalcifications, irregular margins, taller-than-wide shape) can override a benign FNA result and necessitate surgical referral for diagnostic lobectomy or further management. The false negative rate for FNA, though low, also contributes to the need for careful clinical correlation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Reassure. Reassurance is inappropriate because \"normal follicular thyroid cells\" on biopsy, while often benign, does not definitively rule out malignancy, especially follicular carcinoma. Clinical context, nodule size, and ultrasound features are crucial and may still warrant further investigation, making surgical referral the safer and more appropriate next step.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Bethesda Classification | Cytology Finding | Risk of Malignancy | Management |\n| :---------------------- | :--------------- | :----------------- | :--------- |\n| I (Non-diagnostic)      | Insufficient/Acellular | 5-10% | Repeat FNA with US guidance |\n| II (Benign)             | Normal follicular cells | <3% | Clinical follow-up, consider repeat US/FNA, surgical referral if suspicious features |\n| III (Atypia of Undetermined Significance/Follicular Lesion of Undetermined Significance) | Atypia, architectural distortion | 10-30% | Repeat FNA, molecular testing, diagnostic lobectomy |\n| IV (Follicular Neoplasm/Suspicious for Follicular Neoplasm) | Follicular cells arranged in microfollicles | 25-40% | Diagnostic lobectomy |\n| V (Suspicious for Malignancy) | Features suspicious for papillary carcinoma | 60-75% | Near-total or total thyroidectomy |\n| VI (Malignant)          | Definitive malignancy | 97-99% | Near-total or total thyroidectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Normal follicular cells\" on FNA doesn't exclude follicular carcinoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a thyroid nodule with \"normal follicular cells\" on FNA might still show suspicious features like microcalcifications, irregular margins, or a taller-than-wide shape, which would prompt surgical referral despite the benign cytology. Intraoperatively, a follicular carcinoma would be diagnosed by capsular or vascular invasion on final pathology.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines 2015 (or 2023 update). The ATA guidelines provide recommendations for the management of thyroid nodules based on ultrasound features and FNA cytology, recommending surgical referral for Bethesda II nodules with suspicious ultrasound features or significant growth.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Reassure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Surgical refer | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
