  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the patient's too sick to cut, a tube is your best bet!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Cholecystostomy tube. In a critically ill burn patient presenting with signs of acute cholecystitis (dilated gallbladder, thick wall, pericholecystic fluid), percutaneous cholecystostomy is the preferred initial management due to its less invasive nature compared to cholecystectomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCritically ill patients, especially burn victims, are prone to acalculous cholecystitis due to gallbladder stasis, ischemia, and systemic inflammation. These patients often cannot tolerate a major surgical procedure like cholecystectomy. Percutaneous cholecystostomy provides effective decompression and drainage of the inflamed gallbladder, offering a temporizing measure to stabilize the patient. This allows for resolution of the acute inflammatory process, with definitive management (if needed) deferred until the patient's condition improves.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cholecystectomy is the definitive treatment for cholecystitis but carries significant morbidity and mortality risks in a critically ill burn patient who is often hemodynamically unstable or has multiple comorbidities.\nOption C (Incorrect): MRCP is a diagnostic imaging modality used to visualize the biliary tree and pancreatic ducts, primarily for stones or strictures. It is not a therapeutic intervention for acute cholecystitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Cholecystectomy | Cholecystostomy | MRCP |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Indication** | Definitive treatment for symptomatic cholelithiasis/cholecystitis | Temporizing measure for acute cholecystitis in high-risk patients | Diagnostic imaging for biliary/pancreatic duct pathology |\n| **Invasiveness** | Surgical (laparoscopic or open) | Percutaneous (minimally invasive) | Non-invasive (imaging) |\n| **Role in Critically Ill** | Generally avoided due to high risk | Preferred initial management | Diagnostic, not therapeutic |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Critically ill + cholecystitis = drain, don't cut.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, findings of acute cholecystitis include gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, gallbladder distension, and often the absence of gallstones (acalculous cholecystitis). A cholecystostomy tube would appear as a catheter inserted into the gallbladder lumen, draining bile.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis recommend percutaneous cholecystostomy as the first-line treatment for patients with Grade II or III acute cholecystitis who are high-risk surgical candidates.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cholecystectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cholecystostomy tube | ✅ Correct |\n| C | MRCP | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
