  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Perforation management: stabilize first, then seal or sew.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe management of iatrogenic esophageal perforation following pneumodilation for achalasia is highly dependent on the patient's clinical status. For stable patients, endoscopic stenting is often the initial preferred approach, whereas unstable patients or those with signs of systemic infection require immediate surgical intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEsophageal perforation is a critical condition where prompt and appropriate management is paramount. In stable patients with contained perforations, an esophageal stent can effectively seal the defect, diverting luminal contents and allowing the perforation to heal while avoiding the morbidity of immediate surgery. This approach is less invasive and can be highly successful. Conversely, in unstable patients, those with large perforations, or signs of sepsis (e.g., high temperature, elevated WBC), surgical drainage and primary repair or diversion (anastomosis if feasible) are essential to control infection, prevent mediastinitis, and ensure patient survival. The decision between endoscopic and surgical management is thus dictated by the patient's physiological stability and the extent of contamination.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (esophagectomy) (Incorrect): Esophagectomy is a highly morbid procedure and is generally reserved for extensive, irreparable perforations, or severe, uncontrolled sepsis where other measures have failed, not as a primary management for iatrogenic perforation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Scenario | Management Strategy | Rationale |\n| :---------------- | :------------------ | :-------- |\n| Stable, contained perforation, small | Conservative (NPO, antibiotics, PPI) or Endoscopic stent | Allows healing, less invasive, diverts contents |\n| Stable, larger perforation, no sepsis | Endoscopic stent | Seals defect, avoids surgery, suitable for contained leaks |\n| Unstable, sepsis, large perforation, delayed presentation | Surgical repair/drainage, diversion, or esophagectomy (last resort) | Controls infection, prevents mediastinitis, definitive repair |\n| Perforation during endoscopy (early recognition) | Endoscopic clip closure | Minimally invasive, effective for small, fresh perforations |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stability dictates perforation management: stent for stable, surgery for unstable.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT scan with oral contrast), an esophageal perforation would appear as extravasation of contrast material outside the esophageal lumen, often with mediastinal air, fluid collections, or pleural effusions. Intraoperatively, one would identify the site of perforation, assess the extent of mediastinal contamination, and determine the feasibility of primary repair.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) 2019 Guidelines for the management of iatrogenic perforation during endoscopy recommend conservative management or endoscopic closure for small, contained perforations in stable patients, and surgical intervention for larger perforations, unstable patients, or those with signs of sepsis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Esophageal stent | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | esophagectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Surgical drainage + anastomosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) stable > A, if unstable or high temp or WBC > C.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
