  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the liver bleeds post-PTC, find the vessel, stop the flow.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAngiography is the most appropriate investigation for upper GI bleeding following Percutaneous Transhepatic Cholangiography (PTC). This is because post-PTC bleeding, especially significant GI bleeding, often originates from vascular injury within the liver or biliary tree, which angiography can both diagnose and treat.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPTC involves puncturing the liver parenchyma and bile ducts, which carries a risk of vascular injury to intrahepatic arteries or portal vein branches. Such injuries can lead to pseudoaneurysms, arteriovenous fistulas, or direct arterial lacerations, resulting in hemobilia (bleeding into the biliary tree) that drains into the GI tract. Angiography is the gold standard for identifying the precise location of active arterial bleeding or vascular anomalies within the liver. Crucially, it offers the unique advantage of therapeutic intervention through embolization, allowing for immediate control of the hemorrhage once the source is identified.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CT) (Incorrect): While CT can detect active extravasation, it is less sensitive for slow bleeds or small vascular injuries like pseudoaneurysms compared to angiography, and it offers no therapeutic capability.\nOption B (US) (Incorrect): Ultrasound is limited by bowel gas, operator dependence, and poor sensitivity for active deep vascular bleeding. It cannot provide therapeutic intervention.\nOption C (MRI) (Incorrect): MRI is excellent for soft tissue characterization but is not the primary modality for acute active GI bleeding localization due to its slower acquisition time and lack of interventional capability in this acute setting.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Primary Use | Strengths | Limitations |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Angiography | Active vascular bleeding, pseudoaneurysms | Diagnostic & Therapeutic (embolization), highly sensitive for arterial bleeds | Invasive, radiation, contrast nephropathy |\n| CT Angiography | Acute GI bleeding, trauma | Rapid, good for extravasation, pseudoaneurysms | Less sensitive for slow bleeds, diagnostic only |\n| Endoscopy | Upper/Lower GI bleeding (luminal) | Direct visualization, biopsy, therapeutic (clips, cautery) | Cannot detect extra-luminal vascular injury (e.g., hemobilia source) |\n| Ultrasound | Initial screening, gallbladder, ascites | Non-invasive, no radiation | Operator dependent, limited by gas, poor for active bleeding |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-procedure bleeding, think vascular injury, think angiography.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn angiography, you would look for contrast extravasation from an injured vessel, a pseudoaneurysm (a contained rupture of an artery), or an arteriovenous fistula, which would appear as early venous filling from an arterial injection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety of Interventional Radiology (SIR) Quality Improvement Guidelines for Percutaneous Transhepatic Cholangiography and Biliary Drainage (2017) recommend prompt recognition and management of complications, with hemorrhage being a critical one often requiring angiographic intervention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Angiography | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
