  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Phyllodes: Don't forget the lungs, they're not just for breathing!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. Malignant phyllodes tumors have a significant risk of distant metastasis, primarily to the lungs, making systemic staging imperative before definitive local treatment. Therefore, imaging the chest is the most appropriate next step.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant phyllodes tumors are characterized by their potential for hematogenous dissemination, with the lungs being the most common site of distant metastasis. Unlike typical breast cancers, lymph node metastasis is rare. Therefore, a CT chest with contrast is the most appropriate initial staging modality to assess for pulmonary metastases, which would significantly alter management and guide further therapeutic decisions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Chemotherapy) (Incorrect): Chemotherapy is generally not effective for phyllodes tumors and is not the initial next step after diagnosis. Comprehensive staging for distant disease must precede systemic treatment decisions, as local control is paramount and systemic therapy has limited efficacy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Benign Phyllodes Tumor | Borderline Phyllodes Tumor | Malignant Phyllodes Tumor |\n| :---------------- | :--------------------- | :------------------------- | :------------------------ |\n| **Stroma** | Mild atypia, low mitosis | Moderate atypia, increased mitosis | Marked atypia, high mitosis, stromal overgrowth |\n| **Margins** | Pushing | Pushing/Infiltrative | Infiltrative |\n| **Metastasis Risk** | Very low | Low (local recurrence higher) | High (hematogenous, primarily lung) |\n| **Treatment** | Wide local excision | Wide local excision | Wide local excision/Mastectomy + Staging |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Malignant phyllodes: Stage lungs first, then cut.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA CT chest with contrast would reveal pulmonary nodules or masses if distant metastasis has occurred, guiding further management. This imaging is crucial for accurate staging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024) recommend imaging for distant metastasis (e.g., CT chest) for malignant phyllodes tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT chest with contrast | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Chemotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) hormone receptor status, if not there go with A.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
