  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't rush to cut, just watch it grow (or not)!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C because a 0.6 cm gallbladder polyp, without associated gallstones or symptoms, falls into a low-risk category that warrants surveillance rather than immediate surgical intervention. The primary goal is to monitor for growth or changes that might indicate malignant transformation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallbladder polyps are frequently incidental findings, and their management hinges on assessing the risk of malignancy. Polyps less than 10 mm, especially without other risk factors like patient age over 60, primary sclerosing cholangitis, or rapid growth, are typically benign (e.g., cholesterol polyps, adenomyomas). Regular ultrasound follow-up allows for the detection of any increase in size or development of suspicious features, which would then prompt consideration for cholecystectomy. This conservative approach avoids unnecessary surgery while ensuring patient safety.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Immediate surgical consultation for cholecystectomy is generally reserved for larger polyps (typically >= 10 mm), symptomatic polyps, rapid growth, or those with high-risk features. A 0.6 cm polyp does not meet these criteria.\nOption B (Incorrect): While the immediate risk of malignancy for a small polyp is low, it is not zero. Simple reassurance without any follow-up would be irresponsible, as polyps can grow or develop malignant potential over time, necessitating intervention. Surveillance is crucial for risk stratification.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Polyp Size/Feature | Management | Rationale |\n| :----------------- | :--------- | :-------- |\n| < 6 mm, no risk factors | US F/U at 1, 3, 5 years | Very low malignancy risk, long-term surveillance |\n| 6-9 mm, no risk factors | US F/U at 6-12 months, then annually | Low malignancy risk, closer surveillance |\n| >= 10 mm OR rapid growth OR symptomatic OR PSC | Cholecystectomy | Increased malignancy risk or symptomatic |\n| Any size with associated gallstones | Consider cholecystectomy if symptomatic | Gallstones increase risk, symptoms warrant surgery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Small gallbladder polyps get surveillance, not surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a gallbladder polyp appears as a non-shadowing, non-mobile echogenic lesion protruding into the gallbladder lumen. It is distinct from gallstones, which typically cast an acoustic shadow and are mobile with patient position changes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Guideline on the Management of Gallbladder Polyps (2020). It recommends surveillance for polyps <10mm without risk factors, specifically for polyps 6-9mm, follow-up at 6-12 months, then annually.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | consult surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | reassurance | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | us f/u after 6 wk | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
