  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just look at the ulcer, feel the pulse!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is checking pulses because a lateral malleolus ulcer in a non-diabetic patient with hypertension strongly suggests arterial insufficiency. A thorough physical exam, starting with palpation of peripheral pulses, is the essential first step in evaluating peripheral arterial disease (PAD) and guiding subsequent diagnostic tests.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPalpation of peripheral pulses (femoral, popliteal, dorsalis pedis, posterior tibial) is a fundamental component of the vascular physical examination. Diminished or absent pulses are highly indicative of peripheral arterial disease, which is a common cause of lateral malleolus ulcers, especially in patients with risk factors like hypertension. This initial, non-invasive assessment helps to quickly triage patients and determine the urgency and type of further diagnostic workup, such as ABI or arterial duplex, thereby avoiding unnecessary advanced imaging in cases where pulses are robust.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Venous duplex) (Incorrect): Venous ulcers typically occur around the medial malleolus due to venous hypertension. A lateral malleolus ulcer is less likely to be venous, and a duplex is a diagnostic test performed *after* initial clinical assessment, not as the first step.\nOption B (Arterial duplex) (Incorrect): While an arterial duplex is appropriate for suspected arterial disease, it is a secondary diagnostic test. The initial step should always be a physical examination, including pulse palpation, to guide the need for and interpretation of such imaging.\nOption D (ABI) (Incorrect): An Ankle-Brachial Index (ABI) is an excellent screening tool for PAD, but it is also a secondary diagnostic test. A physical examination, including pulse palpation, precedes ABI measurement to establish clinical suspicion and ensure the ABI is performed appropriately.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Venous Ulcer | Arterial Ulcer | Neuropathic Ulcer |\n| :--------------- | :----------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------- |\n| **Location** | Medial malleolus, gaiter area | Lateral malleolus, toes, pressure points | Plantar foot, metatarsal heads, toes |\n| **Appearance** | Irregular, shallow, exudative, granulation | \"Punched out,\" pale base, minimal granulation | Calloused rim, deep, often painless |\n| **Pain** | Mild to moderate, relieved by elevation | Severe, worse with elevation, relieved by dependency | Often painless (due to neuropathy) |\n| **Pulses** | Present, often normal | Diminished or absent | Present, often bounding (due to calcification) |\n| **Skin changes** | Edema, hyperpigmentation, lipodermatosclerosis | Pallor, dependent rubor, hair loss, shiny skin | Dry, cracked skin, callus formation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lateral malleolus ulcer + HTN = think arterial. Always check pulses first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn arterial duplex, one would see areas of stenosis, occlusion, or calcification in the peripheral arteries. Angiography would show the extent of arterial narrowing or blockage. In the OR, surgical exploration for arterial reconstruction (e.g., bypass) would reveal atherosclerotic plaques and diseased arterial segments.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2016 AHA/ACC Guideline on the Management of Patients With Lower Extremity Peripheral Artery Disease. It recommends a thorough history and physical examination, including pulse palpation, as the initial step in evaluating suspected PAD.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Venous duplex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Arterial duplex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Check pulse | ✅ Correct |\n| D | ABI | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
