  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bloody nipple discharge? Think papilloma first, but always rule out cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, red. Intraductal papilloma is a common benign cause of pathologic nipple discharge, and its characteristic presentation is often bloody or serosanguineous (red) discharge due to the friable nature of the lesion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraductal papillomas are benign epithelial growths within the lactiferous ducts, typically composed of a fibrovascular core covered by epithelial cells. These delicate, vascularized structures are prone to microtrauma and bleeding, leading to the classic red or bloody nipple discharge. This discharge is usually spontaneous, unilateral, and originates from a single duct, making it a key indicator for further investigation to differentiate from malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (white) (Incorrect): White discharge is typically milky (galactorrhea), often bilateral, and associated with hormonal imbalances like hyperprolactinemia or certain medications.\nOption B (green) (Incorrect): Green or dark brown discharge is commonly associated with duct ectasia or fibrocystic changes, often sticky and originating from multiple ducts.\nOption C (yellow) (Incorrect): Yellow or clear serous discharge can be seen with fibrocystic changes, early papillomas, or even carcinoma, but red is the most classic and specific color for bleeding from a papilloma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Discharge Color | Common Causes | Characteristics |\n|---|---|---|\n| Red/Bloody | Intraductal papilloma, Ductal Carcinoma In Situ (DCIS), Invasive Carcinoma | Unilateral, single duct, spontaneous |\n| Green/Brown | Duct Ectasia, Fibrocystic Changes | Bilateral, multi-ductal, sticky |\n| White/Milky | Galactorrhea (hyperprolactinemia, medications) | Bilateral, multi-ductal, spontaneous or expressed |\n| Clear/Serous | Fibrocystic Changes, Papilloma, Carcinoma | Unilateral or bilateral, can be single or multi-ductal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Red nipple discharge from a single duct demands investigation for papilloma or cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, an intraductal papilloma may appear as a solid mass within a dilated duct. Ductography (galactography) can visualize a filling defect within the affected duct. Intraoperatively, microdochectomy involves excising the specific duct responsible for the discharge.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Nipple Discharge (2020). Recommends mammography and ultrasound for initial evaluation of pathologic nipple discharge, with consideration for ductography.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | white | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | green | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | yellow | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | red | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
