  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Post-cholecystectomy jaundice? Think stone, not just leak!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, retained CBD stone. The patient's presentation of jaundice, RUQ discomfort, elevated bilirubin and ALP, and a dilated CBD (9mm) post-cholecystectomy are classic signs of biliary obstruction, most commonly caused by a retained stone in this context.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA retained common bile duct (CBD) stone obstructs bile flow, leading to cholestasis. This obstruction causes bile to back up, resulting in jaundice (elevated bilirubin), and increased pressure within the biliary tree, leading to elevated alkaline phosphatase (ALP) and gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT). The CBD dilates proximal to the obstruction as it tries to accommodate the increased pressure. The subhepatic collection could be a reactive fluid collection or a small bile leak due to the high intraductal pressure, but the primary pathology is the obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CBD injury) (Incorrect): While a CBD injury can cause obstructive jaundice and a dilated CBD, it often presents with a more significant bile leak (larger biloma) or a stricture developing later. A retained stone is a more common and direct cause of acute post-cholecystectomy obstructive jaundice with a dilated CBD.\nOption C (slipped clamp) (Incorrect): A slipped clamp typically refers to a dislodged clip on the cystic duct stump, leading to a bile leak and a biloma. This would cause RUQ pain and a subhepatic collection, but it generally does not cause obstructive jaundice or a dilated CBD, as the main bile duct remains patent.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Retained CBD Stone | CBD Injury | Cystic Duct Stump Leak |\n| :------------------ | :----------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Timing** | Early or late post-cholecystectomy | Early post-cholecystectomy | Early post-cholecystectomy |\n| **Jaundice** | Present (obstructive) | Present (obstructive if ligated/transected) | Absent (unless biloma causes extrinsic compression) |\n| **Bilirubin/ALP** | Elevated (obstructive pattern) | Elevated (obstructive pattern) | Normal (unless extrinsic compression) |\n| **CBD Diameter** | Dilated (>8mm post-cholecystectomy) | Dilated (proximal to injury) | Normal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-cholecystectomy jaundice + dilated CBD = retained stone until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a dilated CBD (9mm) would be visible, and often the stone itself can be seen within the duct. MRCP (Magnetic Resonance Cholangiopancreatography) would clearly delineate the dilated CBD and confirm the presence and location of the retained stone(s).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASGE Standards of Practice Committee. The role of endoscopy in the management of choledocholithiasis. Gastrointest Endosc. 2019;89(6):1075-1100. This guideline outlines the diagnostic and therapeutic approach to choledocholithiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CBD injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | retained CBD stone | ✅ Correct |\n| C | slipped clamp (something like that) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
