  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Three days of IV PPI keeps rebleeding away!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 72 hours (D) because current guidelines recommend this duration of intravenous proton pump inhibitor (IV PPI) therapy after successful endoscopic hemostasis for high-risk peptic ulcer bleeding. This sustained acid suppression is critical to prevent rebleeding during the initial vulnerable period.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSuccessful endoscopic hemostasis, often achieved through clipping or thermal coagulation (a 'cleps'), stops active bleeding from a duodenal ulcer. However, the ulcer bed remains susceptible to rebleeding, primarily due to acid-pepsin digestion. IV PPIs provide profound and sustained gastric acid suppression, maintaining an intragastric pH above 6. This elevated pH stabilizes the clot, promotes platelet aggregation, and facilitates healing, significantly reducing the risk of rebleeding. The 72-hour duration is based on evidence demonstrating that this period carries the highest risk of rebleeding, and continuous IV PPI therapy effectively mitigates this risk.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (24 hours) (Incorrect): This duration is generally insufficient for high-risk peptic ulcer bleeding, as the rebleeding risk remains significant beyond 24 hours.\nOption B (36 hours) (Incorrect): While longer than 24 hours, 36 hours still falls short of the guideline-recommended duration for optimal rebleeding prevention in high-risk cases.\nOption C (48 hours) (Incorrect): Although closer, 48 hours does not meet the 72-hour standard established by clinical evidence and guidelines for continuous IV PPI therapy after successful endoscopic hemostasis for high-risk ulcers.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Low-Risk PUD Bleed | High-Risk PUD Bleed (e.g., Forrest Ia, Ib, IIa, IIb) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Endoscopic Findings | Clean base, flat spot, pigmented spot | Active spurting/oozing, visible vessel, adherent clot |\n| IV PPI Duration Post-Endoscopy | Often not required, or short course (e.g., 24h) | 72 hours continuous IV PPI |\n| Oral PPI Duration Post-IV | Standard course (e.g., 4-8 weeks) | Standard course (e.g., 4-8 weeks) |\n| Rebleeding Risk | Low | High (up to 20%) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: High-risk PUD bleed = 72 hours IV PPI.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopically, a successful 'cleps' (clipping or coagulation) of a duodenal ulcer would show a clean ulcer base with no active bleeding, visible vessel, or adherent clot, confirming effective hemostasis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Upper Gastrointestinal and Ulcer Bleeding (2021). Recommends 72 hours of continuous IV PPI after successful endoscopic hemostasis for high-risk peptic ulcer bleeding.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 24 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 36 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 48 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 72 | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
