  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Low fistula, high success with fistulotomy!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nFistulotomy is the correct management for a low perianal fistula with a close opening. This procedure offers the highest success rates with minimal risk of incontinence for appropriately selected low fistulas.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFistulotomy involves unroofing the entire fistula tract, curetting any granulation tissue, and marsupializing the edges. This allows the tract to heal by secondary intention from the base upwards. For low fistulas, which typically involve less than 30-50% of the external anal sphincter, this technique is safe as it preserves sufficient sphincter muscle, thereby minimizing the risk of postoperative fecal incontinence while effectively eradicating the fistula.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Fistulogram) (Incorrect): A fistulogram is a diagnostic imaging technique used to delineate the fistula tract, not a definitive management strategy. While it can be helpful for complex cases, it is not the treatment itself.\nOption C (MRI) (Incorrect): MRI is a highly effective diagnostic imaging modality for mapping the anatomy of perianal fistulas, especially complex ones. However, it is a diagnostic tool, not a surgical management procedure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fistula Type | Description | Management Principle |\n|---|---|---|\n| Low (Intersphincteric/Subcutaneous) | Tract passes through minimal or no external sphincter. | Fistulotomy (high success, low incontinence risk) |\n| High (Transsphincteric/Suprasphincteric/Extrasphincteric) | Tract involves significant portion of external sphincter. | Sphincter-sparing techniques (Seton, LIFT, advancement flap, fibrin glue) |\n| Complex | Multiple tracts, recurrent, associated with Crohn's disease. | Detailed imaging (MRI), staged procedures, Seton placement, biological agents |\n| Abscess | Acute infection, precursor to fistula. | Incision and drainage (I&D) |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Low fistula, simple opening? Fistulotomy is your go-to.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, a low perianal fistula would typically present with a visible external opening, a palpable tract, and a probe easily passing through the tract into the internal opening, confirming a superficial or low intersphincteric course amenable to fistulotomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Anorectal Abscess, Fistula-in-Ano, and Rectovaginal Fistula (2016): Recommends fistulotomy as the primary treatment for low fistulas due to its high success rate and low recurrence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fistulogram | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fistulotomy | ✅ Correct |\n| C | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
