  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Image wisely, operate precisely.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe \"next step\" in an appendicitis scenario is highly dependent on patient demographics and clinical suspicion. While appendectomy is the definitive treatment, imaging is often crucial to confirm the diagnosis or rule out other conditions, with the choice of modality varying based on age and pregnancy status.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe decision-making process for suspected appendicitis prioritizes patient safety and diagnostic accuracy. Ultrasound (US) is favored in children and pregnant patients to avoid ionizing radiation, despite its operator dependence. Computed Tomography (CT) offers higher sensitivity and specificity, making it the preferred initial imaging modality in non-pregnant adults with equivocal clinical findings, as it can also identify alternative diagnoses. A high Alvarado score often indicates sufficient clinical certainty to proceed directly to appendectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Appendectomy) (Incorrect): This is the definitive treatment, not the initial diagnostic step, unless clinical suspicion is extremely high (e.g., high Alvarado score) and diagnosis is clear.\nOption B (US) (Incorrect): While preferred in children and pregnant patients due to radiation concerns, it has lower sensitivity and specificity than CT in adults and is operator-dependent.\nOption C (CT) (Incorrect): While preferred in non-pregnant adults for its diagnostic accuracy, it exposes patients to ionizing radiation, making it less ideal for children and pregnant individuals.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Patient Group | Initial Imaging/Action | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Non-pregnant Adult, equivocal exam | CT abdomen/pelvis | High sensitivity/specificity, rules out other causes, generally preferred |\n| Child, equivocal exam | US abdomen | Avoids ionizing radiation, good initial screen, operator-dependent |\n| Pregnant Patient, equivocal exam | US abdomen | Avoids ionizing radiation, good initial screen, operator-dependent |\n| High Clinical Suspicion (e.g., high Alvarado score) | Appendectomy | Clinical certainty, proceed directly to treatment |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Appendicitis imaging: US for kids/pregnant, CT for adults.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, appendicitis appears as a dilated appendix (>6mm diameter) with wall thickening, periappendiceal fat stranding, and sometimes an appendicolith. On US, it presents as a non-compressible, blind-ending tubular structure with a diameter >6mm, often with a target sign in cross-section and surrounding fluid or hyperechoic fat.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020) recommends a graded approach to diagnosis, prioritizing US in children and pregnant women, and CT in adults with equivocal findings.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Appendectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) Answer is: in adult > C, in child and pregnant > B, in high Alvarado score > A.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
