  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the urethra's in doubt, keep the Foley out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, suprapubic catheter. In cases of suspected blunt urethral trauma, especially in males, a Foley catheter is contraindicated due to the risk of exacerbating the injury, while a suprapubic catheter provides safe bladder drainage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBlunt trauma to the urethra, often associated with pelvic fractures, can lead to partial or complete urethral disruption. Attempting to pass a Foley catheter in this setting can convert a partial tear into a complete one, create a false passage, or introduce infection, significantly increasing patient morbidity. A suprapubic catheter, placed percutaneously into the bladder, bypasses the injured urethra entirely, allowing for bladder decompression and stabilization of the patient without further urethral manipulation. Definitive repair is typically delayed until the patient is stable and inflammation subsides.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Foley catheterization is absolutely contraindicated in suspected urethral injury until a retrograde urethrogram (RUG) has ruled out significant disruption. \nOption C (Incorrect): This is not a medical management option.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Scenario | Initial Management | Diagnostic Study |\n|---|---|---|\n| Suspected Urethral Injury (e.g., blood at meatus, high-riding prostate, pelvic fracture) | Suprapubic Catheter | Retrograde Urethrogram (RUG) |\n| No Suspected Urethral Injury | Foley Catheter | None (if no other indications) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Blood at the meatus? Think suprapubic, not Foley!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA retrograde urethrogram (RUG) is the gold standard for diagnosing urethral injury. It would show extravasation of contrast material outside the urethral lumen, indicating a tear, or a complete transection with no contrast reaching the bladder.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Urethral Trauma (2012, reaffirmed 2017) recommends performing a retrograde urethrogram (RUG) in all patients with suspected urethral injury prior to attempting urethral catheterization.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Foly catheter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | suprapubic catheter | ✅ Correct |\n| C | i don’t remember | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Answer is: B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
