  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Enoxaparin: The hip fracture's best friend against clots.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nEnoxaparin is the correct answer. Patients with hip fractures, especially the elderly, are at high risk for venous thromboembolism (VTE), and low molecular weight heparin (LMWH) like enoxaparin is the preferred agent for prophylaxis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHip fracture patients experience significant immobility, trauma, and often undergo surgery, all contributing to a hypercoagulable state. Enoxaparin, a low molecular weight heparin, provides effective VTE prophylaxis by primarily inhibiting Factor Xa. Its advantages over unfractionated heparin include a longer half-life, predictable pharmacokinetics allowing for subcutaneous administration without routine monitoring, and a lower incidence of heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Heparin) (Incorrect): Unfractionated heparin (UFH) is less effective for VTE prophylaxis in this setting, requires frequent monitoring (aPTT), and carries a higher risk of HIT compared to LMWH.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Unfractionated Heparin (UFH) | Low Molecular Weight Heparin (LMWH) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Administration | IV or SC | SC |\n| Half-life | Short (1-2 hours) | Longer (4-6 hours) |\n| Monitoring | aPTT required | Generally not required (anti-Xa for specific cases) |\n| HIT Risk | Higher | Lower |\n| Factor Inhibition | IIa (thrombin) and Xa | Primarily Xa |\n| Preferred for VTE Prophylaxis in Ortho Trauma | No | Yes (e.g., Enoxaparin) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: LMWH is the standard for VTE prophylaxis in hip fractures.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAn X-ray of the hip would confirm the fracture type and displacement. Intraoperatively, the fracture site would be directly visualized during reduction and fixation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nACCP Guidelines (e.g., 10th edition, 2012) recommend LMWH over UFH for VTE prophylaxis in patients undergoing major orthopedic surgery, including hip fracture repair.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Heparin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Enoxaparin | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Answer is: B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
