  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the urethra's torn, a suprapubic path is born.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Suprapubic catheter. In a patient with a pelvic fracture and a suspected membranous urethral injury, immediate urinary diversion via a suprapubic catheter is the most appropriate initial step to prevent further injury and allow for patient stabilization.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMembranous urethral injuries, often associated with pelvic fractures, are typically posterior urethral injuries. The primary goal of initial management is urinary diversion without further trauma to the urethra. A suprapubic catheter achieves this by bypassing the injured segment, allowing for drainage and preventing extravasation of urine into the pelvic tissues. This approach also permits delayed definitive repair, which has better outcomes as it allows for resolution of inflammation and hematoma, and better assessment of the extent of injury.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Surgery) (Incorrect): Immediate open surgical repair of a membranous urethral injury in the acute setting, especially with an unstable pelvic fracture, is generally contraindicated. It is associated with higher rates of complications, including stricture, impotence, and incontinence, compared to delayed repair after initial suprapubic diversion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Urethral Injury | Initial Management | Definitive Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Anterior Urethral Injury (partial) | Foley catheter (if passable) | Urethroplasty (if stricture develops) |\n| Anterior Urethral Injury (complete) | Suprapubic catheter | Delayed urethroplasty |\n| Posterior Urethral Injury (partial) | Careful Foley catheter attempt or SPC | Delayed urethroplasty (if stricture) |\n| Posterior Urethral Injury (complete) | Suprapubic catheter | Delayed urethroplasty (3-6 months later) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pelvic fracture + urethral injury = suprapubic diversion first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA retrograde urethrogram (RUG) would show extravasation of contrast material from the urethra, indicating a tear or discontinuity. In a complete transection, no contrast would be seen entering the bladder. This confirms the diagnosis and guides the decision for suprapubic diversion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Urethral Trauma (2020) recommend initial urinary diversion with a suprapubic catheter for complete posterior urethral injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Suprapubic catheter | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Answer is: A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
