  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Big polyp, big problem: cut it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that for a 6 cm gallbladder polyp, surgical intervention (cholecystectomy) is the next step. This is because polyps of this size carry a significant risk of malignancy and require definitive management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallbladder polyps are common, but their management depends critically on size and associated risk factors. Polyps greater than 1 cm are generally considered high risk for malignancy and warrant cholecystectomy. A 6 cm polyp is exceptionally large and almost certainly indicates malignancy or high malignant potential, making surgical resection imperative to prevent or treat cancer.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Monitoring with US after 6 months is appropriate for small, asymptomatic polyps (typically < 6-10 mm) without other risk factors, not for a 6 cm polyp which is highly suspicious for malignancy.\nOption B (Incorrect): Liver function tests are part of a general workup but do not address the primary management decision for a large gallbladder polyp. They would not change the indication for surgery.\nOption C (Incorrect): While a CT scan might be used for staging if malignancy is confirmed or suspected, it is not the \"next step\" in management for a 6 cm polyp. The next step is to plan for surgical removal, with CT potentially as part of pre-operative staging.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Polyp Size | Risk of Malignancy | Recommended Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| < 6 mm | Very Low | Monitor with US annually |\n| 6-9 mm | Low to Moderate | Monitor with US every 6-12 months; consider surgery if symptomatic or risk factors |\n| ≥ 10 mm (1 cm) | High | Cholecystectomy |\n| Any size with risk factors (e.g., primary sclerosing cholangitis, Asian ethnicity, sessile, rapid growth) | Increased | Cholecystectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gallbladder polyps > 1 cm or with risk factors require cholecystectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a gallbladder polyp appears as a non-mobile, echogenic lesion protruding into the lumen. A 6 cm polyp would be a very large, often broad-based mass, potentially with internal vascularity on Doppler, raising high suspicion for malignancy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Guidelines on the Management of Gallbladder Polyps (2020). Recommends cholecystectomy for polyps ≥ 1 cm, or polyps 6-9 mm with risk factors, or symptomatic polyps.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Monitor with US after 6 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Liver function test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) Answer is: if 6 cm > surgery, if 0.6 cm > A.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
