  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Adhesions are the silent, sticky legacy of abdominal surgery.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Adhesions are the most common cause of small bowel obstruction (SBO) in patients with a history of prior abdominal surgery, including sleeve gastrectomy, especially several years post-op. The symptoms of abdominal distension and exaggerated bowel sounds are classic for SBO.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdhesions are fibrous bands that form between abdominal organs or between organs and the abdominal wall following surgical trauma or inflammation. These bands can entrap or kink loops of small bowel, leading to mechanical obstruction. While internal hernias are a known complication of bariatric surgery, particularly Roux-en-Y gastric bypass, adhesions remain the leading cause of SBO after any abdominal surgery, including sleeve gastrectomy, with incidence increasing over time. The 6-year interval strongly favors an adhesive etiology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (internal hernia) (Incorrect): While internal hernias can occur after sleeve gastrectomy, they are far less common than after Roux-en-Y gastric bypass, and adhesions are the most prevalent cause of SBO after any abdominal surgery, regardless of type, especially 6 years post-op. \nOption C (Other I exclude) (Incorrect): This is not a specific medical diagnosis and therefore cannot be the correct answer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Adhesions | Internal Hernia |\n| :------------------ | :-------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------- |\n| **Incidence** | Most common cause of SBO after any surgery | More common after RYGB than sleeve gastrectomy |\n| **Onset** | Can occur anytime, often years post-op | Can be early or late, often within first few years |\n| **Mechanism** | Fibrous bands causing kinking/entrapment | Bowel herniates through mesenteric defect |\n| **Imaging Clues** | Transition point, clustered loops, no obvious defect | Swirl sign, clustered loops, specific mesenteric defect |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prior abdominal surgery + SBO = adhesions until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, findings suggestive of SBO due to adhesions include a transition point with dilated proximal bowel and collapsed distal bowel, often without an obvious hernia sac or defect. Intraoperatively, dense fibrous bands would be seen tethering bowel loops.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) 2022 Guidelines for the Perioperative Nutritional, Metabolic, and Nonsurgical Support of Patients Undergoing Bariatric Surgery. These guidelines discuss the management of complications like SBO.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | adhesion | ✅ Correct |\n| B | internal hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Other I exclude | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
