  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ear lobe and jaw numb? Think greater auricular, don't be dumb!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT, the correct answer is the Greater auricular nerve. This nerve provides sensory innervation to the lower half of the ear pinna and the angle of the mandible, precisely matching the patient's reported symptoms after neck surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Greater auricular nerve, originating from the C2 and C3 spinal nerves, is the largest ascending branch of the cervical plexus. It ascends obliquely across the sternocleidomastoid muscle, becoming superficial near its posterior border, making it susceptible to injury during neck dissections, parotidectomy, or other procedures in the posterior cervical triangle. Its sensory distribution includes the skin over the mastoid process, the parotid gland, the angle of the mandible, and the lower two-thirds of the auricle, which aligns perfectly with the patient's numbness.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The Third occipital nerve (C3) supplies sensation to the skin over the lower nuchal region and suboccipital area, not the ear or mandible.\nOption C (Incorrect): The Lesser occipital nerve (C2) provides sensation to the skin over the mastoid process and the upper posterior auricle, but not the angle of the mandible or the lower ear pinna.\nOption D (Incorrect): The Greater occipital nerve (C2) supplies sensation to the posterior scalp up to the vertex, far from the ear or mandible.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Sensory Distribution |\n|---|---|---|\n| Greater Auricular | C2, C3 | Lower 2/3 auricle, angle of mandible, parotid, mastoid |\n| Lesser Occipital | C2 | Upper posterior auricle, mastoid process |\n| Greater Occipital | C2 | Posterior scalp to vertex |\n| Third Occipital | C3 | Lower nuchal region, suboccipital area |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Greater auricular nerve: lower ear, angle of mandible.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the greater auricular nerve can be identified emerging from the posterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, often running superficially towards the ear and mandible. It is a common nerve to be injured or intentionally sacrificed during neck dissections (e.g., modified radical neck dissection) or parotidectomies, leading to the described sensory deficits.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific guideline applies to this fundamental anatomical knowledge. This is a core concept in surgical anatomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Third occipital nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Greater auricular nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Lesser occipital nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Greater occipital nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
