  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the tear is minor and the patient is stable, let nature heal.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Conservative management. Mallory-Weiss tears are typically superficial mucosal lacerations at the gastroesophageal junction that often stop bleeding spontaneously, especially in a hemodynamically stable patient.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMallory-Weiss tears are longitudinal tears of the gastric cardia or distal esophagus, usually precipitated by forceful vomiting or retching. The bleeding originates from submucosal arterioles but is self-limited in 80-90% of cases due to the superficial nature of the tear and the body's intrinsic hemostatic mechanisms. For stable patients, observation, antiemetics, and supportive care are the mainstays of treatment, allowing the tear to heal without intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Endoscopy is primarily indicated for diagnosis and therapeutic intervention (e.g., epinephrine injection, clipping, cautery) in patients with persistent bleeding, hemodynamic instability, or when conservative management fails. It is not the initial management for a stable patient with a typical Mallory-Weiss presentation where bleeding is likely to have ceased or be minimal.\nOption B (Correct): Conservative management is appropriate for stable patients as the bleeding from Mallory-Weiss tears is often self-limiting.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Patient Status | Management | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Stable, self-limiting bleed | Conservative (observation, supportive care) | Most tears stop bleeding spontaneously |\n| Persistent bleeding, unstable | Endoscopy (epinephrine injection, clips, cautery) | Diagnose, achieve hemostasis |\n| Endoscopic failure | Angiographic embolization, surgery (oversewing) | Salvage options for refractory bleeding |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stable Mallory-Weiss = conservative management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, a Mallory-Weiss tear appears as a linear, non-circumferential mucosal laceration, typically at the gastroesophageal junction, often with evidence of recent or active bleeding (e.g., clot, fibrin, oozing).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2021). Recommends conservative management for stable patients with Mallory-Weiss tears that have spontaneously ceased bleeding.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Endoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Conservative | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
