  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Phyllodes: Wide margins prevent recurrence, simple mastectomy often wins.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Simple Mastectomy. Malignant phyllodes tumors are primarily managed by wide surgical excision to achieve clear margins, and simple mastectomy is often the most reliable method to ensure adequate local control and prevent recurrence, especially for larger tumors or when wide local excision would result in poor cosmesis or positive margins.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant phyllodes tumors are biphasic fibroepithelial tumors characterized by stromal overgrowth, increased mitotic activity, and infiltrative borders. Unlike typical breast cancers, they rarely metastasize to regional lymph nodes, making axillary dissection unnecessary in the absence of suspicious nodes. The primary goal of treatment is complete local excision with wide, clear margins (ideally >1 cm) to minimize the high risk of local recurrence. Simple mastectomy reliably achieves these margins, which is crucial as systemic therapies like chemotherapy and radiation have limited efficacy as primary treatment modalities.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (WLEB) (Incorrect): While wide local excision can be considered for smaller malignant phyllodes tumors if adequate margins (>1 cm) can be achieved, simple mastectomy is often preferred for larger tumors or when WLEB would compromise cosmesis or risk positive margins, as local recurrence is a significant concern.\nOption B (Chemo) (Incorrect): Chemotherapy is generally not effective as a primary treatment for malignant phyllodes tumors. It may be considered for metastatic disease, but the question specifies 'no mets'.\nOption C (Radiation) (Incorrect): Adjuvant radiation therapy for malignant phyllodes tumors is controversial and not routinely indicated unless there are positive margins, very large tumors, or high-risk features, and it does not replace the need for adequate surgical excision.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Benign Phyllodes | Borderline Phyllodes | Malignant Phyllodes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Stromal Cellularity | Mild | Moderate | Marked |\n| Mitotic Rate | <5/10 HPF | 5-9/10 HPF | >=10/10 HPF |\n| Margins | Pushing | Pushing/Infiltrative | Infiltrative |\n| Metastasis | Rare | Rare | Hematogenous (rarely nodal) |\n| Primary Management | WLE (1cm margin) | WLE (1-2cm margin) | Simple Mastectomy (or WLE with >1cm margin if feasible) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Malignant phyllodes: wide excision is paramount, simple mastectomy often preferred.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (mammogram, ultrasound), phyllodes tumors often present as rapidly growing, well-circumscribed, lobulated masses, sometimes with cystic degeneration. Intraoperatively, they are typically firm, rubbery, and on cut section, may exhibit a characteristic leaf-like or 'phyllodes' pattern due to stromal proliferation pushing into glandular elements.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024) recommend wide local excision with clear margins (at least 1 cm) or mastectomy for malignant phyllodes tumors, emphasizing the importance of achieving negative margins.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | WLEB | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Chemo | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radiation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) Simple Mastectomy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
