  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a \"jersey finger\" tackle your FDP.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, flexor profundus. The inability to extend the DIP joint after a fall on a stretched hand strongly suggests an injury to the flexor digitorum profundus (FDP) tendon, which is solely responsible for DIP joint flexion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe flexor digitorum profundus (FDP) tendon originates from the ulna and interosseous membrane, passing through the carpal tunnel and inserting onto the distal phalanx of the four medial fingers. Its primary action is flexion of the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint, as well as contributing to PIP and MCP joint flexion. A common mechanism for FDP injury, often termed \"jersey finger,\" involves forced hyperextension of an actively flexing finger, leading to avulsion or rupture of the tendon from its insertion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (flexor superficialis) (Incorrect): The flexor digitorum superficialis (FDS) tendon inserts onto the middle phalanx and primarily flexes the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint. An FDS injury would impair PIP flexion, not DIP extension.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Flexor Digitorum Superficialis (FDS) | Flexor Digitorum Profundus (FDP) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Insertion | Middle phalanx | Distal phalanx |\n| Primary Action | PIP joint flexion | DIP joint flexion |\n| Clinical Test | Isolate finger flexion with other fingers extended | Isolate DIP flexion with PIP/MCP stabilized |\n| Injury Name | - | Jersey Finger (avulsion) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: DIP flexion = FDP. PIP flexion = FDS.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, an avulsion fracture (bony fragment pulled off the distal phalanx) may be visible. MRI can confirm tendon rupture and retraction. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would identify the retracted FDP tendon stump, often requiring retrieval from the palm, and reattach it to the distal phalanx.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Surgery of the Hand (ASSH) Clinical Practice Guidelines (various years) provide recommendations for the diagnosis and management of flexor tendon injuries, emphasizing early surgical repair for optimal outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | flexor superficialis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | flexor profundus | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
