  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't numb the arm, save the intercostobrachial charm!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, the intercostobrachial nerve. This nerve is frequently injured during axillary dissection in a modified radical mastectomy, leading to sensory deficits in its distribution, specifically inner arm numbness.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe intercostobrachial nerve is a purely sensory nerve originating from the lateral cutaneous branch of the second (and sometimes third) intercostal nerve (T2-T3). It traverses the axilla, supplying sensation to the skin of the axilla and the medial aspect of the upper arm. Due to its superficial course through the axillary fat and its proximity to the axillary lymph nodes, it is highly susceptible to stretch, transection, or thermal injury during axillary lymph node dissection, a standard component of modified radical mastectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The long thoracic nerve innervates the serratus anterior muscle. Injury results in a \"winged scapula\" due to paralysis of this muscle, not numbness.\nOption B (Incorrect): The thoracodorsal nerve innervates the latissimus dorsi muscle. Injury leads to weakness in adduction, extension, and internal rotation of the arm, not sensory loss.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Function | Injury Symptom |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Intercostobrachial | T2 (T3) | Sensory to axilla & medial arm | Numbness/dysesthesia in medial arm |\n| Long Thoracic | C5-C7 | Motor to serratus anterior | Winged scapula |\n| Thoracodorsal | C6-C8 | Motor to latissimus dorsi | Weakness in arm adduction/extension/internal rotation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial arm numbness post-mastectomy = intercostobrachial nerve.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the intercostobrachial nerve is often seen as a thin, white, thread-like structure traversing the axillary fat, typically superficial to the axillary vein and often crossing the lateral thoracic vessels. It can be identified and preserved, though sometimes it must be sacrificed for adequate oncologic dissection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (2023). These guidelines emphasize the importance of surgical technique to minimize morbidity, including nerve injury, during axillary dissection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | long thoracic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | thoracodorsal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | intercostobrachial | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
