  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 ERCP + air leak? Think duodenum, then act fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is duodenal perforation. Subcutaneous emphysema, especially tracking widely to the neck, chest, and abdomen after an ERCP, is a classic sign of retroperitoneal air from a duodenal injury.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nERCP involves instrumentation of the duodenum, particularly the periampullary region. The second and third portions of the duodenum are retroperitoneal. A perforation in this area allows air and digestive contents to extravasate into the retroperitoneal space. From there, air can track superiorly along fascial planes into the mediastinum and then into the subcutaneous tissues of the neck and chest, and inferiorly into the abdomen, leading to the widespread subcutaneous emphysema described.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (esophagus) (Incorrect): While esophageal perforation can occur during endoscopy, it is less common with ERCP specifically, and the air tracking would typically be more localized to the mediastinum and neck initially, rather than also involving the abdomen from a primary esophageal injury.\nOption C (trachea) (Incorrect): Tracheal injury is not a complication of ERCP, which involves the gastrointestinal tract. Perforation of the trachea would lead to pneumomediastinum and subcutaneous emphysema, but would not be associated with an ERCP procedure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Mechanism/Location | Clinical Presentation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Duodenal Perforation (ERCP) | Retroperitoneal injury (D2/D3) | Abdominal pain, fever, leukocytosis, retroperitoneal air, widespread subcutaneous emphysema |\n| Esophageal Perforation (Endoscopy) | Direct trauma, usually cervical or thoracic esophagus | Chest/neck pain, dysphagia, fever, cervical subcutaneous emphysema, pneumomediastinum |\n| Pancreatitis (ERCP) | Sphincter of Oddi manipulation, contrast injection | Epigastric pain radiating to back, elevated amylase/lipase, nausea/vomiting |\n| Bleeding (ERCP) | Papillotomy, sphincterotomy | Hematemesis, melena, drop in hemoglobin, hypotension |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Widespread subcutaneous emphysema post-ERCP strongly suggests retroperitoneal duodenal perforation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, you would expect to see retroperitoneal air, often tracking along the psoas muscles and into the mediastinum, possibly with retroperitoneal fluid collections or extravasation of oral contrast if administered. Intraoperatively, a leak of bile or duodenal contents would be visible, often requiring mobilization of the duodenum (Kocher maneuver) to fully assess the posterior aspect.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) guidelines on the management of ERCP-related complications (e.g., 2017 guideline) recommend prompt diagnosis and management of perforations, often involving surgical consultation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | duodenal | ✅ Correct |\n| B | esophagus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | trachea | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
