  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Phyllodes: Cut it out, don't just scan it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nMalignant phyllodes tumors require prompt surgical management. While imaging for distant staging might be considered in specific high-risk cases, the primary next step after diagnosis is typically definitive surgical excision with wide margins, often a simple mastectomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant phyllodes tumors are rare fibroepithelial tumors of the breast. Unlike invasive ductal carcinomas, they are generally not hormone-sensitive, making hormone receptor status less relevant for treatment planning. The cornerstone of treatment is wide surgical excision, aiming for negative margins. Simple mastectomy is often performed to achieve adequate margins, especially for larger tumors or those with close margins after initial excision. Distant metastasis is rare but can occur, primarily to the lungs, bone, and liver.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Contrast ct of chest) (Incorrect): While chest CT might be considered for staging in high-risk malignant phyllodes tumors (e.g., very large size, high mitotic activity, stromal overgrowth, positive margins after initial excision), it is not the immediate next step for all malignant phyllodes tumors. Definitive local control via surgery is paramount.\nOption B (pet scan) (Incorrect): PET scans are generally not routinely recommended for the staging of phyllodes tumors due to their limited utility and high cost compared to conventional imaging like CT for detecting distant metastases, which are themselves rare. Surgical management remains the priority.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Malignant Phyllodes Tumor | Invasive Ductal Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Origin** | Stromal and epithelial components | Epithelial (ductal) cells |\n| **Hormone Receptors** | Generally negative/not relevant | Often positive (ER/PR) |\n| **HER2 Status** | Not typically assessed/relevant | Often assessed (HER2+) |\n| **Primary Treatment** | Wide local excision/Mastectomy | Surgery + Adjuvant (chemo/radiation/endocrine) |\n| **Metastasis** | Hematogenous (lung, bone, liver) | Lymphatic and hematogenous |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Malignant phyllodes: think wide excision, not hormone receptors or routine PET.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, phyllodes tumors can appear as well-circumscribed, lobulated masses, often with cystic areas. Malignant features may include rapid growth, irregular margins, and heterogeneous enhancement. Intraoperatively, they are typically firm, often with a \"leaf-like\" or \"frond-like\" appearance on cut section, and can be quite large.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer (e.g., NCCN Guidelines Version 1.2024). These guidelines recommend wide local excision with negative margins (≥1 cm) or mastectomy for malignant phyllodes tumors. Routine systemic staging with CT or PET is not recommended unless there are specific clinical indications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Contrast ct of chest | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | pet scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) hormone receptor status, more accurate simple mastectomy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
