  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Preserve the greater auricular nerve, or your patient's ear will feel weird!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, the Greater Auricular nerve. This nerve is a superficial branch of the cervical plexus and is highly susceptible to injury during neck dissections due to its anatomical course, leading to sensory deficits in the lower ear and mandibular region.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe greater auricular nerve originates from the C2 and C3 spinal nerves, emerging from Erb's point at the posterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle. It ascends obliquely across the muscle, dividing into anterior and posterior branches to supply sensory innervation to the skin over the parotid gland, the angle of the mandible, and the lower half of the auricle (pinna). Its superficial location makes it particularly vulnerable during surgical procedures like neck dissections, parotidectomies, and even facelift surgeries, making its injury a common cause of the described sensory loss.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Third occipital) (Incorrect): The third occipital nerve provides sensation to the suboccipital region and upper neck, not the ear or mandible.\nOption C (Lesser occipital) (Incorrect): The lesser occipital nerve supplies sensation to the skin behind the ear and the upper part of the posterior scalp, not the lower pinna or mandible.\nOption D (Greater occipital) (Incorrect): The greater occipital nerve provides sensation to the posterior scalp up to the vertex, not the ear or mandible.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Sensory Distribution | Common Injury Site |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Greater Auricular | C2, C3 | Lower auricle, skin over parotid and angle of mandible | Neck dissection, parotidectomy |\n| Lesser Occipital | C2 | Skin behind ear, upper posterior scalp | Neck dissection, mastoidectomy |\n| Greater Occipital | C2 | Posterior scalp to vertex | Suboccipital region trauma, nerve entrapment |\n| Transverse Cervical | C2, C3 | Skin over anterior cervical region | Neck dissection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Neck dissection + ear/mandible numbness = Greater Auricular Nerve.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the greater auricular nerve can be identified emerging from Erb's point, approximately midway along the posterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle. It courses superiorly and anteriorly, often lying superficial to the external jugular vein. Careful identification and preservation are crucial during neck dissections to prevent iatrogenic injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Head and Neck Society (AHNS) and American Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Consensus Statement on the Classification and Terminology of Neck Dissections (2002). This guideline emphasizes meticulous surgical technique to preserve vital neurovascular structures, including sensory nerves, during neck dissections.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Third occipital | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Greater auricle | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Lesser occipital | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Greater occipital | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
