  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Core biopsy: the smart start to sarcoma surgery.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, core biopsy. For suspected limb sarcomas, a core needle biopsy is the preferred method as it provides sufficient tissue for diagnosis and grading while minimizing disruption to tissue planes, which is crucial for subsequent definitive surgical resection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCore needle biopsy allows for accurate histological diagnosis, tumor grading, and molecular profiling, all essential for pre-operative planning and determining the extent of surgical resection (e.g., wide local excision or limb salvage). This minimally invasive approach preserves the integrity of surrounding healthy tissue and avoids contaminating a large surgical field, which is paramount for achieving clear margins during definitive surgery and reducing the risk of local recurrence.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (incisional) (Incorrect): While an incisional biopsy can provide a larger tissue sample, it is generally more invasive than a core biopsy and carries a higher risk of contaminating surrounding tissue planes, potentially complicating future definitive surgery. It is typically reserved for cases where core biopsy is non-diagnostic or insufficient.\nOption B (Excisional) (Incorrect): Excisional biopsy is contraindicated for suspected sarcomas. Performing an excisional biopsy on a sarcoma can compromise limb salvage by creating a large, contaminated surgical field, making it difficult to achieve adequate margins during definitive wide local excision and increasing the risk of local recurrence. It should only be performed for small, clearly benign-appearing lesions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Biopsy Method         | Indication for Soft Tissue Mass                               | Advantages                                                              | Disadvantages                                                                                             | \n|----------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------| \n| **Core Needle Biopsy**   | **Preferred for suspected sarcoma**                           | Minimally invasive, preserves tissue planes, sufficient for diagnosis/grading | May require multiple passes, risk of non-diagnostic sample                                                | \n| Incisional Biopsy    | If core biopsy is non-diagnostic or insufficient              | Larger tissue sample                                                    | More invasive, higher risk of contamination, complicates definitive surgery if not planned carefully    | \n| Excisional Biopsy    | Small, benign-appearing lesions (e.g., lipoma)                | Complete removal of lesion                                              | **Contraindicated for suspected sarcoma**, compromises limb salvage, high risk of recurrence if malignant | \n| Fine Needle Aspiration | Initial assessment, often insufficient for sarcoma diagnosis  | Least invasive                                                          | Often insufficient tissue for grading/subtyping of sarcoma, high false-negative rate                     |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For sarcoma, core biopsy is the diagnostic gold standard to plan definitive surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPre-biopsy MRI is crucial to define tumor extent and guide the biopsy tract. Intraoperatively, the biopsy tract must be excised en bloc with the tumor during definitive resection to prevent local recurrence.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (2023): Recommends image-guided core needle biopsy as the preferred method for diagnosis of soft tissue sarcomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | incisional | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Excisional | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | core biopsy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
