  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Antibiotics first, then investigate, then operate.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Antibiotics. Peritonitis 4 days post-appendectomy, while concerning, often warrants an initial trial of broad-spectrum antibiotics to manage potential infection before considering re-operation, especially if the patient is not in septic shock.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPost-operative peritonitis can stem from residual infection, a stump leak, or a surgical site infection extending into the peritoneum. The initial management strategy for suspected intra-abdominal infection, particularly in a stable patient, involves aggressive fluid resuscitation and prompt initiation of broad-spectrum antibiotics. These antibiotics target common culprits like Gram-negative rods and anaerobes, aiming to control the infection and prevent systemic sepsis. This approach allows time for further diagnostic workup, such as a CT scan, to localize the source and guide definitive management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Laparotomy): Incorrect. While re-exploration may be necessary for uncontrolled sepsis, abscess, or definitive source control, it is not the immediate first step without attempting medical management with antibiotics and further diagnostic imaging, unless the patient is in extremis.\nOption B (Dressing): Incorrect. Dressing changes are appropriate for superficial wound infections or dehiscence, but peritonitis is an intra-abdominal process requiring systemic treatment, not just local wound care.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Scenario | Initial Management | Further Management (if needed) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Post-op Peritonitis (stable) | Broad-spectrum Antibiotics, Fluid Resuscitation | CT scan, Percutaneous Drainage, Laparotomy |\n| Post-op Peritonitis (septic shock) | Resuscitation, Broad-spectrum Antibiotics, Urgent Laparotomy | Source control, ICU care |\n| Superficial Surgical Site Infection | Wound opening, Drainage, Local care | Debridement, Systemic antibiotics (if cellulitis) |\n| Anastomotic Leak (early, contained) | Antibiotics, NPO, Drains | Percutaneous drainage, Endoscopic stenting, Re-operation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-op peritonitis: always start with antibiotics unless clear indication for immediate re-exploration.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis would be crucial, potentially revealing free fluid, localized abscesses, bowel wall thickening, or even a subtle appendiceal stump leak. Intraoperatively, one might find diffuse purulent exudate, localized collections, or evidence of a dehiscence at the appendiceal stump.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Intra-abdominal Infections (2022) recommend prompt initiation of appropriate empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics for patients with suspected intra-abdominal infections, alongside source control when indicated.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Laparotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Dressing | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Antibiotics | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
