  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let pregnancy mask appendicitis; it's a surgical emergency!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, appendicitis. This diagnosis is critical in a pregnant patient presenting with right-sided abdominal pain and fever, especially after obstetric causes have been ruled out. Appendicitis is the most common non-obstetric surgical emergency during pregnancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDiagnosing appendicitis in pregnancy can be challenging due to the physiological changes and anatomical displacement of the appendix. As the uterus enlarges, the appendix can shift superiorly and laterally, altering the classic right lower quadrant pain presentation. However, fever and localized right-sided pain, even if atypical in location, remain strong indicators, necessitating prompt evaluation to prevent perforation, which carries significant maternal and fetal morbidity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (gastritis) (Incorrect): Gastritis typically presents with epigastric pain, often burning, and is less likely to cause fever or localized right-sided pain.\nOption B (pancreatitis) (Incorrect): Pancreatitis usually presents with severe epigastric pain radiating to the back, often associated with nausea/vomiting, and while it can cause fever, the pain location is distinct from right-sided abdominal pain.\nOption C (cholecystitis) (Incorrect): Cholecystitis causes right upper quadrant pain, often postprandial, and can be associated with fever. While possible, appendicitis is more common in pregnancy and the question specifies \"right-sided abdominal pain\" which is broad, but appendicitis is a more acute and common surgical emergency in this context.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Typical Pain Location | Key Features in Pregnancy | Diagnostic Imaging |\n| :-------- | :-------------------- | :------------------------ | :----------------- |\n| Appendicitis | RLQ (can shift superiorly/laterally) | Most common non-OB surgical emergency, fever, N/V | US, MRI |\n| Cholecystitis | RUQ | More common in multiparous women, gallstones, fatty food intolerance | US |\n| Pancreatitis | Epigastric, radiating to back | Severe pain, elevated amylase/lipase, often gallstone-related | US, MRI |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Appendicitis is the most common non-OB surgical emergency in pregnancy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nInitial imaging for suspected appendicitis in pregnancy is ultrasound, which can identify a non-compressible, dilated appendix. If ultrasound is inconclusive, MRI without gadolinium is the preferred next step due to its safety profile in pregnancy and high diagnostic accuracy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety of American Gastrointestinal and Endoscopic Surgeons (SAGES) Guidelines for the Management of Appendicitis (2020) recommends ultrasound as the initial imaging modality in pregnant patients, followed by MRI if ultrasound is non-diagnostic.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | gastritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | appendicitis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
