  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pregnancy doesn't hide appendicitis; it just moves it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Appendicitis. In a pregnant female presenting with right-sided abdominal pain, tenderness, and rebound, appendicitis is the most critical and likely diagnosis requiring urgent surgical evaluation due to its potential for severe maternal and fetal complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAppendicitis is the most common non-obstetric surgical emergency during pregnancy. The gravid uterus can displace the appendix superiorly and laterally, altering the classic right lower quadrant pain presentation, making diagnosis challenging. However, the presence of tenderness and rebound, indicating peritoneal irritation, remains a strong indicator for appendicitis, necessitating a high index of suspicion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Pancreatitis - Incorrect): While pancreatitis can cause abdominal pain, it typically presents with severe epigastric pain radiating to the back, often with nausea and vomiting. Without more specific symptoms or risk factors, it is less likely than appendicitis given general right abdominal pain and rebound.\nOption B (Cholecystitis - Incorrect): Cholecystitis causes right upper quadrant pain, often post-prandial, and can have tenderness and rebound. However, appendicitis is statistically more common as a surgical emergency in pregnancy, and the pain location was not specified as RUQ, making appendicitis a more encompassing and likely diagnosis for 'right abdominal pain'.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Typical Pain Location | Commonality in Pregnancy | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Appendicitis | RLQ (can shift superiorly/laterally) | Most common non-obstetric surgical emergency | Tenderness, rebound, anorexia, nausea |\n| Cholecystitis | RUQ, epigastric | Common, often related to gallstones | Post-prandial pain, nausea, vomiting, fever |\n| Pancreatitis | Epigastric, radiating to back | Less common than appendicitis/cholecystitis | Severe pain, nausea, vomiting, elevated amylase/lipase |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Right abdominal pain + rebound in pregnancy = think appendicitis first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound is the preferred initial imaging modality for suspected appendicitis in pregnancy. A non-compressible, blind-ending tubular structure >6mm in diameter, often with surrounding inflammation, is diagnostic. Laparoscopic appendectomy is generally safe in all trimesters.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 178 (2017) recommends early diagnosis and surgical intervention for appendicitis in pregnancy to minimize maternal and fetal morbidity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Appendicitis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
