  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Unstable GI bleed? Embolize and stabilize!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAngioembolization is the correct answer. In a patient with a large amount of bleeding from angiodysplasia who is hypotensive, immediate and definitive control of the bleeding source is paramount to stabilize the patient.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAngioembolization offers a rapid, minimally invasive approach to achieve hemostasis in hemodynamically unstable patients with acute lower gastrointestinal bleeding. It involves selective catheterization of the bleeding vessel, identified angiographically by contrast extravasation, followed by occlusion using embolic agents. This technique directly addresses the fragile, dilated submucosal vessels of angiodysplasia, providing immediate cessation of hemorrhage without the need for open surgery or potentially difficult endoscopic visualization in a blood-filled lumen.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Endoscopic laser) (Incorrect): Endoscopic therapy, while effective for angiodysplasia, is typically reserved for stable patients or chronic/recurrent bleeding. In a hypotensive patient with a large bleed, visualization may be poor, and the procedure may not be rapid or definitive enough to achieve hemodynamic stability.\nOption B (Conservative) (Incorrect): A hypotensive patient with a large amount of bleeding is hemodynamically unstable and requires active intervention, not conservative management. Conservative management is only appropriate for minor, self-limiting bleeds or after definitive hemostasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Patient Status | Bleeding Severity | Preferred Intervention |\n|---|---|---|\n| Hemodynamically Unstable | Large/Active | Angioembolization (after localization) |\n| Hemodynamically Stable | Active/Recurrent | Endoscopic Therapy (APC, laser, clips) |\n| Hemodynamically Stable | Chronic/Occult | Medical Management (e.g., octreotide, iron supplementation) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unstable GI bleed + identified source = Angioembolization.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAngiography would demonstrate active extravasation of contrast material from the angiodysplasia, pinpointing the bleeding site for targeted embolization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Patients With Acute Lower Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2016). This guideline recommends angiography with embolization for patients with severe, ongoing lower GI bleeding who are hemodynamically unstable, especially when endoscopic hemostasis fails or is not feasible.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Endoscopic laser | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Conservative | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Angioembolization | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
