  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Antibiotics for mastitis, drain only if it's an abscess.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Flucloxacillin. Initial management of mastitis in a lactating woman involves antibiotic therapy to treat the underlying bacterial infection, typically caused by Staphylococcus aureus.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLactational mastitis is an inflammatory condition of the breast, often accompanied by infection, commonly occurring in breastfeeding women. It usually results from milk stasis, which can lead to bacterial entry through cracked nipples. Staphylococcus aureus is the most common causative organism. Flucloxacillin (or dicloxacillin) is a penicillinase-resistant penicillin, making it an excellent first-line choice due to its efficacy against Staph aureus. Continued breastfeeding or milk expression is also crucial to relieve milk stasis and aid recovery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (I & D) (Incorrect): Incision and drainage (I&D) is indicated for a breast abscess, which is a complication of untreated or inadequately treated mastitis. It is not the initial management for uncomplicated mastitis, where antibiotics are the primary treatment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Features | Initial Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mastitis (non-abscess) | Breast pain, redness, warmth, swelling, fever, flu-like symptoms; no fluctuance | Oral antibiotics (e.g., Flucloxacillin), continued breastfeeding/pumping, pain relief |\n| Breast Abscess | Localized, tender, fluctuant mass within the breast; may follow mastitis | Incision & Drainage (or needle aspiration), antibiotics |\n| Engorgement | Bilateral breast fullness, tenderness; no fever or systemic symptoms | Frequent breastfeeding/pumping, warm compresses, pain relief |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Treat mastitis with antibiotics; drain an abscess.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIf clinical suspicion for an abscess is high (e.g., persistent fever despite antibiotics, palpable fluctuant mass), a breast ultrasound should be performed to confirm the presence and location of an abscess, guiding potential aspiration or incision and drainage.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) 2000: Mastitis: Causes and Management. Recommends antibiotic therapy (e.g., dicloxacillin or flucloxacillin) as first-line treatment for infectious mastitis, alongside continued breastfeeding.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Flucloxacillin | ✅ Correct |\n| B | I & D | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
