  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just treat the surface; find the source!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is \"Venous duplex.\" Before performing sclerotherapy for spider veins, it is critical to investigate for underlying venous insufficiency, which is often the root cause of these superficial manifestations. Failure to do so can lead to treatment failure and recurrence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSpider veins, or telangiectasias, are often a cosmetic concern but can be a sign of underlying venous reflux, particularly from the great saphenous vein (GSV), small saphenous vein (SSV), or incompetent perforator veins. A venous duplex ultrasound is a non-invasive, highly accurate imaging modality that allows for comprehensive assessment of the venous system. It can identify valvular incompetence, map refluxing segments, and rule out deep vein thrombosis, ensuring that the primary source of venous hypertension is addressed before or concurrently with superficial treatment. This systematic approach leads to more durable and successful cosmetic outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): \"No investigation needed\" is incorrect because treating spider veins without assessing for underlying venous insufficiency is a common cause of treatment failure and recurrence. It is essential to identify and address the source of venous hypertension to achieve lasting results and prevent complications.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Spider Veins (Telangiectasias) | Reticular Veins | Varicose Veins |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Diameter | < 1 mm | 1-3 mm | > 3 mm |\n| Location | Intradermal | Subdermal | Subcutaneous |\n| Pathophysiology | Often associated with underlying reflux | Often feeding spider veins | Always associated with reflux |\n| Treatment | Sclerotherapy, laser | Sclerotherapy | Sclerotherapy, ablation, phlebectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always rule out underlying reflux before treating superficial venous disease.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn venous duplex ultrasound, you would look for reflux (retrograde flow lasting >0.5 seconds in superficial veins or >1 second in deep veins) in the saphenous veins and perforators, and assess for thrombus. The ultrasound helps map the extent and source of venous insufficiency.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Venous Forum (AVF) and Society for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Varicose Veins and Associated Chronic Venous Diseases (2022). These guidelines recommend duplex ultrasound for the evaluation of symptomatic varicose veins and before any intervention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Venous duplex | ✅ Correct |\n| B | No investigation needed | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
