  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Twisted ovary, urgent surgery!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Ovarian torsion. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the sudden acute onset of abdominal pain in a female patient, coupled with the presence of an ovarian mass on ultrasound. Ovarian torsion is a surgical emergency requiring prompt intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOvarian torsion occurs when the ovary, and often the fallopian tube, twists around its vascular pedicle, leading to venous and lymphatic congestion, followed by arterial compromise. This acute ischemia causes severe, sudden pain. The presence of an ovarian mass, such as a cyst or tumor, significantly increases the risk of torsion by providing a lead point for the twisting. Early diagnosis and surgical detorsion are crucial to preserve ovarian viability.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Rupture of an ovarian cyst can cause sudden acute abdominal pain and may be associated with an ovarian mass. However, the description of \"sudden acute onset\" with an ovarian mass on ultrasound in this context more strongly points to ovarian torsion due to the immediate vascular compromise and time-sensitive nature of the condition, which is a distinct surgical emergency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ovarian Torsion | Ruptured Ovarian Cyst | Ectopic Pregnancy |\n| :----------------------- | :---------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Pain Onset** | Sudden, acute, severe, often colicky | Sudden, acute, sharp | Acute or subacute, often unilateral |\n| **Associated Symptoms** | Nausea, vomiting, fever (late), adnexal mass | Nausea, vomiting, vaginal bleeding (less common) | Amenorrhea, vaginal bleeding, syncope, shoulder pain |\n| **Risk Factors** | Ovarian mass (>5cm), pregnancy, tubal ligation | Functional cysts, trauma, intercourse | Previous ectopic, PID, IVF, IUD |\n| **Ultrasound Findings** | Enlarged ovary, free fluid, \"whirlpool sign\", absent/decreased Doppler flow | Free fluid in cul-de-sac, collapsed cyst, normal flow | Adnexal mass, free fluid, absence of intrauterine pregnancy |\n| **Management** | Surgical detorsion/oophorectomy | Expectant, pain control; surgery for hemorrhage | Medical (methotrexate) or surgical (salpingectomy) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sudden acute pain with an ovarian mass on US? Think torsion, act fast!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, key findings for ovarian torsion include an enlarged, edematous ovary, often with multiple peripheral follicles, free fluid in the cul-de-sac, and a \"whirlpool sign\" of the twisted pedicle. Doppler flow may be absent or diminished, especially venous flow, but arterial flow can be preserved, so its presence does not rule out torsion. Intraoperatively, the ovary will appear congested, edematous, and often purplish-black due to ischemia, with a visibly twisted pedicle.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 174 (2016) on Adnexal Masses. It recommends prompt surgical evaluation for suspected ovarian torsion to preserve ovarian viability.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Rupture of ovarian cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ovarian torsion | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
