  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Foreskin for hypospadias repair: save it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is referral to a pediatric surgeon because circumcision is absolutely contraindicated in the presence of hypospadias, chordee, or a hooded foreskin. These conditions are congenital anomalies that require specialized surgical repair, and the foreskin is often crucial for reconstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypospadias is a congenital malformation where the urethral opening is located on the ventral aspect of the penis, rather than at the tip. Chordee is a downward curvature of the penis, often associated with hypospadias, caused by fibrous tissue. A hooded foreskin, or dorsal hood, is also a common finding in these cases, where the foreskin is deficient ventrally. Performing a circumcision would remove tissue that is often vital for the subsequent reconstructive surgery to correct the hypospadias and chordee, making immediate circumcision inappropriate and potentially complicating future repair.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (open circumcision) (Incorrect): Any form of circumcision is contraindicated in the presence of hypospadias or other penile anomalies, as the foreskin is often needed for reconstructive surgery.\nOption B (plastibell circumcision) (Incorrect): This is a specific method of circumcision, and like any circumcision, it should not be performed when hypospadias, chordee, or a hooded foreskin is present.\nOption C (circumcision with) (Incorrect): This option is incomplete but implies circumcision, which is the incorrect management strategy for a newborn with hypospadias, chordee, and a hooded foreskin.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Description | Management | Contraindications for Circumcision |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Normal Newborn | Urethral meatus at tip, no curvature | Elective circumcision (if desired) | None |\n| Hypospadias | Urethral meatus on ventral aspect of penis | Referral to pediatric urologist/surgeon | **Absolute Contraindication** |\n| Chordee | Downward curvature of penis | Referral to pediatric urologist/surgeon | **Absolute Contraindication** |\n| Hooded Foreskin | Dorsally deficient foreskin, often with hypospadias | Referral to pediatric urologist/surgeon | **Absolute Contraindication** |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Never circumcise a baby with hypospadias; save the foreskin for repair.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, one would observe the urethral meatus located ventrally along the shaft of the penis, rather than at the glans. There might also be a palpable fibrous band causing ventral curvature (chordee) and a dorsally deficient or 'hooded' foreskin, which is often the only part of the foreskin present.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Policy Statement 2012 (reaffirmed 2017): \"Circumcision should not be performed if the infant has a penile anomaly (e.g., hypospadias, chordee, or ambiguous genitalia).\"\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | open circumcision | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | plastibell circumcision | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | circumcision with | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | referral to pedia surgeon | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
