  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let pregnancy mask the appendix; it's still the top surgical emergency!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Appendicitis. This diagnosis is most likely given the patient's right-sided abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting, especially after ruling out pregnancy-related causes. Appendicitis is the most common non-obstetric surgical emergency in pregnancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAppendicitis in pregnancy presents a diagnostic challenge due to the physiological changes and anatomical shifts of the appendix. As pregnancy progresses, the appendix typically migrates superiorly and laterally, often into the right upper quadrant or flank, which can alter the classic right lower quadrant pain presentation. However, right-sided abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting remain hallmark symptoms. Early diagnosis and intervention are crucial as delayed treatment significantly increases the risk of perforation, which carries higher maternal and fetal morbidity and mortality.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Gastritis) (Incorrect): Gastritis typically presents with epigastric pain, burning sensation, and dyspepsia, which is less consistent with the described right-sided abdominal pain.\nOption B (Pancreatitis) (Incorrect): Pancreatitis usually causes severe epigastric pain radiating to the back, often associated with elevated amylase/lipase, and is less likely to present primarily as right-sided abdominal pain.\nOption C (Cholecystitis) (Incorrect): Cholecystitis presents with right upper quadrant pain, often post-prandial, and can radiate to the right shoulder. While possible in pregnancy, appendicitis is statistically more common as a surgical emergency in this context and the pain location is less specific to RUQ.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Typical Pain Location | Associated Symptoms | Diagnostic Challenges in Pregnancy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Appendicitis | Right lower quadrant (can shift to RUQ/flank in pregnancy) | Nausea, vomiting, anorexia, fever | Appendix displacement, physiological leukocytosis, overlapping symptoms with pregnancy |\n| Cholecystitis | Right upper quadrant | Nausea, vomiting, fatty food intolerance, fever | Gallbladder sludge/stones more common, symptoms can mimic other conditions |\n| Pancreatitis | Epigastric, radiating to back | Severe pain, nausea, vomiting, elevated amylase/lipase | Hypertriglyceridemia of pregnancy can be a cause, severe illness |\n| Gastritis | Epigastric | Burning pain, dyspepsia, bloating | Common in pregnancy due to hormonal changes and reflux, usually not right-sided |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Right-sided pain in pregnancy? Think appendicitis first, even with atypical location.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound is the initial imaging modality of choice for suspected appendicitis in pregnancy, looking for a non-compressible, dilated appendix (>6mm). If ultrasound is inconclusive, MRI without gadolinium is the preferred second-line imaging due to its high sensitivity and specificity and lack of ionizing radiation. Intraoperatively, a laparoscopic appendectomy is generally preferred, allowing for direct visualization and minimal invasiveness, though open appendectomy is also safe.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 197 (2018) on Appendicitis in Pregnancy recommends ultrasound as the initial imaging modality and MRI as the preferred second-line imaging.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Appendicitis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
