  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feel the sausage, find the intussusception.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, palpation of a sausage-shaped mass on the abdomen. This finding represents the actual invaginated bowel segment, making it the most direct and diagnostic physical sign of intussusception.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntussusception occurs when one segment of the intestine telescopes into an adjacent segment. The palpable sausage-shaped mass is the intussusceptum itself, typically felt in the right upper quadrant or mid-abdomen. This physical finding directly correlates with the underlying pathology, indicating the presence of the telescoped bowel. While other symptoms are important, this mass is a direct physical manifestation of the condition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Passage of jelly stool, or 'currant jelly stool,' is a classic symptom of intussusception, resulting from sloughed mucosa, blood, and mucus due to bowel ischemia. However, it is a later sign and not as directly diagnostic as palpating the actual intussuscepted bowel. It can also be seen in other conditions causing lower GI bleeding.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Description | Diagnostic Value |\n|---|---|---|\n| Palpable Sausage-shaped Mass | Direct physical finding of the intussusceptum | High (direct evidence of pathology) |\n| Currant Jelly Stool | Blood and mucus from ischemic bowel | Moderate (classic, but late and indirect) |\n| Colicky Abdominal Pain | Intermittent, severe pain with drawing up of legs | High (early and common symptom) |\n| Vomiting | Often bilious, due to bowel obstruction | High (early and common symptom) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sausage mass is intussusception's direct physical sign.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the classic 'target sign' or 'donut sign' (concentric rings of bowel) is seen. In the operating room, the telescoped bowel segment (intussusceptum) is directly visualized and can be manually reduced.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline: Intussusception (2010) - Recommends ultrasound as the primary diagnostic imaging modality for suspected intussusception.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Passage of jelly stool. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Palpation of a sausage shaped mass on abdomen. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
