  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 6mm polyp? Watch and wait, don't operate!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D is the correct answer. For an asymptomatic patient with a 6mm gallbladder polyp, the most appropriate management is surveillance with ultrasound, as immediate surgical intervention is not indicated for polyps of this size without high-risk features.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallbladder polyps are common incidental findings, and their management hinges on size and symptoms. Polyps less than 10mm, especially in asymptomatic patients, have a very low risk of malignancy. The 6mm size falls into a surveillance category, where monitoring for growth or changes is crucial. Cholecystectomy is typically reserved for polyps 10mm or larger, symptomatic polyps, or those with associated risk factors like primary sclerosing cholangitis or Asian ethnicity, which increase the risk of malignant transformation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (No intervention required): Incorrect. While not immediate surgery, surveillance is a form of intervention to monitor for potential changes or growth, which is necessary for polyps of this size.\nOption B (Lap chole): Incorrect. Laparoscopic cholecystectomy is indicated for polyps 10mm or larger, symptomatic polyps, or those with high-risk features. A 6mm asymptomatic polyp does not meet these criteria.\nOption C (Open chole): Incorrect. Open cholecystectomy is generally reserved for cases with contraindications to laparoscopic approach or complex pathology. It is not indicated for a 6mm asymptomatic polyp, nor is it the primary surgical approach for benign gallbladder disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Gallbladder Polyp Size | Symptoms | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| <6mm | Asymptomatic | No routine follow-up (unless risk factors) |\n| 6-9mm | Asymptomatic | Ultrasound surveillance at 6-12 months, then annually if stable |\n| >=10mm | Asymptomatic or Symptomatic | Cholecystectomy |\n| Any size | Symptomatic | Cholecystectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Small, asymptomatic polyps get surveillance, not surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a gallbladder polyp appears as a non-shadowing, non-mobile echogenic lesion protruding into the gallbladder lumen. It is crucial to differentiate true polyps from sludge balls or stones, which are typically mobile and may shadow.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) 2020 Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Gallbladder Polyps. These guidelines recommend surveillance for polyps 6-9mm in asymptomatic patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | No intervention required | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lap chole | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Open chole | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Follow up with US after 6 months | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
