  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a twisted ovary turn into a lost ovary!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Ovarian torsion is the correct answer because this clinical presentation in a young, reproductive-age female with acute, severe RLQ pain, nausea, vomiting, and peritoneal signs (rebound tenderness) is highly suggestive of an acute gynecologic emergency requiring prompt surgical intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOvarian torsion occurs when the ovary and sometimes the fallopian tube twist around the infundibulopelvic ligament and utero-ovarian ligament, compromising its blood supply. Initially, venous and lymphatic outflow are obstructed, leading to edema and congestion. If arterial flow is also compromised, it results in ischemia and necrosis, causing severe, acute pain, often radiating, and associated with nausea and vomiting due to peritoneal irritation. Rebound tenderness indicates peritoneal inflammation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ureterocele) (Incorrect): A ureterocele is a congenital dilation of the distal ureter, typically causing urinary symptoms or obstruction, not acute severe RLQ pain with rebound tenderness.\nOption C (PID) (Incorrect): Pelvic Inflammatory Disease (PID) usually presents with lower abdominal pain, fever, vaginal discharge, and cervical motion tenderness, but severe, acute, unilateral RLQ pain with rebound is less typical than for torsion.\nOption D (Honeymoon cystitis) (Incorrect): \"Honeymoon cystitis\" is a urinary tract infection (UTI) characterized by dysuria, frequency, and urgency, not severe RLQ pain with rebound tenderness.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ovarian Torsion | Acute Appendicitis | Ectopic Pregnancy (ruptured) | PID (severe) |\n| :------------------ | :--------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------- |\n| **Pain Onset** | Sudden, severe, unilateral | Periumbilical migrating to RLQ, gradual to sudden | Sudden, severe, unilateral, often with syncope | Gradual, bilateral lower abdominal |\n| **Associated Sx** | N/V, adnexal mass, stable vitals | N/V, anorexia, fever, leukocytosis | Vaginal bleeding, syncope, hypotension, shoulder pain | Fever, vaginal discharge, cervical motion tenderness |\n| **Exam Findings** | Tenderness, rebound, adnexal mass | RLQ tenderness, rebound, guarding (McBurney's) | Abdominal tenderness, rebound, adnexal mass, shock | Bilateral tenderness, CMT, adnexal tenderness |\n| **Key Diagnostic** | Ultrasound with Doppler (whirlpool sign, absent flow) | CT scan (dilated appendix, fat stranding) | Positive hCG, transvaginal US (adnexal mass, free fluid) | Clinical, elevated inflammatory markers, US (tubo-ovarian abscess) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute RLQ pain in young female? Always consider ovarian torsion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, findings may include an enlarged, edematous ovary, free fluid in the cul-de-sac, and often absent or diminished Doppler flow to the ovary, especially venous flow. A \"whirlpool sign\" of twisted vessels can be seen. Intraoperatively, the ovary will appear enlarged, congested, and dusky or cyanotic due to ischemia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 174 (2016) on Adnexal Masses. It recommends prompt diagnosis and surgical management for suspected ovarian torsion to preserve ovarian viability.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Uretrocele | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ovarian torsion | ✅ Correct |\n| C | PID | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Honeymoon cystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
