  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Foreskin for hypospadias: Save it, don't shave it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct action when encountering mid-shaft hypospadias during a planned circumcision is to refer the patient to a surgical specialist. Circumcision is contraindicated in this scenario because the foreskin is a vital tissue source for future reconstructive surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypospadias is a congenital anomaly where the urethral meatus is located abnormally on the ventral aspect of the penis. The foreskin, often appearing as a dorsal hood with ventral deficiency, is crucial for hypospadias repair, serving as a source for grafts (e.g., preputial flaps) or skin coverage. Performing a circumcision would remove this essential tissue, significantly complicating or precluding a successful single-stage repair. Therefore, referral to a pediatric urologist or plastic surgeon specializing in hypospadias is the appropriate first step for comprehensive evaluation and staged repair planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Do it now\" is incorrect because performing a circumcision would remove the foreskin, which is a critical tissue needed for the subsequent surgical repair of hypospadias.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Not possible since they will use it for the repair,\" while stating a correct reason, is not an action. The question asks \"what to do?\", and the appropriate action is to refer the patient for specialized care, not merely to state a fact.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Urethral Opening Location | Foreskin Management | Surgical Approach |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Hypospadias** | Ventral aspect of penis | **Preserve foreskin** | Staged repair, often using foreskin |\n| **Epispadias** | Dorsal aspect of penis | Often deficient dorsally | Complex repair, bladder exstrophy association |\n| **Normal Circumcision** | Tip of glans penis | Remove foreskin | Elective procedure, no underlying anomaly |\n| **Chordee (isolated)** | Tip of glans penis | Preserve foreskin if needed for skin coverage | Correct curvature, often without hypospadias |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Never circumcise a patient with hypospadias; save the foreskin for repair.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, upon examination, one would observe the urethral meatus located proximally on the ventral aspect of the penile shaft, often accompanied by ventral curvature (chordee) and a characteristic dorsal hood of foreskin with a deficient ventral prepuce.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Management of Hypospadias (2017). It recommends that circumcision should not be performed in infants with hypospadias, and referral to a pediatric urologist is indicated.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Do it now | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Not possible since they will use it for the repair, | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Refere to surgery doctor | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
