  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gallstones come and go, but the pain is unforgettable.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Biliary Colic. This diagnosis perfectly aligns with the clinical presentation of acute, severe right upper quadrant pain that spontaneously resolves, characteristic of transient obstruction of the cystic duct by a gallstone.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBiliary colic occurs when a gallstone temporarily obstructs the cystic duct, leading to increased intraluminal pressure in the gallbladder. This causes visceral pain, typically severe, episodic, and localized to the right upper quadrant or epigastrium, often radiating to the back or right shoulder. The pain resolves when the stone dislodges, allowing bile flow to resume, which explains the spontaneous resolution observed in this child.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Mirrizi syndrome) (Incorrect): Mirizzi syndrome involves persistent obstruction of the common hepatic duct by a stone impacted in the cystic duct or gallbladder neck, leading to jaundice and often inflammation, which would not spontaneously resolve.\nOption B (Renal colic) (Incorrect): Renal colic typically presents with severe flank pain radiating to the groin, often associated with hematuria and dysuria, not primarily RUQ pain.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Biliary Colic | Renal Colic | Acute Cholecystitis |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------ |\n| **Pain Location** | RUQ/Epigastrium | Flank, radiating to groin | RUQ |\n| **Pain Character** | Severe, episodic, crescendo-decrescendo | Severe, colicky, unrelenting | Persistent, severe, often with fever |\n| **Resolution** | Spontaneous (hours) | May resolve with stone passage | Requires intervention, not spontaneous |\n| **Associated Sx** | Nausea, vomiting, post-prandial | Hematuria, dysuria, nausea, vomiting | Fever, leukocytosis, Murphy's sign |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Episodic RUQ pain that resolves spontaneously is classic for biliary colic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAn abdominal ultrasound would typically reveal gallstones within the gallbladder lumen, without evidence of gallbladder wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, or common bile duct dilation, which would suggest cholecystitis or choledocholithiasis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Cholecystitis 2020. These guidelines discuss the differentiation of biliary colic from acute cholecystitis based on clinical and imaging findings.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Mirrizi syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Renal colic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Biliary colic | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
