  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Extend your knowledge: Radial nerve rules forearm extension!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Radial nerve. The patient's inability to extend the forearm, wrist, and fingers, commonly known as 'wrist drop,' is the classic presentation of radial nerve palsy. This nerve is particularly vulnerable in humerus fractures due to its anatomical course.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe radial nerve courses along the spiral groove of the humerus, making it highly susceptible to injury during mid-shaft humerus fractures or subsequent surgical fixation (ORIF). It innervates the triceps brachii (forearm extension), the extensor muscles of the wrist (e.g., extensor carpi radialis longus and brevis), and the extensor muscles of the fingers (e.g., extensor digitorum). Damage to this nerve, therefore, directly results in the described loss of extension capabilities, leading to the characteristic 'wrist drop' deformity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ulnar) (Incorrect): Ulnar nerve injury primarily affects intrinsic hand muscles, causing claw hand deformity and loss of sensation in the medial 1.5 digits, not wrist or finger extension.\nOption C (Median) (Incorrect): Median nerve injury affects most forearm flexors and thenar muscles, leading to 'ape hand' deformity and loss of sensation in the lateral 3.5 digits, not wrist or finger extension.\nOption D (Median) (Incorrect): Same as Option C; median nerve injury does not cause the described extensor deficits.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Key Motor Function | Classic Injury Sign |\n|---|---|---|\n| Radial | Forearm, wrist, and finger extension | Wrist Drop |\n| Ulnar | Intrinsic hand muscles, finger adduction/abduction | Claw Hand |\n| Median | Forearm flexion, thenar muscles, thumb opposition | Ape Hand, Hand of Benediction (proximal injury) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Humerus fracture + wrist drop = Radial nerve until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, a humerus fracture, especially mid-shaft, would be evident, along with the ORIF hardware. Intraoperatively, the radial nerve should be carefully identified and protected, as it lies in close proximity to the bone in the spiral groove, making it vulnerable to direct trauma, entrapment, or iatrogenic injury during screw placement or plate application.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Treatment of Humeral Shaft Fractures (2019) recommends careful assessment for nerve injury, particularly radial nerve, both pre- and post-operatively.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ulnar … | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Radial … | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Median … | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Median …. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
