  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Phyllodes: Wide excision, clear margins, no games.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Wide Local Excision (WLE). Phyllodes tumors, regardless of their benign, borderline, or malignant classification, require surgical excision with clear margins to minimize the risk of local recurrence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhyllodes tumors are biphasic fibroepithelial tumors of the breast with a stromal component that dictates their biological behavior. Due to their propensity for local recurrence, especially if margins are involved, WLE with at least a 1 cm clear margin is the standard of care for tumors up to 5 cm. This approach aims to remove the entire tumor while preserving as much breast tissue as possible, balancing oncologic safety with cosmetic outcome. The 4x5 cm size fits well within the scope for WLE.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Simple mastectomy) (Incorrect): A simple mastectomy is generally considered overtreatment for a 4x5 cm phyllodes tumor unless it is recurrent, very large, or has extensive malignant features not amenable to WLE. WLE is usually sufficient.\nOption C (Chemo) (Incorrect): Chemotherapy is not a primary treatment modality for phyllodes tumors. It is rarely used, primarily in the setting of metastatic malignant phyllodes, not for initial local management.\nOption D (Radio) (Incorrect): Radiotherapy is not a primary treatment for phyllodes tumors. Adjuvant radiotherapy may be considered for large malignant phyllodes or in cases of positive surgical margins after WLE, but it is not the initial management.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Phyllodes Tumor (Benign/Borderline) | Malignant Phyllodes Tumor | Fibroadenoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Management | WLE with clear margins (1cm) | WLE with wider margins (1-2cm) or Mastectomy if large/recurrent | Excision if symptomatic/growing/large |\n| Recurrence Risk | Local recurrence possible if margins positive | Higher risk of local recurrence and distant mets | Rare recurrence |\n| Adjuvant Therapy | Rarely indicated | Radiotherapy for positive margins, Chemo for mets | Not indicated |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Phyllodes tumors require wide local excision with clear margins.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (ultrasound/mammogram), phyllodes tumors often appear as well-circumscribed, lobulated masses, sometimes with cystic areas, and can be difficult to distinguish from fibroadenomas. Intraoperatively, they are typically firm, mobile, and well-encapsulated, but can grow rapidly and distort breast architecture.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer, Version 1.2024, recommends wide local excision with clear margins (typically 1 cm) for phyllodes tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Simple mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | WLE | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Chemo | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Radio | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
