  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When blood and inversion meet, the duct must go.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is WLE (Wide Local Excision), often performed as a microdochectomy or total duct excision. This is the appropriate next step for a patient presenting with spontaneous, unilateral bloody nipple discharge and a new inverted nipple, as these are highly suspicious signs for an underlying intraductal pathology, potentially malignant. WLE serves both diagnostic and therapeutic purposes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWLE, specifically microdochectomy or total duct excision, involves excising the affected duct or the entire duct system beneath the nipple. This procedure allows for complete histological evaluation of the lesion causing the discharge, which is crucial for definitive diagnosis (e.g., intraductal papilloma, DCIS, or invasive carcinoma). The anatomical precision of excising the involved duct ensures removal of the pathology, often resolving the discharge and providing clear margins if malignancy is present.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Core biopsy) (Incorrect): Core biopsy is less effective for intraductal lesions causing nipple discharge, as it may miss the pathology within the ductal system, leading to false negatives. It's better suited for palpable masses.\nOption C (Simple mastectomy) (Incorrect): Simple mastectomy is an overly aggressive and inappropriate initial step without a definitive diagnosis of malignancy. It is a treatment, not a diagnostic procedure.\nOption D (FNA) (Incorrect): Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA) has very low sensitivity for nipple discharge and intraductal lesions. It cannot reliably distinguish between benign, atypical, or malignant intraductal pathologies and is generally not recommended for nipple discharge evaluation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Presentation | Initial Workup | Management/Next Step |\n| :-------------------- | :------------- | :------------------- |\n| Spontaneous, unilateral bloody nipple discharge | Mammogram, Ultrasound, +/- MRI, Ductography | Microdochectomy/Total Duct Excision (WLE) |\n| Spontaneous, bilateral multi-ductal non-bloody discharge | Clinical exam, Mammogram, Ultrasound, Prolactin/TSH | Observation, endocrine evaluation if indicated |\n| Nipple discharge with associated palpable mass | Mammogram, Ultrasound, Core Biopsy of mass | Excision of mass +/- duct excision based on biopsy |\n| New onset inverted nipple | Mammogram, Ultrasound, Clinical exam | Excisional biopsy/WLE if suspicious, otherwise observation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unilateral bloody nipple discharge + new inversion = duct excision.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (mammogram, ultrasound, MRI) may show ductal ectasia, an intraductal mass, or microcalcifications. Ductography can delineate the affected duct and identify filling defects. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would identify the discharging duct (often by cannulating it or observing discharge with pressure) and excise it along with surrounding tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBrS) Consensus Guideline on the Management of Nipple Discharge (2016). It recommends surgical excision for spontaneous, unilateral, single-duct bloody or serosanguinous nipple discharge.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | WLE | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Core biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Simple mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | FNA | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
