  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Axillary numbness? Blame the intercostobrachial nerve!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Intercostobrachial nerve. This nerve is a purely sensory nerve that innervates the axilla and medial upper arm, making its injury during mastectomy with axillary dissection the direct cause of the described symptoms.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe intercostobrachial nerve (ICBN) is a sensory nerve, typically a lateral cutaneous branch of the second intercostal nerve (T2), sometimes with contributions from T3. It traverses the axilla, often piercing the serratus anterior muscle, and provides sensation to the skin of the axilla, medial arm, and sometimes the chest wall. Due to its superficial course through the axillary fat and lymph nodes, it is highly susceptible to transection or traction injury during axillary lymph node dissection (ALND) or even sentinel lymph node biopsy, leading to the common complaint of paraesthesia and numbness in its distribution.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Injury to the long thoracic nerve (C5-C7) paralyzes the serratus anterior muscle, resulting in a 'winged scapula' (scapular winging), not sensory deficits.\nOption B (Incorrect): Injury to the thoracodorsal nerve (C6-C8) paralyzes the latissimus dorsi muscle, causing weakness in arm adduction, extension, and internal rotation, not sensory loss in the upper arm/axilla.\nOption D (Incorrect): Injury to the medial pectoral nerve (C8-T1) affects the pectoralis major and minor muscles, leading to weakness in arm adduction and internal rotation, and potentially pectoralis muscle atrophy, not sensory symptoms in the specified area.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Function | Consequence of Injury |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Intercostobrachial | T2 (T3) intercostal | Sensory to axilla, medial arm | Paraesthesia, numbness (Post-Mastectomy Pain Syndrome) |\n| Long Thoracic | C5-C7 | Motor to serratus anterior | Winged scapula |\n| Thoracodorsal | C6-C8 | Motor to latissimus dorsi | Weakness of arm adduction, extension, internal rotation |\n| Medial Pectoral | C8-T1 | Motor to pectoralis major/minor | Weakness of arm adduction, internal rotation, pectoralis atrophy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intercostobrachial nerve injury = axillary/medial arm numbness post-mastectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the intercostobrachial nerve can be identified as a thin, white, cord-like structure traversing the axillary fat, typically running obliquely across the axilla. Surgeons often attempt to identify and preserve it during axillary lymph node dissection to minimize sensory deficits.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (e.g., Version 3.2023). These guidelines emphasize careful surgical technique during axillary dissection to minimize morbidity, including nerve injury, and discuss management of post-mastectomy pain syndrome.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Long thoracic nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thoracodorsal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Intercostobrachial nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Medial pectoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
