  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When legs are pigmented but pulses are strong, ultrasound is the song!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation of pigmentation with intact femoral and distal pulses strongly suggests chronic venous insufficiency (CVI). In this scenario, the next best step is to perform a US duplex to evaluate the venous system for reflux and obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUS duplex is the gold standard non-invasive diagnostic tool for chronic venous insufficiency. It allows for real-time visualization of venous anatomy, assessment of valvular function (identifying reflux), and detection of venous obstruction or thrombus. This dynamic evaluation is crucial for quantifying reflux time, identifying incompetent perforator veins, and guiding subsequent management strategies for CVI, all without radiation or contrast.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CT venography - Incorrect): CT venography involves radiation and intravenous contrast, and while it can visualize venous anatomy and detect acute deep vein thrombosis (DVT) or central venous obstruction, it is not the primary or best initial test for evaluating chronic venous insufficiency or valvular incompetence. It provides static images and is less effective than duplex ultrasound for assessing dynamic venous reflux.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | US Duplex | CT Venography |\n|---|---|---|\n| Primary Use | Chronic Venous Insufficiency (CVI), DVT, Venous Mapping | Acute DVT (complex), Central Venous Obstruction, Detailed Anatomy |\n| Mechanism | Ultrasound waves, Doppler flow | X-rays, IV contrast |\n| Reflux Assessment | Excellent (dynamic, real-time) | Poor (static images) |\n| Radiation/Contrast | None | Yes (radiation, IV contrast) |\n| Cost/Availability | Lower, widely available | Higher, less available for routine CVI |\n| Patient Comfort | High | Moderate (IV, scanner) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pigmentation + intact pulses = suspect CVI, image with US duplex.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn US duplex, you would expect to see dilated superficial or deep veins, incompetent venous valves with prolonged reflux (flow reversal exceeding 0.5 seconds in superficial veins or 1.0 second in deep veins) during Valsalva maneuver or distal compression, and potentially evidence of post-thrombotic changes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) and American Venous Forum (AVF) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Venous Ulcers (2014) recommend duplex ultrasound as the initial diagnostic test for patients with suspected chronic venous disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT venography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | US duplex | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
