  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When scopes are clear, but blood still flows, the capsule knows where the small bowel goes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with obscure gastrointestinal bleeding (OGIB), characterized by both melena and hematochezia, after normal upper and lower endoscopies. Capsule endoscopy is the appropriate next diagnostic step to evaluate the small bowel, which is the most common source of OGIB.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCapsule endoscopy is a non-invasive diagnostic tool that allows for direct visualization of the entire small bowel mucosa, an area not accessible by conventional upper or lower endoscopy. It is highly effective in identifying lesions such as angioectasias, ulcers, tumors, or inflammatory conditions that cause obscure GI bleeding, making it the gold standard for small bowel evaluation in this context.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Isotope scan) (Incorrect): Isotope scans (e.g., Tc-99m tagged RBC scan) are primarily indicated for active, rapid GI bleeding (typically >0.1-0.5 mL/min) to localize the bleeding source. Given the \"sometimes blood per rectum\" and the chronicity implied by melena, the bleeding is likely intermittent or slow, making capsule endoscopy a more sensitive and specific diagnostic tool for identifying the underlying lesion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Indication | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| EGD/Colonoscopy | Upper/Lower GI bleeding | Direct visualization, biopsy, therapy | Limited to proximal/distal GI tract |\n| Capsule Endoscopy | Obscure GI bleeding (small bowel) | Non-invasive, full small bowel view | No biopsy/therapy, can miss rapid bleeding |\n| CT Angiography | Active, rapid GI bleeding | Localizes active bleeding, non-invasive | Requires active bleeding (>0.3-0.5 mL/min), radiation |\n| Tc-99m Tagged RBC Scan | Intermittent/slow active GI bleeding | Detects slower bleeding (>0.1 mL/min), non-invasive | Poor localization, no therapy, radiation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Normal EGD/colonoscopy + OGIB = Capsule Endoscopy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCapsule endoscopy would reveal mucosal lesions within the small bowel, such as angioectasias, ulcers, polyps, or tumors, which are the source of the bleeding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Diagnosis and Management of Small Bowel Bleeding (2021). It recommends capsule endoscopy as the initial diagnostic test for obscure GI bleeding after negative upper and lower endoscopies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Endoscopy capsule | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Isotope scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Can’t remember the rest but no tec-99 or tagged RBCs)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
