  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 If pain wakes you, it's not a dream, it's a disease!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is B because pain that consistently awakens a patient from sleep is a strong indicator of organic pathology, distinguishing it from functional or psychological pain.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPain that disrupts sleep, particularly 'before awakening' or in the early morning hours, often signifies an underlying organic process. This is because physiological processes like inflammation, ischemia, or increased visceral activity (e.g., gastric acid secretion in peptic ulcer disease) can intensify during rest or specific circadian rhythms, leading to discomfort severe enough to rouse a patient. Functional pain, in contrast, rarely has this characteristic.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Pain occurring 'Before sleep time' is non-specific and can be associated with both organic and functional etiologies, offering no clear distinction for organic pain.\nOption C (Incorrect): This option is incomplete and cannot be evaluated as a valid choice.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Organic Pain | Functional Pain |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Timing** | Often wakes from sleep, constant, progressive | Variable, rarely wakes from sleep, often stress-related |\n| **Character** | Localized, specific, burning, cramping, sharp | Diffuse, vague, dull, aching |\n| **Associated Symptoms** | Weight loss, fever, bleeding, vomiting | Bloating, altered bowel habits (IBS), fatigue |\n| **Relief** | Specific treatments, antacids (ulcer) | Stress reduction, lifestyle changes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pain that wakes you up is usually organic, not just in your head.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile no image was provided, organic pain often correlates with visible findings on imaging or endoscopy, such as an ulcer on EGD, inflammation on CT (e.g., diverticulitis), or a mass on ultrasound. Intraoperatively, one might find adhesions, perforations, or inflammatory changes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guidelines for the Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017) recommend investigating nocturnal pain as a symptom suggestive of active ulcer disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Before sleep time. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Before awakening. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Two choices I forgot it | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
