  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bloody discharge? Mammogram first, no excuses!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nMammogram is the correct initial investigation for a 40-year-old patient presenting with bloody nipple discharge, even with a normal physical exam. This symptom is concerning for underlying pathology, including malignancy, and requires prompt and appropriate imaging evaluation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBloody nipple discharge, especially if spontaneous and unilateral, is a red flag symptom that necessitates a thorough workup to rule out malignancy (e.g., intraductal papilloma, ductal carcinoma in situ, or invasive carcinoma). Mammography is the gold standard initial imaging modality for breast evaluation in women over 30-35 years old. It effectively visualizes microcalcifications, masses, and architectural distortions that may be the source of the discharge, guiding further diagnostic steps like ultrasound or biopsy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (US) (Incorrect): While ultrasound is an excellent adjunct to mammography, especially for characterizing palpable masses or in dense breasts, it is not typically the *initial* standalone investigation for bloody nipple discharge in this age group. It's often used to further evaluate findings from a mammogram or to guide procedures.\nOption C (MRI) (Incorrect): Breast MRI is a highly sensitive tool but is generally reserved for specific indications such as high-risk screening, staging of known cancer, or evaluating implant integrity. It is not the initial imaging modality for bloody nipple discharge due to its higher cost, limited availability, and potential for false positives.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Primary Role in Bloody Nipple Discharge (40 y/o) | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n| :--------------- | :----------------------------------------------- | :--------- | :------------ |\n| Mammogram        | Initial diagnostic tool to detect masses/calcifications | Widely available, standard, good for calcifications | Less sensitive in dense breasts, radiation exposure |\n| Ultrasound       | Adjunct to mammogram, characterize masses, guide biopsy | No radiation, good for cysts/solid masses, dense breasts | Operator dependent, limited field of view |\n| MRI              | Problem-solving, staging, high-risk screening (not initial) | High sensitivity, good for dense breasts | High cost, contrast required, false positives |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bloody nipple discharge in a 40-year-old means mammogram first, always.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, the source of bloody discharge might appear as a mass, architectural distortion, or suspicious microcalcifications. If mammogram and ultrasound are inconclusive, ductography (galactography) can be performed to inject contrast into the discharging duct and visualize intraductal lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Nipple Discharge (2017) recommends mammography as the initial imaging study for women aged 30 and older presenting with nipple discharge, often followed by targeted ultrasound.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mammogram | ✅ Correct |\n| C | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
