  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Post-PTC bleed? CT angio first, then embolize fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is CT angiography. Post-percutaneous transhepatic cholangiography (PTC) upper GI bleeding strongly suggests hemobilia, a serious complication requiring prompt diagnosis and management. CT angiography is the most appropriate initial investigation to localize the source of bleeding within the liver or biliary system.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPTC is an invasive procedure that can lead to vascular injury, most commonly involving hepatic arteries or portal veins, resulting in hemobilia. This bleeding into the biliary tree can manifest as upper GI bleeding. CT angiography is the gold standard for detecting active arterial extravasation, pseudoaneurysms, or arteriovenous fistulas within the liver parenchyma or biliary system. Its ability to precisely localize the bleeding source is crucial for guiding subsequent therapeutic interventions like transarterial embolization, which is often definitive.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Endoscopy) (Incorrect): While endoscopy can confirm upper GI bleeding, it is often insufficient to identify the source of hemobilia originating from within the liver or biliary tree, especially if the bleeding is intermittent or from a small vessel not directly visible in the duodenum.\nOption C (US) (Incorrect): Ultrasound is a good initial imaging modality for the liver and biliary system but has limited sensitivity for detecting active bleeding or small vascular lesions like pseudoaneurysms, making it less effective for localizing the source of hemobilia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Indication | Pros | Cons |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| CT Angiography | Suspected hemobilia/vascular injury post-PTC | Localizes active bleeding, identifies pseudoaneurysms/fistulas, guides embolization | Radiation exposure, contrast risk, may miss very slow bleeds |\n| Endoscopy (EGD) | Upper GI bleeding, rule out mucosal lesions | Direct visualization of gastric/duodenal mucosa, therapeutic options for luminal bleeding | Poor for intrahepatic source, may miss intermittent hemobilia |\n| Ultrasound (US) | Initial liver/biliary assessment, rule out bile duct dilation | Non-invasive, no radiation, readily available | Limited sensitivity for active bleeding or small vascular lesions |\n| Angiography (DSA) | Definitive diagnosis & treatment (embolization) | Gold standard for localization & treatment of arterial bleeding | Invasive, higher radiation/contrast, usually performed after CT angio localization |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-procedural GI bleeding? CT angio localizes the source for intervention.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT angiography, look for active contrast extravasation within the liver parenchyma or biliary tree, or the presence of a pseudoaneurysm or arteriovenous fistula, which would appear as a focal collection of contrast or an early draining vein.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria® Acute Gastrointestinal Hemorrhage (2021) recommends CT angiography as a highly appropriate imaging modality for suspected active GI bleeding, especially when endoscopy is negative or the source is obscure, due to its ability to localize the bleeding site.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Endoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT angio | ✅ Correct |\n| C | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
