  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, rest it out, especially with a bleed on anticoagulation!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, rest and analgesics, because rectus sheath hematomas (RSH) are typically self-limiting and resolve with conservative management in stable patients. Given the patient's anticoagulation, avoiding invasive procedures is paramount unless absolutely necessary.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRectus sheath hematomas occur due to rupture of the epigastric arteries or their branches, often precipitated by increased intra-abdominal pressure (like lifting) or trauma, particularly in patients on anticoagulation. The rectus sheath contains the hematoma, which usually tamponades itself. Conservative management with pain control, fluid resuscitation if needed, and temporary cessation or reversal of anticoagulation (if severe and not contraindicated) is the mainstay. Surgical intervention or angioembolization is reserved for hemodynamic instability, expanding hematoma, or failure of conservative measures.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (angioembolization and …): Incorrect. Angioembolization is an invasive procedure reserved for cases of active bleeding with hemodynamic instability or failure of conservative management. It is not the initial most appropriate management for a stable patient with RSH, especially when conservative measures are highly effective.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Rectus Sheath Hematoma (RSH) | Inguinal Hernia | Appendicitis |\n| :------------------ | :--------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------ |\n| **Onset** | Sudden, often after strain/trauma | Gradual or sudden, often with strain | Gradual, periumbilical migrating to RLQ |\n| **Mass** | Fixed, often palpable, *does not change with cough* | Reducible, often changes with cough/Valsalva | No palpable mass (unless abscess) |\n| **Cough Test** | Negative (mass does not protrude/change) | Positive (mass protrudes/expands) | N/A (pain worsens with cough, but no mass change) |\n| **Muscle Tense** | Yes, even with clenching (hematoma within muscle/sheath) | No, unless incarcerated/strangulated | Yes, guarding/rigidity |\n| **Risk Factors** | Anticoagulation, trauma, coughing, abdominal surgery | Increased intra-abdominal pressure, male sex, age | Fecalith, lymphoid hyperplasia |\n| **Initial Mgmt** | Conservative (rest, analgesia, reverse anticoagulation if severe) | Elective surgical repair | Surgical appendectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Anticoagulation + RLQ mass + negative cough = Rectus Sheath Hematoma, manage conservatively.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT scan of the abdomen and pelvis would show a well-defined, high-attenuation collection within the rectus abdominis muscle or between the muscle and its posterior sheath, often with active extravasation if bleeding is ongoing.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines for Antithrombotic Therapy and Prevention of Thrombosis (e.g., 2012 or later editions) would discuss management of bleeding complications in anticoagulated patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | angioembolization and … | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | rest and analgesic | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
