  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a Jersey finger retract to the palm, catch it early!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Rupture of flexor profundus. This diagnosis perfectly aligns with the clinical presentation of a hyperextension trauma causing distal phalanx pain and volar tenderness, coupled with tenderness in the palm, which indicates proximal retraction of the avulsed tendon.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA rupture of the flexor digitorum profundus (FDP) tendon, often termed a 'Jersey finger,' typically results from forced hyperextension of the DIP joint while the finger is actively flexing. The FDP tendon inserts onto the volar base of the distal phalanx, and its avulsion leads to an inability to actively flex the DIP joint. The characteristic tenderness in the palm arises from the elastic recoil and retraction of the severed FDP tendon, which can pull it proximally into the palm or even forearm, making it a critical diagnostic clue.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Rupture of flexor superficialis would primarily affect the PIP joint and would not typically cause isolated distal phalanx pain or palm tenderness from tendon retraction in this manner.\nOption C (Incorrect): An intra-articular fracture of the proximal phalanx, while possible with hyperextension, would not explain the specific volar distal phalanx tenderness combined with palm tenderness indicative of tendon retraction.\nOption D (Incorrect): An extra-articular fracture of the distal phalanx would cause distal phalanx pain but would not account for the tenderness in the palm, which strongly suggests a retracted tendon.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Mechanism | Key Symptoms | Physical Exam Finding |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| FDP Rupture (Jersey Finger) | Forced hyperextension of DIP joint | Distal phalanx pain (volar), palm tenderness | Inability to actively flex DIP joint |\n| FDS Rupture | Laceration or forceful extension of PIP joint | Middle phalanx pain (volar) | Inability to actively flex PIP joint (with other fingers held extended) |\n| Mallet Finger | Forced flexion of DIP joint | Distal phalanx pain (dorsal) | Inability to actively extend DIP joint |\n| Phalanx Fracture | Direct trauma, crush, or hyperextension | Localized pain, swelling, deformity | Tenderness over bone, crepitus, limited range of motion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hyperextension + distal phalanx pain + palm tenderness = FDP avulsion (Jersey finger).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPlain radiographs are essential to rule out an avulsion fracture (Type II, III, IV Jersey finger). MRI can confirm soft tissue rupture and locate the retracted tendon. Intraoperatively, the surgeon will identify the retracted FDP tendon, often found in the palm, and reattach it to the distal phalanx.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Surgery of the Hand (ASSH) Flexor Tendon Injury Guidelines (2019) recommend early surgical repair for FDP avulsions to prevent tendon shortening and improve functional outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Rupture of flexor profundus | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Rupture of flexor superficialis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | intra-articular fracture of proximal phalanx | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | extra-articular fracture of distal phalanx | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
