  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Adult intussusception: When bowel telescopes, cut it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Surgical resection. Adult intussusception is a rare condition, and unlike in children, it is almost always secondary to a pathological lead point, such as a tumor (benign or malignant), polyp, or Meckel's diverticulum. Therefore, definitive surgical management is required to address both the intussusception and its underlying cause.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSurgical resection involves identifying the intussuscepted segment of bowel and excising it along with the causative lead point. This approach is crucial because attempting manual reduction without resection carries a high risk of recurrence, perforation, or disseminating malignant cells if the lead point is cancerous. Following resection, primary anastomosis is typically performed to restore bowel continuity, ensuring both resolution of the obstruction and definitive treatment of the underlying pathology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Surgical decompression) (Incorrect): While decompression might be part of managing severe obstruction, it does not address the intussusception itself or its underlying cause, which is critical in adults.\nOption C (Colonoscopy q) (Incorrect): Colonoscopy can be diagnostic for colonic intussusception and may sometimes reduce it, but it is not the definitive management, especially if a lead point is suspected or if the intussusception is in the small bowel. It does not remove the lead point.\nOption D (Enema) (Incorrect): Enema reduction (air or hydrostatic) is the primary non-operative treatment for pediatric intussusception. However, it is generally contraindicated in adults due to the high likelihood of a pathological lead point and the increased risk of perforation, especially with ischemic bowel.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pediatric Intussusception | Adult Intussusception |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Often idiopathic (viral), Peyer's patch hypertrophy | Pathological lead point (e.g., tumor, polyp, Meckel's) |\n| **Management** | Non-operative enema reduction (air/hydrostatic) | Surgical resection of involved segment and lead point |\n| **Malignancy Risk** | Very low | High (up to 50% for colonic, 25% for small bowel) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adult intussusception = surgical resection for the underlying lead point.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, intussusception typically appears as a 'target sign' or 'sausage-shaped mass' due to layers of bowel within bowel. Intraoperatively, one would observe a segment of bowel telescoped into an adjacent segment, often with associated edema and possibly signs of ischemia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWhile there isn't one specific guideline solely for adult intussusception, general surgical principles for bowel obstruction and management of suspected intra-abdominal masses, as outlined by organizations like the American College of Surgeons (ACS) or the American Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS), guide the decision for surgical resection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Surgical resection | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Surgical decompression | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Colonoscopy q | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Enema | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Answer is: A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
