  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Thenar atrophy, intact thenar sensation: think median nerve, carpal tunnel!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Median nerve. The clinical presentation of thenar muscle atrophy with preserved sensation over the thenar eminence is highly characteristic of a median nerve injury, specifically carpal tunnel syndrome. This scenario highlights the unique anatomical course of the palmar cutaneous branch of the median nerve.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe median nerve provides motor innervation to the thenar muscles, including the abductor pollicis brevis, opponens pollicis, and superficial head of the flexor pollicis brevis. Atrophy of these muscles directly points to median nerve dysfunction. Crucially, the palmar cutaneous branch of the median nerve, which supplies sensation to the thenar eminence, typically branches off proximal to the carpal tunnel and travels superficial to the transverse carpal ligament. Therefore, in carpal tunnel syndrome, where the median nerve is compressed within the carpal tunnel, the motor fibers are affected, but the palmar cutaneous branch and its sensory supply to the thenar eminence are often spared, leading to the described clinical picture.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Radial) (Incorrect): The radial nerve primarily innervates the extensor muscles of the wrist and fingers and provides sensation to the dorsum of the hand, not the thenar muscles.\nOption C (Axillary) (Incorrect): The axillary nerve innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles and provides sensation over the lateral shoulder, with no involvement in hand function.\nOption D (Ulnar) (Incorrect): The ulnar nerve innervates most of the intrinsic hand muscles (hypothenar, interossei, adductor pollicis) and provides sensation to the ulnar side of the hand, but it does not innervate the thenar muscles responsible for the atrophy described.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Key Motor Innervation | Key Sensory Innervation | Clinical Presentation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Median** | Thenar muscles (APB, OP, FPB superficial head), FDS, FPL, FDP (radial half) | Palmar aspect of thumb, index, middle, radial half of ring finger; dorsal tips of same digits | Thenar atrophy, 'ape hand' deformity, impaired pincer grasp, carpal tunnel syndrome |\n| **Ulnar** | Hypothenar muscles, interossei, adductor pollicis, FDP (ulnar half) | Palmar and dorsal aspects of little finger, ulnar half of ring finger | Hypothenar atrophy, 'claw hand' deformity, impaired grip strength, Froment's sign |\n| **Radial** | Extensors of wrist and fingers, supinator, brachioradialis | Dorsum of hand (radial side), dorsal thumb, index, middle finger (proximal) | Wrist drop, finger drop, impaired supination |\n| **Axillary** | Deltoid, teres minor | Lateral shoulder (regimental badge area) | Deltoid weakness, impaired shoulder abduction |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Thenar atrophy + intact thenar sensation = median nerve compression *at* the carpal tunnel.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, median nerve swelling and flattening at the carpal tunnel inlet are common findings. Intraoperatively, during carpal tunnel release, the transverse carpal ligament is divided, and the median nerve is visualized. The palmar cutaneous branch is typically seen superficial to the ligament, confirming its sparing in classic carpal tunnel syndrome.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis of Carpal Tunnel Syndrome (2016). It recommends electrodiagnostic studies for confirmation and surgical release for severe or refractory cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Radial | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Median | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Axillary | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ulnar | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Answer is: B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
