  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Chest pain post-op: Heart first, then lungs next!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer emphasizes the critical initial step in evaluating post-operative chest pain. While pulmonary embolism (PE) is a significant concern after surgery, myocardial infarction (MI) must always be ruled out first, making an ECG the most appropriate initial diagnostic test.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPost-operative chest pain demands a systematic approach to rule out life-threatening conditions. An ECG is a rapid, non-invasive, and essential tool for diagnosing or excluding acute coronary syndromes (ACS), which can manifest as chest pain. If the ECG is normal and cardiac enzymes are not elevated, then the focus shifts to other differentials like pulmonary embolism, for which a CT angiogram (CT angio) would be the next logical step, as indicated by the answer key.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (US) (Incorrect): Abdominal ultrasound is irrelevant for the evaluation of chest pain. While a cardiac ultrasound (echocardiogram) might be considered later, it is not the initial diagnostic test for acute chest pain.\nOption B (Catheterization) (Incorrect): Cardiac catheterization is an invasive procedure used to diagnose and treat coronary artery disease. It is not the initial diagnostic step for chest pain; an ECG is performed first to assess for acute myocardial ischemia or infarction.\nOption C (CT angio) (Incorrect as initial step): CT angiography is the gold standard for diagnosing pulmonary embolism. While PE is a strong differential in a post-operative patient with chest pain, cardiac causes (MI) must be excluded first with an ECG before proceeding to imaging for PE.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Initial Workup for Acute Chest Pain | Key Findings | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| **ECG** | ST elevation/depression, T wave inversion, new LBBB | Rapidly identifies acute myocardial ischemia/infarction |\n| **Cardiac Troponins** | Elevated levels | Confirms myocardial injury, though takes time for elevation |\n| **Chest X-ray (CXR)** | Pneumonia, atelectasis, pneumothorax, pleural effusion | Screens for pulmonary causes, often done with ECG |\n| **CT Angiogram (CTA Chest)** | Filling defects in pulmonary arteries | Confirms pulmonary embolism, performed after cardiac causes are less likely |\n| **Echocardiogram** | Wall motion abnormalities, valvular disease, pericardial effusion | Assesses cardiac function and structure, often after initial workup |\n| **D-dimer** | Elevated | Suggests thrombosis (PE/DVT), but non-specific; useful for ruling out PE in low-risk patients |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-op chest pain? ECG first, then consider PE with CT angio.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAn ECG would show characteristic changes for myocardial infarction (e.g., ST elevation). A CT Angiogram of the chest would reveal filling defects within the pulmonary arteries, indicative of a pulmonary embolism.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2021 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Evaluation and Diagnosis of Chest Pain: Recommends ECG as the initial diagnostic test for all patients presenting with chest pain to assess for acute coronary syndromes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Catheterization | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CT angio | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ECG, if not there > C) Answer is: ECG, if not there > C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
