  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't wait for descent; bring it down, or risk regret!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Orchidopexy. For a 5-year-old boy with a unilateral undescended testis, surgical correction via orchidopexy is the indicated management because spontaneous descent is highly unlikely after 6 months of age, and early intervention mitigates risks of infertility and malignancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOrchidopexy is the surgical procedure to bring an undescended testis into the scrotum and secure it. This involves mobilizing the testis, spermatic cord, and gubernaculum to achieve sufficient length for tension-free placement within a dartos pouch in the scrotum. The primary goals are to place the testis in a physiologically normal and palpable position, which facilitates easier examination for malignancy surveillance, improves spermatogenesis, and reduces the risk of torsion. While the optimal timing is between 6 and 18 months, it is still indicated at 5 years old as spontaneous descent is no longer expected.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Orchiectomy) (Incorrect): Orchiectomy, the removal of the testis, is not indicated for a unilateral undescended testis in a child, especially when the testis is viable. It is reserved for non-viable, severely atrophic, or dysgenetic testes.\nOption C (Wait until puberty) (Incorrect): Waiting until puberty is incorrect. Spontaneous descent rarely occurs after 6 months of age. Delaying surgery beyond 18 months significantly increases the risk of impaired fertility and malignant transformation.\nOption D (Androgen hormone) (Incorrect): Hormonal therapy (e.g., hCG) has limited efficacy (around 20% success rate) and is not the primary or preferred treatment for undescended testes, especially at 5 years of age. Surgical orchidopexy is the gold standard.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Management Option | Indication | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Orchidopexy | Undescended testis (after 6 months, ideally 6-18 months) | Prevents infertility, facilitates cancer surveillance, reduces torsion risk |\n| Observation | Palpable retractile testis | Testis descends spontaneously, no intervention needed |\n| Orchiectomy | Non-viable, severely dysgenetic, or atrophic testis | Prevents potential malignancy if dysgenetic, removes non-functional tissue |\n| Hormonal Therapy (hCG) | Rarely used, limited efficacy | May induce descent in some cases, but surgical success rates are higher |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Undescended testis after 6 months needs orchidopexy, not observation or hormones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the surgeon would identify the undescended testis, often located in the inguinal canal or abdomen, and mobilize its vascular supply and vas deferens to allow tension-free placement into the scrotum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Management of Cryptorchidism (2014, reaffirmed 2018). It recommends surgical intervention for cryptorchidism that persists beyond 6 months of age, ideally between 6 and 18 months.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Orchidopexy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Orchedectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Wait until puberty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Androgen hormone | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Answer is: A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
