  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gallbladder shrinks, think Klatskin's distinct clinical wink.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Klatskin tumor. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the classic triad of progressive jaundice, RUQ pain, and imaging showing dilated intrahepatic ducts with a shrunken gallbladder, which points to a proximal biliary obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nKlatskin tumors, or perihilar cholangiocarcinomas, arise at the bifurcation of the common hepatic duct. Their location causes obstruction of the intrahepatic biliary tree, leading to upstream dilation. The gallbladder typically remains shrunken or normal because the obstruction is proximal to the cystic duct insertion, preventing bile from reaching and distending the gallbladder. This specific imaging finding is a critical differentiator from more distal obstructions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Pancreatic cancer) (Incorrect): Pancreatic head cancer typically causes a distal CBD obstruction, leading to dilation of both intrahepatic and extrahepatic ducts, and often a distended gallbladder (Courvoisier's sign).\nOption C (CBD stones) (Incorrect): CBD stones can cause jaundice and dilated ducts, but the gallbladder is usually normal or distended, not shrunken, especially with progressive obstruction. Stones often present with episodic pain and cholangitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Klatskin Tumor | Pancreatic Head Cancer | CBD Stones |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Jaundice** | Progressive | Progressive | Often fluctuating/episodic |\n| **RUQ Pain** | Present | Variable | Often colicky, can be severe |\n| **Intrahepatic Ducts** | Dilated | Dilated | Dilated |\n| **Extrahepatic Ducts** | Normal/Mildly dilated (proximal) | Dilated (distal) | Dilated |\n| **Gallbladder** | Shrunken/Normal | Distended (Courvoisier's) | Normal/Distended |\n| **Obstruction Location** | Perihilar | Distal CBD | CBD |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Shrunken gallbladder + dilated intrahepatic ducts = Klatskin until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT/MRI, a Klatskin tumor appears as a focal stricture or mass at the hepatic confluence, causing marked intrahepatic biliary dilation with a normal or shrunken gallbladder. Intraoperatively, a firm, often infiltrative mass is seen at the hilum, encasing the hepatic ducts.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Hepatobiliary Cancers (2023). Recommends detailed imaging (MRI/MRCP) for diagnosis and staging of cholangiocarcinoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Klatskin tumor | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Pancreatic cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CBD stones | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Answer is: A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
