  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Extend yourself: Radial nerve rules the wrist!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Radial nerve. The clinical presentation of inability to extend the forearm, wrist, and fingers following a humerus fracture and ORIF is pathognomonic for radial nerve injury, often termed 'wrist drop'.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe radial nerve innervates the triceps brachii (forearm extension), the extensor carpi radialis longus and brevis, and extensor carpi ulnaris (wrist extension), and the extensor digitorum, indicis, and digiti minimi (finger extension). Its course around the spiral groove of the humerus makes it particularly vulnerable to injury in mid-shaft humerus fractures. Surgical intervention like ORIF can also risk iatrogenic injury to this nerve.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ulnar…): Incorrect. Ulnar nerve injury primarily affects intrinsic hand muscles, causing a 'claw hand' deformity and sensory loss to the medial 1.5 digits, not wrist or finger extension.\nOption C (Median…): Incorrect. Median nerve injury affects forearm pronation, wrist flexion, thumb opposition, and sensation to the lateral 3.5 digits, leading to an 'ape hand' deformity, not wrist drop.\nOption D (Median….): Incorrect. Similar to option C, median nerve injury does not cause the described extensor deficits. The mention of '2 branches of median nerve' in the question is a significant distractor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Key Motor Function | Classic Injury Sign | Common Injury Site |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Radial | Forearm, wrist, finger extension | Wrist drop | Mid-shaft humerus fracture, Saturday night palsy |\n| Median | Forearm pronation, thumb opposition, wrist flexion | Ape hand, inability to make 'OK' sign | Supracondylar humerus fracture, carpal tunnel syndrome |\n| Ulnar | Finger abduction/adduction, 4th/5th digit flexion | Claw hand | Medial epicondyle fracture, cubital tunnel syndrome |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Wrist drop = Radial nerve. Humerus fracture = Radial nerve risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs, a humerus fracture, especially in the mid-diaphysis, should immediately raise suspicion for potential radial nerve involvement. Intraoperatively, the radial nerve can be seen traversing the spiral groove of the humerus, making it susceptible to direct trauma during fracture reduction or fixation with plates and screws.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAAOS Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Humerus Fractures (2019) recommends careful neurological assessment pre- and post-operatively for radial nerve function.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ulnar … | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Radial … | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Median … | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Median …. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Answer is: B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
