  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't radiate the baby, ultrasound the booby!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Bilateral US. In a pregnant patient presenting with a new breast mass, ultrasound is the preferred initial imaging modality due to its safety profile for the fetus and its effectiveness in characterizing breast lesions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUltrasound is highly effective in differentiating cystic from solid lesions, which is crucial in the initial workup of a breast mass. It provides real-time imaging, allows for targeted evaluation of the palpable mass, and can guide subsequent biopsy if indicated, all without exposing the fetus to ionizing radiation. The increased breast density and glandular tissue during pregnancy can also make mammography less sensitive, further favoring ultrasound as the primary diagnostic tool.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Bilateral mammogram) (Incorrect): Mammography involves ionizing radiation, which should be avoided or minimized during pregnancy due to potential fetal risks, even with shielding. It is not the first-line imaging in this population.\nOption C (Core biopsy) (Incorrect): Biopsy is an invasive procedure and is typically performed after initial imaging (like ultrasound) has characterized the mass and determined its suspicious nature. It is not the immediate next step without prior imaging.\nOption D (Follow up after delivery) (Incorrect): Any new breast mass, especially one that is firm and mobile, requires prompt evaluation regardless of pregnancy status. Delaying diagnosis until after delivery could lead to progression of a potentially malignant lesion, which is unacceptable.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Use in Pregnancy | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Ultrasound** | First-line | No radiation, differentiates solid/cystic, guides biopsy, effective in dense breasts | Operator dependent, limited view of entire breast |\n| **Mammography** | Second-line (with shielding) | Good for microcalcifications, overall breast architecture | Ionizing radiation, less sensitive in dense breasts of pregnancy |\n| **MRI** | Third-line (no contrast) | High sensitivity, good for extent of disease | Gadolinium contraindicated, expensive, limited availability |\n| **Biopsy** | After imaging | Definitive diagnosis | Invasive, not an imaging modality |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: New breast mass in pregnancy? US first, always.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn breast ultrasound, a suspicious mass might appear as an irregular, hypoechoic lesion with posterior acoustic shadowing, microlobulated margins, or non-parallel orientation. Benign lesions often appear well-circumscribed, oval, and hyperechoic or isoechoic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 210 (2019) recommends ultrasound as the initial imaging modality for a palpable breast mass in pregnant and lactating women.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bilateral mammogram | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bilateral US | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Core biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Follow up after delivery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Answer is: B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
