  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For axillary sensation, spare the intercostobrachial nerve.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is the Intercostobrachial nerve. Post-mastectomy paresthesia and numbness in the upper arm and axilla are classic symptoms of intercostobrachial nerve injury, a common iatrogenic complication during axillary dissection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuring axillary lymph node dissection, the intercostobrachial nerve, a purely sensory nerve, is highly susceptible to traction or transection injury due to its superficial course. This nerve typically arises from the second (and sometimes third) intercostal nerve, pierces the serratus anterior muscle, and provides sensory innervation to the skin of the axilla and the medial aspect of the upper arm. Its injury results in the characteristic sensory deficits described.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Long thoracic nerve) (Incorrect): Injury to the long thoracic nerve causes paralysis of the serratus anterior muscle, leading to a 'winged scapula,' not sensory deficits in the arm or axilla.\nOption B (Thoracodorsal nerve) (Incorrect): Injury to the thoracodorsal nerve causes paralysis of the latissimus dorsi muscle, resulting in weakness of arm adduction, extension, and internal rotation, not sensory loss.\nOption D (Medial pectoral nerve) (Incorrect): Injury to the medial pectoral nerve affects the pectoralis major and minor muscles, leading to weakness in arm adduction and internal rotation, not sensory deficits in the axilla or upper arm.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Function/Innervation | Injury Symptom |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Intercostobrachial Nerve | T2 (T3) intercostal nerve | Sensory to axilla & medial upper arm | Paresthesia/numbness in axilla/medial arm |\n| Long Thoracic Nerve | C5, C6, C7 | Motor to Serratus Anterior | Winged Scapula |\n| Thoracodorsal Nerve | C6, C7, C8 (posterior cord) | Motor to Latissimus Dorsi | Weakness in arm adduction/extension/internal rotation |\n| Medial Pectoral Nerve | C8, T1 (medial cord) | Motor to Pectoralis Major (sternocostal head) & Minor | Weakness in arm adduction/internal rotation, pectoral atrophy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Axillary numbness post-mastectomy = Intercostobrachial nerve.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the intercostobrachial nerve is often visualized crossing the axilla transversely, superficial to the axillary vein, making it a key structure to identify and potentially preserve or sacrifice depending on the extent of dissection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024): These guidelines emphasize meticulous surgical technique during axillary dissection to minimize complications, including nerve injury, while achieving oncologic goals.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Long thoracic nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thoracodorsal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Intercostobrachial nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Medial pectoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Answer is: C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
