  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For varicose veins, duplex ultrasound is the diagnostic MVP.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is US duplex. For patients presenting with bilateral varicose veins, duplex ultrasound is the gold standard investigation due to its ability to non-invasively assess venous anatomy, flow dynamics, and valvular competence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuplex ultrasound provides real-time, dynamic imaging of the venous system. It allows for precise mapping of the great saphenous vein (GSV), identification of incompetent valves, quantification of reflux duration and velocity, and assessment of vein diameter. This detailed information is crucial for planning appropriate interventions, distinguishing primary from secondary venous insufficiency, and ruling out deep vein thrombosis (DVT) or other underlying pathologies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CT venography) (Incorrect): CT venography involves radiation exposure and intravenous contrast, making it more invasive and less suitable for routine evaluation of superficial varicose veins. While useful for deep venous thrombosis or complex central venous anatomy, it is inferior to duplex ultrasound for assessing valvular reflux and dynamic flow in superficial venous disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Investigation | Primary Use | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **US Duplex** | Varicose veins, DVT, venous insufficiency | Non-invasive, no radiation, dynamic, assesses flow/reflux, detailed anatomy | Operator dependent, limited by obesity/bowel gas |\n| **CT Venography** | DVT, central venous obstruction, complex anatomy | Good for deep/central veins, 3D reconstruction | Radiation, contrast, less effective for reflux, expensive |\n| **Conventional Venography** | Historical gold standard, specific indications (e.g., malformations) | Detailed anatomical mapping | Invasive, radiation, contrast, pain, risk of DVT |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Duplex ultrasound is the gold standard for varicose veins.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn US duplex, you would observe dilated, tortuous great saphenous veins, incompetent valves with retrograde flow (reflux) during Valsalva maneuvers or distal compression/release, and potentially increased vein diameter.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Society for Vascular Surgery (SVS) and American Venous Forum (AVF) 2022 Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Chronic Venous Disease recommend duplex ultrasound as the primary diagnostic tool for evaluating chronic venous disease, including varicose veins.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT venography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | US duplex | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Answer is: B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
