  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Move it or lose it: early rehab conquers CRPS.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Physiotherapy is the cornerstone of management for Complex Regional Pain Syndrome (CRPS), particularly after a precipitating event like surgery, focusing on early mobilization, pain reduction, and functional restoration.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCRPS involves a complex interplay of neuropathic, inflammatory, and autonomic dysfunction. Physiotherapy, including graded motor imagery, desensitization techniques, and progressive exercise, aims to restore normal sensory processing, improve range of motion, and reduce pain, thereby preventing long-term disability. Early and intensive rehabilitation is crucial for optimal outcomes in CRPS.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Opioid) (Incorrect): Opioids are generally not recommended as first-line treatment for CRPS due to limited evidence of long-term efficacy, significant side effects, and the risk of dependence. They may be considered only for severe, refractory pain under strict supervision.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Management Strategy | Key Principles | Role in CRPS |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Physiotherapy** | Graded motor imagery, desensitization, progressive exercise, functional restoration | First-line, essential for pain reduction, functional recovery, and preventing chronicity. |\n| **Pharmacological** | NSAIDs, gabapentinoids, tricyclic antidepressants, bisphosphonates, corticosteroids | Adjunctive for pain control, neuropathic symptoms, or bone changes. |\n| **Interventional** | Sympathetic blocks, spinal cord stimulation, intrathecal drug delivery | Reserved for severe, refractory cases after conservative measures fail. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Physiotherapy is the primary, non-pharmacological pillar for CRPS management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging like X-rays or MRI may show secondary changes such as osteopenia or soft tissue edema in CRPS, but the diagnosis remains primarily clinical. There are no specific diagnostic imaging findings for CRPS.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Association for the Study of Pain (IASP) guidelines (2010, updated criteria 2012) recommend a multidisciplinary approach with physiotherapy as a cornerstone.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | physiotherapy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Opioid | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Answer is: A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
