  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Phyllodes: Size and grade dictate the surgical grade!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct approach to phyllodes tumors is highly dependent on their size and histological characteristics. Therefore, a definitive answer between wide local excision (WLE) and simple mastectomy cannot be given without more information, as the management strategy is individualized.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhyllodes tumors exist on a spectrum from benign to borderline to malignant, and their management is primarily surgical. The goal is complete excision with adequate tumor-free margins, typically 1 cm, to minimize local recurrence. For smaller, benign, or even some borderline tumors, a wide local excision with clear margins is often sufficient for breast conservation. However, for larger tumors, those with malignant features, or those where adequate margins cannot be achieved with WLE, more extensive surgery, including simple mastectomy, may be necessary to ensure complete removal and reduce recurrence risk.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (WLE - Incorrect): While WLE is the primary treatment for many phyllodes tumors, it may be insufficient for very large tumors, those with malignant features, or if adequate margins cannot be achieved, necessitating more extensive resection.\nOption B (simple mastectomy - Incorrect): Simple mastectomy is often overtreatment for smaller, benign, or even some borderline phyllodes tumors, where breast conservation with WLE and adequate margins is a viable and preferred option.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Benign/Small Borderline Phyllodes | Large Borderline/Malignant Phyllodes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Surgical Goal | WLE with 1 cm margin | WLE with 1-2 cm margin or Mastectomy |\n| Adjuvant Therapy | Usually none | Consider radiation for positive margins/large malignant |\n| Recurrence Risk | Low | Higher, especially with positive margins |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Phyllodes tumor management depends on size, grade, and margin status.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, phyllodes tumors often appear as well-circumscribed, lobulated masses, sometimes with cystic areas. Rapid growth is a key clinical feature. Intraoperatively, they can be large, firm, and on cut section, may exhibit a characteristic 'leaf-like' pattern due to stromal overgrowth.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (2023): Recommend surgical excision with clear margins (typically 1 cm) for phyllodes tumors, with consideration of mastectomy for large or recurrent tumors, or those with malignant features where breast conservation is not feasible.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | WLE | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | simple mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: Depends on the size) Answer is: Depends on the size** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
