  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 SVT + gastric varices = spleen's out, pressure's down!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nSplenectomy is the correct management for this patient. The presence of splenic vein thrombosis (SVT) with gastric varices, in the setting of a patent portal vein, indicates isolated left-sided portal hypertension, which is effectively treated by removing the spleen and the thrombosed vein.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatitis is a common cause of splenic vein thrombosis due to inflammation and compression of the splenic vein. When the splenic vein thromboses, blood flow from the spleen is obstructed, leading to increased pressure in the splenic venous system. This elevated pressure is transmitted to the short gastric veins, which drain into the fundus of the stomach, resulting in gastric varices (left-sided portal hypertension). Since the portal vein is patent, the problem is localized. Splenectomy removes the high-pressure system (spleen and thrombosed splenic vein), thereby decompressing the gastric varices and preventing further bleeding without affecting the main portal circulation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Portal-systemic shunt. A portal-systemic shunt is typically indicated for generalized portal hypertension (e.g., due to cirrhosis or portal vein thrombosis) to decompress the entire portal system. In this case, the portal vein is patent, and the pathology is isolated to the splenic vein, making a shunt unnecessary and potentially harmful.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Pathophysiology | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Splenic Vein Thrombosis (isolated, with gastric varices) | Localized obstruction of splenic vein, leading to left-sided portal hypertension and gastric varices. Portal vein patent. | Splenectomy |\n| Portal Vein Thrombosis (PVT) | Obstruction of the main portal vein, leading to generalized portal hypertension. | Anticoagulation, TIPS/shunt if refractory bleeding |\n| Generalized Portal Hypertension (e.g., cirrhosis) | Increased resistance to blood flow in the liver, leading to elevated pressure in the entire portal system. | Endoscopic therapy (banding/sclerotherapy), beta-blockers, TIPS/shunt for refractory cases |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Isolated splenic vein thrombosis + gastric varices = splenectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound would show absent flow or thrombus within the splenic vein, with normal flow in the portal vein. Endoscopy reveals gastric fundal varices. Intraoperatively, one would observe an enlarged spleen and dilated, tortuous short gastric veins.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) (2021) guidelines on portal hypertension, while not specific to isolated SVT, advocate for managing the source of elevated portal pressure.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Splenectomy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Portal-systemic shunt | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Answer is: A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
