  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just reassure; excise benign phyllodes with a wide margin!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is wide local excision because benign phyllodes tumours require complete surgical removal with clear margins to prevent local recurrence. This approach effectively treats the lesion while preserving breast tissue.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhyllodes tumours, even benign ones, have a propensity for local recurrence if not adequately excised. Wide local excision aims to remove the tumour with a margin of normal breast tissue (typically 1 cm or more) to ensure clear margins. This surgical strategy is curative for benign lesions and avoids the morbidity of more extensive procedures while minimizing recurrence risk.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Wide local excision with radio) (Incorrect): Adjuvant radiotherapy is generally reserved for borderline or malignant phyllodes tumours, especially those with positive or close margins, or large size, to reduce local recurrence risk. It is not indicated for benign lesions.\nOption C (Mastectomy) (Incorrect): Mastectomy is an overtreatment for benign phyllodes tumours. It is typically reserved for very large or recurrent malignant phyllodes tumours, or when clear margins cannot be achieved with breast-conserving surgery.\nOption D (Reassurance) (Incorrect): Phyllodes tumours, even benign ones, are true neoplasms with growth potential and a risk of local recurrence if untreated. Reassurance alone is inappropriate as surgical excision is the standard of care.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Benign Phyllodes | Borderline Phyllodes | Malignant Phyllodes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Stroma** | Mild atypia, low mitotic activity | Moderate atypia, increased mitotic activity | Marked atypia, high mitotic activity, stromal overgrowth |\n| **Margins** | Pushing | Infiltrative | Infiltrative |\n| **Management** | Wide local excision (1cm margin) | Wide local excision (1-2cm margin), consider XRT if positive/close margins | Wide local excision (2cm margin) or mastectomy, consider XRT, rarely chemo |\n| **Metastasis** | Rare | Rare | ~20% (hematogenous) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Benign phyllodes need wide local excision with clear margins, not radiation or mastectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a phyllodes tumour often appears as a well-circumscribed, lobulated, heterogeneous mass with cystic spaces. Intraoperatively, it is typically a firm, well-defined, often glistening mass that can be easily separated from surrounding tissue, though larger lesions may have an infiltrative appearance.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer (e.g., 2023) recommend wide local excision with clear margins for phyllodes tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Wide local excision | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Wide local excision with radio | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Reassurance | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 494863076-Penguins-Surgery-August-Septumber.pdf**\n",
